city.name: London
city.about:
London, a city where history and modernity effortlessly intertwine, offers an unforgettable experience for every traveler. As the capital of England, it stands as a global hub of culture, art, commerce, and innovation. From the majestic Thames River to the iconic silhouette of Big Ben and the historic Tower Bridge, London’s landmarks echo tales of a bygone era while paving the way for contemporary urban developments. Visitors can explore centuries-old palaces and world-class museums, all nestled within an expansive network of vibrant neighborhoods that celebrate diversity and creativity.

Steeped in rich heritage yet always evolving, London is a melting pot of traditions, ideas, and cuisines. Its bustling markets, stylish boutiques, and cutting-edge art galleries perfectly encapsulate the city’s dynamic spirit. Whether you’re wandering through the tranquil paths of its many parks or soaking in the pulsating nightlife, London offers endless opportunities to immerse yourself in its multifaceted charm. This guidebook introduction invites you to uncover hidden gems and famous landmarks alike, promising an adventure that captures the very essence of one of the world’s most influential cities.

points_of_interest.name: The Devonshire Arms
points_of_interest.description: The Dev The dress code is strictly alternative and the pub has got a late night license for Fridays and Saturdays. DJs every night and some gigs. The artwork on the walls was produced by Robin, the barman.

points_of_interest.name: The Camden Road Draft House
points_of_interest.description: Camden Road Arms Victorian Boozer

points_of_interest.name: The Dublin Castle
points_of_interest.description: A bit rowdy and often quite packed, this pub and music venue has played a pivotal role in British music. It is well known for producing the 1980s band Madness and helping a great many other groups along their path to glory. Worth a stop, just for the atmosphere.

points_of_interest.name: The Edinboro Castle
points_of_interest.description: A more refined side of Camden, this pub is part of a chain in North London attempting to apply a little class. It has a fine selection of beer and cider, including a selection of Belgian beers both bottled and draught. The food is always good and the staff always friendly. There is a large, semi-covered outdoor seating area with heaters.

points_of_interest.name: The Good Mixer
points_of_interest.description: A nice pub where the likes of Blur and Pulp and a load of other Britpop bands from the 1990s used to drink. Prices are reasonable, there are two pool tables, and the general atmosphere is laid back and friendly.

points_of_interest.name: Hawley Arms
points_of_interest.description: Tucked away in a side street close to the Stables Market, this two-story pub has a small garden and a roof terrace. There are sometimes concerts upstairs. A favorite of the late Amy Winehouse.

points_of_interest.name: Jazz Café
points_of_interest.description: Food, drink, and music (jazz, soul, blues). Every Saturday the place turns into a great 1980s music club, with "I love the 80s".

points_of_interest.name: The Alexandra
points_of_interest.description: Large pub with a wine bar next to the main pub called Smart Alex. Food served. Roof terrace with bar.

points_of_interest.name: All Bar One
points_of_interest.description: Food served.

points_of_interest.name: Waitrose's Wine Bar
points_of_interest.description: Pleasant and good-value place to sit and sip, though it closes when Waitrose around 9PM.
points_of_interest.address: 1 Wharf Road, Camden, London, N1C 4BZ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The World's End
points_of_interest.description: Local landmark and a good meeting point. It is large, with two separate bars and a lot of seating. Food is served at the weekend.
points_of_interest.address: 174 Camden High St, Camden Town, NW1 0NE

points_of_interest.name: Beach Blanket Babylon
points_of_interest.description: Beautiful bar with fantastical decor. Quality and service at the restaurant seem to vary wildly, but the bar is usually a safe bet.

points_of_interest.name: Bertie's Bar
points_of_interest.description: A wine bar below the Prince of Wales Pub. Seating outside. Food served.

points_of_interest.name: The Lion And Unicorn
points_of_interest.description: Pub with a Theatre

points_of_interest.name: The Cow
points_of_interest.description: A small and trendy pub/bar with a focus on Guinness.

points_of_interest.name: Crooked Billet
points_of_interest.description: A Youngs pub, food served.

points_of_interest.name: The Goose
points_of_interest.description: Updated Victorian gin palace. Popular with commuters.

points_of_interest.name: Neighbour
points_of_interest.description: with Jukes Basement Bar: previously the Kentish Town police cells

points_of_interest.name: The Electric Brasserie
points_of_interest.description: Attached to the Electric Cinema this trendy brasserie is a good place for a drink before or after your movie. Very busy F Sa evenings especially.

points_of_interest.name: The Bedford
points_of_interest.description: Famed for the comedy and live music in the large galleried back room

points_of_interest.name: Dog & Fox
points_of_interest.description: Large pub in the centre of the Wimbledon village. Food served, lots of seating outside.

points_of_interest.name: Admiral Vernon
points_of_interest.description: Great trad pub with live music at weekends.

points_of_interest.name: The Oxford Tavern
points_of_interest.description: Gastropub

points_of_interest.name: Adventure bar
points_of_interest.description: Cocktail bar with daily happy hour.

points_of_interest.name: The Fox & Grapes
points_of_interest.description: Food served.

points_of_interest.name: Trailer Happiness
points_of_interest.description: Intimate and kitsch lounge bar, den and kitchen with the feel of a low rent, mid-1960s Los Angeles valley bachelor pad.

points_of_interest.name: Kilkenny Tavern
points_of_interest.address: 131 Merton High St, South Wimbledon, SW19 1DE

points_of_interest.name: The Bear
points_of_interest.description: More a beer expedition than a pub.

points_of_interest.name: O'Neill's
points_of_interest.description: Food served.

points_of_interest.name: The Islington Town House
points_of_interest.description: Round Midnight Jazz and blues bar.

points_of_interest.name: The Euston Tap
points_of_interest.description: in a classical Victorian Gatehouse

points_of_interest.name: Bridge House
points_of_interest.description: A beautiful white pub with a theatre inside

points_of_interest.name: The Stonhouse
points_of_interest.description: gastropub with garden.

points_of_interest.name: Rose and Crown
points_of_interest.description: Food served, seating outside.

points_of_interest.name: 69 Colebrook Row
points_of_interest.description: The Bar With No Name Exceptional seasonal cocktails in a quiet, intimate setting from famous mixologist Tony Conigliaro. You'll need to book ahead. Their barrel-aged Negronis are particularly good.

points_of_interest.name: The Prince Arthur
points_of_interest.description: A nice pub away close to Euston station.

points_of_interest.name: Suburban Bar and Lounge
points_of_interest.description: Cocktail bar for chavs, run by chavs!
points_of_interest.hours: Tu–Th 5–11PM, F Sa 5PM–midnight, closed Su M

points_of_interest.name: The Flask
points_of_interest.description: The name dates from the 18th and 19th centuries, when Hampstead was known as an area with many freshwater springs and people went there to ''take the waters''. The current building has been a pub since 1874. Two bar rooms and a separate dining area.
points_of_interest.hours: Bar hours: M-Sa noon-11PM, Su noon-10:30PM

points_of_interest.name: Kings Head
points_of_interest.description: Wood panelled Victorian Pub

points_of_interest.name: The Bricklayers Arms
points_of_interest.description: Rated 3rd best pub in England 2012 by National Geographic. Traditional style pub with an eclectic clientele, well-kept beers, no TV, and no food.

points_of_interest.name: The Duke Of Edinburgh
points_of_interest.description: Only really worth going if the weather is sunny, as the pub itself is nothing to write home about. Step out through the back and you will find a massive beer garden, and the only thing waking you to the reality that you are still in Brixton is the trains that clatter by every 15 minutes or so.

points_of_interest.name: The Sultan
points_of_interest.description: Decent local pub serving very good real ale. The only pub in London owned by the Hopback Brewery. Walled garden. Bar food served. BBQ on Sundays weather permitting. "No loud music/TV policy" for those who want a quiet pint.
points_of_interest.hours: M–Th 3–11PM, F Sa noon–midnight, Su noon–11PM

points_of_interest.name: The Archway Tavern
points_of_interest.description: Pub with a reputed republican history. Live music some nights.

points_of_interest.name: The Rocket
points_of_interest.address: 120 Euston Rd, Somers Town, London NW1 2AL

points_of_interest.name: The Holly Bush
points_of_interest.description: It has been around since 1807 and is an absolute traditional favourite. Two bar rooms with open fireplaces. Consistently rated as one of the best traditional pubs in the whole of London.
points_of_interest.hours: Bar hours: M-Sa noon-11PM, Su noon-10:30PM

points_of_interest.name: The Mad Bishop & Bear
points_of_interest.description: A surprisingly good pub. It is a Fuller's pub, serving well-kept real ales. It is in the CAMRA Good Beer Guide. Breakfast is served from opening (M-F 9AM, Sa 7:30AM, Su 10AM) until noon, standard pub food is served at other times.

points_of_interest.name: The Coat & Badge
points_of_interest.description: The old-world outward appearance of this Youngs pub (established 1715) belies an interior that is distinctly modern. This Putney pub packs in a sizeable crowd of trendy locals, keen to enjoy the attentive service, good pub grub and a wide choice of wines and beers.

points_of_interest.name: The Effra Hall Tavern
points_of_interest.description: A winning combination of great Guinness, a friendly mixed crowd and superb live jazz on weekdays and Sundays.

points_of_interest.name: The Prince of Wales
points_of_interest.description: Serves food, owned by Punch Taverns.

points_of_interest.name: The Landseer Arms
points_of_interest.description: Smart pub with posh food. Fairly lively. Nice hanging plants.

points_of_interest.name: The Blues Kitchen
points_of_interest.hours: M–W noon–midnight, Th noon–1AM, F noon–2AM, Sa 10AM–2AM, Su 10AM–midnight

points_of_interest.name: The King William IV
points_of_interest.description: London's oldest established gay pub and a pleasant place for a drink whether you are gay or straight. Three bar rooms and a pleasant, if small, outdoor beer garden at the rear. Right in the heart of Hampstead village.

points_of_interest.name: Ordnance Arms
points_of_interest.description: Samuel Smith's

points_of_interest.name: Duke's Head
points_of_interest.description: A lovely gastropub with great views on and along the river. A regular for locals.
points_of_interest.address: The Dukes Head, 8 Lower Richmond Rd, SW15 1JN

points_of_interest.name: The Grovenor Arms
points_of_interest.description: Fabulous old school boozer with two bars and a pool table. There is large function room at the back with a growing reputation for putting on interesting rock, reggae and punk acts.

points_of_interest.name: The Terrace
points_of_interest.description: Terrace overlooking central Wimbledon. Serves food.
points_of_interest.address: Above Centre Court Shopping Centre, Queens Rd

points_of_interest.name: Scala
points_of_interest.description: Former cinema which was used in WWII to manufacture weapons and then faced a piracy lawsuit after screening ''A Clockwork Orange'' after Stanley Kubrick famously banned it. Now an alternative music venue.

points_of_interest.name: The Old Bull and Bush
points_of_interest.description: This former farmhouse gained its first licence to sell liquor in 1721 and is the pub that gave rise to famous Victorian music hall song "Down at The Old Bull and Bush". Today it is a thriving pub and one which has modernised sympathetically. A great place to go for a drink and imagine the characters who have done likewise here over the past nearly 300 years.

points_of_interest.name: Cork and Bottle Wine Bar
points_of_interest.description: More of a wine bar than a restaurant, the extensive wine list features selections from Australia and California. They offer reasonable cuisine to wash down this full bodied wines.

points_of_interest.name: The Prince Alfred
points_of_interest.description: Lavishly decorated Victorian pub near Lord's cricket ground.
points_of_interest.hours: Daily Su-Th noon-11PM, F Sa noon-midnight

points_of_interest.name: The Rocket
points_of_interest.description: fancy-dan Wetherspoons

points_of_interest.name: Hootananny Brixton
points_of_interest.description: Popular late licence pub with a penchant for live ska music. Incredibly popular on weekends with upbeat fun atmosphere and large outdoor area. Also hosts El Panzon Mexican kitchen for delicious cheap food.

points_of_interest.name: The Wibbas Down Inn
points_of_interest.description: J D Wetherspoon Food served. Some seating outside - now nearly completely taken up by smokers. Always has a wide and well-kept selection of real ales.

points_of_interest.name: The Charlotte Despard
points_of_interest.description: A relaxed and friendly place, with a nice and eclectic clientele.

points_of_interest.name: The Spaniard's Inn
points_of_interest.description: Been around since 1585 and has just claims to be one of the most famous pubs in London. Keats, Shelly and Byron all drank here and Dickens mentions it in Pickwick Papers. Local lore has it that Dick Turpin used the pub and that his ghost still does. These days it is a decent pub with a real countryside atmosphere.

points_of_interest.name: De Hems Dutch Cafe Bar
points_of_interest.description: Dutch-themed pub with an excellent selection of beers. It is often crowded, but has a good atmosphere and a comedy club.

points_of_interest.name: The Swan
points_of_interest.description: A Fuller's 18th century coaching inn.

points_of_interest.name: The Spotted Horse
points_of_interest.description: Described as the oldest pub on the high street, a refurb has made this local the new kid on the block. Thankfully, the local charm and hospitality remains.

points_of_interest.name: The Marquis of Lorne
points_of_interest.description: Sporting an immaculate and beautifully preserved exterior, this quiet pub deserves to be much better known.

points_of_interest.name: The Twelve Pins
points_of_interest.description: Irish pub which gets very busy on Arsenal match days.
points_of_interest.hours: M–Th 3PM–midnight, F Sa noon–1AM, Su noon–midnight

points_of_interest.name: Electric Ballroom
points_of_interest.description: A historic ballroom turned contemporary rock music venue. As a former dancefloor, the audience stands on a flat surface so it may be difficult to see the stage further back. The Ballroom hosts several different club nights. It is a big venue with two separate dance floors and four bars. Features a rock floor, as well as a floor for the industrial/goth/rock/techno genres.

points_of_interest.name: O'Neill's
points_of_interest.description: Irish chain bar lost in the heart of Chinatown. Three levels with a houseband on busier nights, who always seem to play the same U2 and Kings of Leon songs.

points_of_interest.name: The Union Tavern
points_of_interest.description: with a terrace overlooking the Union Canal

points_of_interest.name: The Selkirk
points_of_interest.description: formerly The Frog Forget Me Not Pub with a big beer garden, dog friendly, and serves food.

points_of_interest.name: Prince Albert
points_of_interest.description: Green King A local favourite that still stubbornly remains a simple pub, without succumbing to standard London bar makeover. Good atmosphere with plenty of places to sit down inside plus a tiny outside beer garden, which is nice in the summer.

points_of_interest.name: The Faultering Fullback
points_of_interest.description: Beautiful pub, popular with locals watching football and eating their Thai Food. Since the smoking ban, a lot of money has been spent on the beer garden at the rear, which now offers a wooden mezzanine floor.

points_of_interest.name: The Underworld
points_of_interest.description: It is a great spot to go and catch alternative bands: goth, metal, electronica, rock, punk and many others are found here. Friday nights are also regular club nights, attracting large numbers from the young alternative crowd and more "studenty" than on Saturdays.

points_of_interest.name: The Lansdowne
points_of_interest.description: Local favourite with a lively bar downstairs and excellent restaurant on the first floor.

points_of_interest.name: Waxy O'Connor's
points_of_interest.description: Irish-themed pub with a fibreglass tree inside it and a pulpit. It is almost invariably unbearably crowded.

points_of_interest.name: The Victoria
points_of_interest.description: Fullers

points_of_interest.name: The Prince of Wales
points_of_interest.description: POW Brxtn The downstairs pub has a late licence while the exquisitely restored upstairs ''POW'' is a members only affair and well worth a visit. There is also a ''boutique'' hotel on the top floor. In the boozer, there's free wi-fi with any bar purchase, making it a good place for daytime meetings.

points_of_interest.name: T-Bird Bar
points_of_interest.description: Open mic night on Thursdays and a free jukebox on Mondays.
points_of_interest.hours: Tu–Th 5PM–midnight, F Sa 5PM–1AM, closed Su M

points_of_interest.name: KOKO
points_of_interest.description: Grade II listed music venue with restaurant. Card only.

points_of_interest.name: The Pembroke Castle
points_of_interest.description: Intimate pub with a cozy inside bar and a very popular beer garden which gets packed in summer.

points_of_interest.name: Waxy's Little Sister
points_of_interest.description: is generally quieter and more relaxed. Check out the upstairs bar that allows ordering via the silent waiter.

points_of_interest.name: The Aeronaut
points_of_interest.description: Styled as a 'Pub, Brewery and Circus', the Aeronaut has been turning the Acton pub experience upside down. It was rated "London's Best Pub" by Design My Night Awards in 2018. This theme pub is inspired by Acton-born turn-of-the-century pilot, George Lee Temple (the first Englishman to fly an aeroplane upside down). Features its own micro-brewery and a program of cabaret acrobats and circus performers.
points_of_interest.hours: M-W noon-midnight, Th-Su noon-1AM, F Sa noon-1:30AM

points_of_interest.name: The Riverside
points_of_interest.description: Gastropub on the Thames Pathway near Vauxhall Bridge. Serves a wide range of food and drink, including Pimms on tap at the bar.

points_of_interest.name: The Coronet
points_of_interest.description: A large and unusually nice Wetherspoons pub with a wide range of cheap drinks, including guest ales, and reasonably price food. Does tend to get busy on Arsenal home matchdays.

points_of_interest.name: The Princess of Wales
points_of_interest.description: Traditional pub which offers a fine selection of beers and has a relatively broad food menu. Traditional jazz is played on Thursday nights. One of the more reasonably priced pubs in the area.

points_of_interest.name: Ruby Blue
points_of_interest.description: Smart themed rooms and a balcony overlooking Leicester Square

points_of_interest.name: The Drayton Court Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Homely old fashioned pub.

points_of_interest.name: Trinity Arms
points_of_interest.description: Young's A proper old man's pub with a picture of the Queen pulling a pint on the wall. Right in the middle of the bustle of Brixton near the tube station, but tucked around a corner on Trinity Gardens that feels like it's in a different part of London altogether. Beer garden in front and back, excellent food as well. They do a Sunday roast that shouldn't be missed if you're in Brixton that evening.

points_of_interest.name: Big Red
points_of_interest.description: A biker-themed pub with several pool tables and live music some nights. Normally quite busy on Friday and Saturday evenings.

points_of_interest.name: The Sir Richard Steele
points_of_interest.description: Old fashioned London pub which runs a regular program of themed nights including some quite eclectic musical themes. Saturday is comedy night and especially popular. Named after the notable Georgian journalist and writer whose home was on this site.

points_of_interest.name: The Haven Arms
points_of_interest.description: Homely old fashioned pub.

points_of_interest.name: The Coach & Horses
points_of_interest.description: A pub for a traditional London sing-song around the Joanna every Saturday night.

points_of_interest.name: Windmill Brixton
points_of_interest.description: A bit of a trek from the Brixton tube (about 15 minutes walk), but it's a gem worth discovering. This small pub regularly hosts live music from up and coming bands, in the past seeing Bloc Party before they hit big time thanks to promoter Tim Perry's meticulous quality filter. Sunday nights they have DJs and BBQs during the summer.

points_of_interest.name: Southampton Arms
points_of_interest.address: 139 Highgate Rd, Kentish Town, London NW5 1LE

points_of_interest.name: The North Star
points_of_interest.description: Slightly more upmarket and stocks a wide variety of draught beers.

points_of_interest.name: Vagabond Fulham
points_of_interest.description: Wine bar

points_of_interest.name: The Crown and 2 Chairmen
points_of_interest.description: Has had a fancy refit and has a good selection of beers. You may have to wait a little while for your drink however. Popular with local media industry crowd.

points_of_interest.name: Dogstar
points_of_interest.description: One of Brixton's long time favourites and worth a visit for a night out. It still runs an eclectic mix of dance music, covering hip-hop, reggae, r&b, ska and house. Has dance floor, big old sofas and screen for sports matches. Upstairs there is Moca (Caribbean restaurant) and a third floor to hire out for private parties.
points_of_interest.hours: M–Th 4PM–midnight, F 4PM–1AM, Sa noon–1AM, Su noon–11PM

points_of_interest.name: Ye Olde Swiss Cottage
points_of_interest.description: Swiss chalet-style pub that gave its name to the tube station.

points_of_interest.name: The Moon on the Square
points_of_interest.description: A Wetherspoon's chain pub.

points_of_interest.name: The French House
points_of_interest.description: The legendary pub in which the French resistance convened during World War II and which was the favoured haunt of legendary Soho characters such as Francis Bacon and Lucian Freud. It is a very small pub, so expect to be jammed in, particularly in winter. The pub only serves beer in half-pints. An absolute Soho institution. Think "Jeffrey Bernard is unwell".

points_of_interest.name: Fire Nightclub
points_of_interest.description: Located in the train arches of Vauxhall are three inter-linked clubs (with separate events and queues): '''Fire''', '''Lightbox''' and '''Protocol'''. The music and crowds range from velvety commercial house for shirtless, partying-till-midday gay audiences to underground techno, South London grime and even Canto and K-Pop nights for the East Asian community.

points_of_interest.name: Magpie and Crown
points_of_interest.description: Offers a fine selection of real ales and imported beer (including fruit beer on draught).

points_of_interest.name: The Dove
points_of_interest.description: This pretty 17th-century riverside establishment may have London's smallest bar (room just to the right of the entrance), as well as an outside seating area with river views. The famous Doves Press was named after this pub.

points_of_interest.name: Glassblower
points_of_interest.description: Green King Pub

points_of_interest.name: Hideaway
points_of_interest.description: Streatham jazz club. Voted the best jazz venue of 2011 by the House of Commons' cross-party Parliamentary Jazz Club.

points_of_interest.name: Old Firestation
points_of_interest.description: Appeals to a younger, more affluent crowd with its contemporary 'bar' vibe and award-winning cocktails.

points_of_interest.name: The Volunteer
points_of_interest.description: A great pub for a relaxed evening. Great atmosphere and a minute walk from Baker Street Tube.

points_of_interest.name: Shakespeares Head
points_of_interest.description: A Green King Pub with

points_of_interest.name: The Yacht
points_of_interest.description: Greene King pub with riverside views from windows. Does food and can be quieter (and friendlier) than the Trafalgar.

points_of_interest.name: White Horse Brixton
points_of_interest.description: Typical London pub with outdoor area and pool table. Serves food. DJs usually play Funk music on the dance floor (although you should expect it to be crowded late on F and Sa).

points_of_interest.name: The Weir Bar
points_of_interest.description: Offers waterside ''al fresco'' drinking in its attractive beer garden.
points_of_interest.hours: Tu W 5PM–midnight, Th-Sa noon–midnight, Su noon–10:30PM, closed M

points_of_interest.name: The Blue Boat
points_of_interest.description: Fuller, Smith and Turner. A modern pub under a tower block

points_of_interest.name: The Windsor Castle Pub
points_of_interest.description: A local pub popular with the London Business School crowd.

points_of_interest.name: The Tottenham
points_of_interest.description: Flying Horse Refurbished pub claiming to be the only pub on the whole of Oxford St. An absolute tourist trap but it is very convenient.

points_of_interest.name: The Trafalgar Tavern
points_of_interest.description: Greenwich Inc-owned. Beautiful old pub but overcrowded. The bar is over bright and sitting outside has become less pleasant since they lined loads of benches up along the river path. Service can also be brusque.

points_of_interest.name: The Railway Tavern
points_of_interest.description: Renovated.
points_of_interest.hours: Su–W noon–11PM, Th noon–midnight, F Sa noon–1AM

points_of_interest.name: Brewery Tap
points_of_interest.description: A tiny two-room pub offering traditional food, live jazz and a highly quirky clientele to those with a desire to discover something of Brentford's true character.

points_of_interest.name: Rutland Arms
points_of_interest.description: Panelled Green King

points_of_interest.name: The Toucan
points_of_interest.description: Widely mistaken for an Irish bar it actually specializes in Guinness, said to be the best pint in London. Also check out their collection of over 100 different Irish whiskies.

points_of_interest.name: The Sail Loft
points_of_interest.description: Pub run by Fuller's on the riverside with decent but limited outdoor seating. In the summer, the doors are opened up so that the entire bar feels like you're drinking by the river.

points_of_interest.name: Royal Vauxhall Tavern
points_of_interest.description: Home to a constant assortment of strange, bawdy, underground, queer and quirky nights from artists, comedians and performers.

points_of_interest.name: The Salisbury Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Huge ornate early Edwardian pub (despite the misleading name). Worth a visit just to look but plenty going on including music and period jazz dancing.
points_of_interest.address: 1 Grand Parade, Green Lanes, Harringay Ladder, N4 1JX
points_of_interest.hours: M–Th 5–11PM, Sa noon–midnight, Su noon–10PM, closed F

points_of_interest.name: Draft House
points_of_interest.description: Duke of Hammersmith
points_of_interest.address: 238 Shepherd's Bush Rd, Hammersmith, London W6 7NL

points_of_interest.name: The Angel in the Fields
points_of_interest.description: Visit on a sunny afternoon to enjoy the stained glass windows.

points_of_interest.name: The Oystercatcher
points_of_interest.description: Youngs pub on the riverside west of Greenwich town centre. Serves brunch, lunch, dinner and drinks and everything in between.

points_of_interest.name: The Sir Colin Campbell
points_of_interest.description: Small, friendly Irish pub with good traditional music sessions on Friday nights.
points_of_interest.hours: M 4–11PM, Tu–Th 4PM–midnight, F 1PM–1AM, Sa noon–1AM, Su noon–12:30AM

points_of_interest.name: Betsey Trotwood
points_of_interest.description: Live music in the cellar every Friday. Venue is like a very small dungeon, but they know what is good music.

points_of_interest.name: The Hawk's Nest
points_of_interest.address: Goldhawk Rd, Shepherd's Bush Market, Shepherd's Bush, London W12 8DF

points_of_interest.name: The Black Lion Guesthouse Bar Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Nice gastropub/restaurant.
points_of_interest.hours: M–Th 3PM–midnight, F Sa noon–1AM, Su noon–midnight

points_of_interest.name: The Craft Beer Company
points_of_interest.description: One of RateBeer's Top 50 bars in the world, and only one of two in the UK (see CASK Pub & Kitchen in Pimlico for the other). Famous for its vast selection beers: cask, keg and bottle.

points_of_interest.name: Coach & Horses
points_of_interest.description: Mock Tudor Pub

points_of_interest.name: The John Snow
points_of_interest.description: Named after a doctor who traced the origin of a cholera outbreak in the area in 1849, and removed the handle of a water pump on Broad Street to prevent it from spreading further. Dr John Snow is today widely remembered as the father of epidemiology.

points_of_interest.name: The Coach and Horses
points_of_interest.description: Young's pub with covered seated area in Greenwich Market - let the shoppers shop while you sup! Does food as well as the usual Young's ales, etc.

points_of_interest.name: The North London Tavern
points_of_interest.description: Popular bar/restaurant. Not quite as good as the Black Lion.

points_of_interest.name: Crown Tavern
points_of_interest.description: A large, traditional pub, rebuilt in 1815 but claiming a history on this site back to 1641. In good weather, outdoor tables in the square can be pleasant. London legend claims that Stalin and Lenin first met in this pub, in a back room (under the "Conspirators' Clock") in 1903.

points_of_interest.name: The Gipsy Moth
points_of_interest.description: Historic Grade I listed pub right next to the Cutty Sark. Big outdoor seating area but the pub is too often filled with tourists.

points_of_interest.name: The Dovetail
points_of_interest.description: Small Belgian bar serving Belgian beer and Belgian food.

points_of_interest.name: The Plough & Harrow
points_of_interest.description: Wetherspoons

points_of_interest.name: Ronnie Scott's Jazz Club
points_of_interest.description: Ronnie Scott's world-famous jazz venue. Most performances get booked up quickly: you need to reserve space on a table for dinner. Upstairs, there is a bar ("Ronnie's Bar") with more of a club-like environment.
points_of_interest.hours: M-Sa 8:30PM-3AM including Bank Holidays (closed 24-26 Dec); live music 9:45PM-2AM

points_of_interest.name: Biddle Bros
points_of_interest.description: Lively pub with a good local following. Often have a live band or DJ in the evenings,.

points_of_interest.name: Greenwich Tavern
points_of_interest.description: Greenwich Park Bar

points_of_interest.name: Fluid
points_of_interest.description: A stylish loosely Japanese themed bar upstairs (they serve sushi), with a more spread out dance floor down a spiral metal staircase. Plenty of sofas everywhere, although on the weekends you will have to get down early to slump in a chair.

points_of_interest.name: The Ledger Building
points_of_interest.description: J D Wetherspoon Although the view is not so good, is probably the cheapest pub in Canary Wharf.
points_of_interest.address: 4 Hertsmere Rd, West India Quay, Docklands, E14 4AL

points_of_interest.name: Mahiki
points_of_interest.description: Cocktail bar and club.

points_of_interest.name: Ain't Nothin But The Blues Bar
points_of_interest.description: Blues bar.

points_of_interest.name: The Birdcage
points_of_interest.description: Friendly Stoke Newington pub that often has live bands playing.

points_of_interest.name: The Greenwich Union on Royal Hill
points_of_interest.description: Owned by the Meantime Brewery, based in nearby Charlton, which stocks its own range of beer in a variety of styles.
points_of_interest.address: 52-54 Royal Hill, Greenwich, London, SE10 8RT, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Fox & Anchor
points_of_interest.description: Independent traditional pub quite close to the Barbican. Beers are often served in pewter tankards for the extra traditional touch. Six rooms are available for those who want to sleep where they drink (or just near the Barbican). Great atmosphere but it can be a little more expensive than average, especially the food and lodging.

points_of_interest.name: Duke on the Green
points_of_interest.description: Very popular Young's pub at the Fulham end of the King's Rd.

points_of_interest.name: The Punchbowl
points_of_interest.description: Comfortable Georgian local with small rooms selling Harveys.

points_of_interest.name: Garlic & Shots
points_of_interest.description: Walk through the unassuming upstairs restaurant and head down the back stairs to find this small hidden basement bar, which boasts 101 different garlic and chilli-infused shots and loud rock/metal music. The 'Bloodshot' is highly recommended! There is also a seated outdoor smoking area out the back.

points_of_interest.name: The Cat & Mutton
points_of_interest.hours: M Tu 4–10PM, W–Sa noon–10PM, Su noon–9PM

points_of_interest.name: Horseshoe
points_of_interest.description: Irish pub where they play live Irish music every Thursday at 8PM (check it on the net!). But, be there in due time, else you risk house full!

points_of_interest.name: The Gun
points_of_interest.description: 18th-century pub with real fires, a terrace where you can sit and stare at the Millennium Dome over the river, and pistachio nuts behind the bar. A haven of warmth after a trek through JG Ballard-style Docklands wasteland (empty streets, vast satellite dishes and rusting industrial machinery).

points_of_interest.name: The White Horse
points_of_interest.description: The Sloaney Pony It offers an extensive choice of local and imported beers, both draught and bottled. It also serves restaurant grade meals. Particularly interesting, each one of them is matched with a beer. Somewhat expensive, but it is a must.

points_of_interest.name: The Anglesey Arms
points_of_interest.description: Traditional feel, friendly staff and good ale, albeit a bit on the pricey side. Shepherd Naeme pub.
points_of_interest.address: 90 Palace Rd, Sundridge Park, Bromley, BR1 3JX

points_of_interest.name: Milk and Honey
points_of_interest.description: Cocktail club with original branch in New York City. Members only, although non-members can phone and book a table. Unlike the rest of Soho, the atmosphere is quiet and unforgiving of rowdiness. If you cannot decide on a drink, ask the waiter to make you something and specify a few characteristics (fruity, gin-based, sour, etc.) and you'll usually be very pleasantly rewarded.

points_of_interest.name: The Cock Tavern
points_of_interest.hours: M–Th 4–11PM, F Sa noon–11PM, Su noon–9PMM

points_of_interest.name: The Lost Hour
points_of_interest.description: Friendly beach-themed bar set over two floors. One of the only bars in Greenwich that shows live sports, with multiple screens and a large projector screen. Video games consoles available to play on the ground floor. Reasonably priced pub food (burgers, wraps, etc.) and a large range of beer and other drinks.

points_of_interest.name: Jerusalem Tavern
points_of_interest.description: A converted Georgian coffee shop, which sells the Norfolk beer, St. Peters. The building is from the 1700s, remodelled in 1810, and it was converted in the 1990s, making this both a new and an old pub. The interior is a little small so, while well worth a visit, after 5PM on weekdays it gets quickly flooded with City workers.

points_of_interest.name: The Grapes
points_of_interest.description: A riverside local since 1583.

points_of_interest.name: The Prince Frederick
points_of_interest.description: Allegedly the only pub named after George II's son, ''Poor Fred'', Prince of Wales. It has managed to retain its traditional feel by maintaining separate saloon and lounge bars. A good choice of ales and lagers but no food. Greene King pub.
points_of_interest.address: 31 Nichol Ln, Sundridge Park, Bromley, BR1 4DE

points_of_interest.name: Bar Termini
points_of_interest.description: Italian-style bar serving cocktails and charcuterie. Excellent (and reasonable for the area) drinks in a cosy, quiet setting. No loud music, no rowdiness.

points_of_interest.name: Crate Brewery
points_of_interest.description: Beer and pizza focused bar on the canal, close to the Olympic Park.
points_of_interest.address: Unit 7, Queens Yard, Hackney Wick, E9 5EN

points_of_interest.name: Bubbledogs
points_of_interest.description: Champagne and cocktail bar serving gourmet hotdogs.

points_of_interest.name: Cafe Kick
points_of_interest.description: Hidden down a backstreet away from the busier parts of Clerkenwell, lies a cosy little bar crammed with several table football machines, and a good selection of cocktails. In the summer people spread out onto the pedestrianised street and chat in the sun. Happy hour 4-7PM daily.

points_of_interest.name: The Old Ship
points_of_interest.description: An East End Boozer with weekend drag acts.

points_of_interest.name: The Red Lion
points_of_interest.description: Some christen this ''the best pub in Bromley''. A friendly atmosphere, good quality ales and decent, affordable pub food make this an excllent choice. Greene King pub.
points_of_interest.address: 10 North Rd, Sundridge Park, Bromley, BR1 3LG

points_of_interest.name: Admiral Duncan
points_of_interest.description: A single room: what it lacks in space, it makes up for with drag performances. Make sure you head here on a Sunday evening for the Divine Ms Frankie Fantastique and her weekly game of "Rock and Roll Bingo".

points_of_interest.name: Chesham Arms
points_of_interest.description: Historic pub that is Hackney's first Asset of Community Value. It has a large beer garden, and won CAMRA East London Pub of The Year in 2016.

points_of_interest.name: Flying Horse
points_of_interest.description: formerly The Tottenham A Grade 11 listed Nicolson's pub.

points_of_interest.name: The Plume of Feathers
points_of_interest.description: A quaint little watering-hole, nearly on the prime meridian, with a variety of guest ales tucked away from the run-of-the mill riff-raff in Greenwich town centre. Excellent food at reasonable prices, try the delicious mixed platter for 4 to get the taste buds going!

points_of_interest.name: Water Rats Pub
points_of_interest.description: Has regular live bands.

points_of_interest.name: The Palm Tree
points_of_interest.description: A traditional East End boozer. Now set in the middle of Mile End Park, originally it was surrounded by houses and a factory. Its incongruous surroundings only add to the charm, however. You may recognise the interior from the number of film and TV appearances the pub has made as an "authentic" location. On Saturday nights the locals crowd into the front bar for a sing-song and the back bar is jammed with trendy students from Queen Mary's college. The presence of a student population mean this pub has less a threatening air than other East End locals.

points_of_interest.name: Green Dragon
points_of_interest.description: Pub with an eclectic but very good natured crowd. Live bands and DJs some nights of the week.

points_of_interest.name: The Wheatsheaf
points_of_interest.description: Freehouse with beautiful leaded windows. Used to be Aleister Crowley's regular.

points_of_interest.name: Richard I
points_of_interest.description: Owned by Young's, which sells its real ales. Nice beer garden at the back and does a good Sunday Roast. Hosts a popular pub quiz on Tuesday evenings.
points_of_interest.address: 50 Royal Hill, Greenwich, London, SE10 8RT, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Cittie of Yorke
points_of_interest.description: The interior gives the impression of being a historic relic but it was only built in 1924 (although there have been other pubs on the site since 1430). Lack of authenticity aside, it really is an impressive and atmospheric pub, a grade II listed building and on CAMRA's national inventory of historic pub interiors.

points_of_interest.name: The Morgan Arms
points_of_interest.description: Locally well-known boozer. The attached restaurant also serves some tasty, albeit pricey fare.

points_of_interest.name: Duke Of Wellington
points_of_interest.description: Superb "neighbourhood pub" which is popular with the bearish crowd. Good music and great choice of drinks. Downstairs is always busy - upstairs is more subdued with sofas and tables.

points_of_interest.name: Saint Monday
points_of_interest.description: Bar and brewery, serving vegan versions of smoke house dishes, including ribs and brisket

points_of_interest.name: The White Cross
points_of_interest.description: An 18th-century pub on the Thames, with seating outside overlooking the towpath, and which is often surrounded by water at high tide.

points_of_interest.name: The Knights Templar
points_of_interest.description: Part of the JD Wetherspoon chain. The building is the former Union Bank and it has nice high-vaulted ceilings with black pillars. The drinks range includes a range of often changing guests beers.

points_of_interest.name: 93 Feet East
points_of_interest.description: This club/bar is made up of three areas: downstairs a loungey bar with low-lit sofa seating everywhere and chilled out music, the main room with a full on sweaty dancefloor (where the headline DJs/bands perform) and an upstairs bar which is mix of the two, plus a large cobbled area outside for the summer. Mon-Thur is mainly live music, and the weekend has the line up of eclectic DJs playing a variety of hip-hop, house and rock music. Charge on the door for gigs, on F Sa usually free before 9PM, £5 after. No dress code.
points_of_interest.hours: M–Th 5–11PM; F 5PM–1AM; Sa noon–1AM; Su noon–10:30PM

points_of_interest.name: G-A-Y Bar
points_of_interest.description: Video monitors showing pop divas, and very cheap drinks. The G-A-Y brand also runs a late night bar, G-A-Y Late, as well as events at the nightclub Heaven (see Covent Garden). Fliers and wristbands for free or discounted entry are available both in and outside the Old Compton Street bar.

points_of_interest.name: Ye Olde Rose and Crown
points_of_interest.description: Rose and Crown The Rose and Crown is a cozy bar, out of main routes in Greenwich Park. As a typical British pub - serves quality food and wide range of drinks (British ales, lagers, wines, spirits, coffee and tea). Friendly staff and nicely selected music.

points_of_interest.name: The Lamb & Flag
points_of_interest.description: Fullers

points_of_interest.name: The Penderel's Oak
points_of_interest.description: Part of the JD Wetherspoon chain. The open-plan, L-shaped ground floor bar is known for a varied selection of guest beers (but poor Wi-Fi). The basement bar is actually part of the Lloyds No. 1 chain, with background music and a different atmosphere.

points_of_interest.name: Old Truman Brewery
points_of_interest.description: A large, lively place, which features a large courtyard and several floors for drinking and dancing. Hosts salsa classes too.

points_of_interest.name: The Yard Bar
points_of_interest.description: Cocktails, shirtless barman and all the usual facilities of a gay bar, plus a large, enclosed outside seating area and first floor balcony—great for sunny summer evenings, great for smokers too.

points_of_interest.name: Pitcher and Piano
points_of_interest.description: Has a large outdoor terrace looking over the River Thames and Richmond Bridge.

points_of_interest.name: The Pelton Arms
points_of_interest.description: Small local pub which hosts music nights and other events. Might be a good bet if you want to drink with locals, rather than tourists.

points_of_interest.name: Doggett's Coat and Badge
points_of_interest.description: A four-floored pub overlooking the Thames near Blackfriars Bridge.

points_of_interest.name: Marquess of Anglesey
points_of_interest.description: Youngs

points_of_interest.name: The Shakespeare's Head
points_of_interest.description: Part of the JD Wetherspoon chain.

points_of_interest.name: Cafe 1001
points_of_interest.description: Contrary to the name, this is another club/bar with a courtyard, which has a gourmet BBQ, next to the entrance. Can get very crowded on the weekend, with several other bars in the enclousre and the famous '''Rough Trade''' record store, which supports gigs (sometimes, surprise performances from a big band like Radiohead).
points_of_interest.address: 91 Brick Lane, Tower Hamlets, London, E1 6QL, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Bubbleology
points_of_interest.description: Quirky shop selling bubble teas in a very interesting way.

points_of_interest.name: The White Swan
points_of_interest.description: It is set further back on Old Palace Lane between the river and the Green

points_of_interest.name: River Ale House
points_of_interest.description: Greenwich's first micropub. Serves real ale, real cider, Belgian beers, wines and spirits. Also tea, coffee and soft drinks.

points_of_interest.name: Founders Arms
points_of_interest.description: Riverside Youngs' pub with an excellent view looking straight across the Thames at St. Paul's Cathedral and the rest of The City's iconic skyline.

points_of_interest.name: Nags Head
points_of_interest.description: McMullens

points_of_interest.name: The Square Pig
points_of_interest.description: Can be pricey and crowded too, but that's because it's used for large language-exchange and online meet-ups.

points_of_interest.name: Bar Kick
points_of_interest.description: A two-floor bar with plenty of table football machines to thrash away at. If you can not get a table the bar has a few sofas to wait for your turn in the quirky surroundings. It is a friendly place, where there is a mix of trendy boys and girls and suits from the city.

points_of_interest.name: Watermans
points_of_interest.description: It serves Thai food on Water Lane, nearer the town centre.

points_of_interest.name: The Vanbrugh
points_of_interest.description: Tucked away from the main roads, with an outdoor area at the rear. Friendly local pub doing gastropub food and guest ales. Weekly quiz nights.

points_of_interest.name: Roxy Bar and Screen
points_of_interest.description: Bar-cinema hybrid. Shows films every night except Friday and Saturday, when it is a normal bar. The back room is fitted with a high-definition projector and screens a range of films, acting as second-run cinema and a bar. Listings can include major sports events as well as mainstream and niche movies.
points_of_interest.address: 128-132 Borough High Street, Southwark, London, SE1 1LB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Porterhouse
points_of_interest.description: A modern pub split across multiple levels connected by narrow staircases and walkways, with a selection of over 100 bottled beers from around the world. Often with a band in the basement at weekends.

points_of_interest.name: Ye Olde Mitre
points_of_interest.description: Called the hardest to find pub in London. A small but historic and award-winning pub; it dates to 1586 and marked the boundary between the gardens of Christopher Hatton and the Bishop of Ely. Parts of the Tudor pub remain, although it was rebuilt in 1757 and partially altered in 1781 and 1930; now a Grade II listed building. It's tied to Fuller's brewery, so it has their usual range plus a few unusual guests. Only open one weekend in the year, to coincide with CAMRA's Great British Beer Festival in August.

points_of_interest.name: Catch
points_of_interest.description: A slightly shabby but friendly bar on the small strip of bars on Kingsland Road. Downstairs they have limited seating and draught beer, but upstairs is where it is happening. In the week you can catch live bands and on the weekends there are DJs playing xfm music mixed with a bit of cheese. It is also free to get in. Bargain.
points_of_interest.hours: M-Th normal pub hours, F Sa until 2AM

points_of_interest.name: Fitzroy Tavern
points_of_interest.description: Owned by the Samuel Smith brewery, the Fitzroy Tavern offers good, cheap beer. The pub, which took its name from a local aristocrat, the Earl of Fitzroy, in turn inspired the name of the surrounding area of Bloomsbury, Fitzrovia, and was a popular drinking place for BBC broadcasters (including George Orwell) following the Second World War. A very friendly pub, with nice outdoor seating in summer.

points_of_interest.name: The Old Ship
points_of_interest.description: A popular sports pub, offers pub grub.

points_of_interest.name: The Crown
points_of_interest.description: Slightly quirky local pub, offering real ales and occasional pizzas, plus board games and books, quizzes, and - in the winter - roaring fires.

points_of_interest.name: Windmill Tavern
points_of_interest.description: Friendly bar staff pouring chilled beers from a wide selection. Great pub food.

points_of_interest.name: Punch & Judy
points_of_interest.description: Visit its balcony looking over Covent Garden Piazza

points_of_interest.name: Ye Old White Horse
points_of_interest.description: The Horse Great little Victorian pub adjacent to the LSE campus. The Horse is one of the last remaining little boozers of its kind; a true throwback. Warm, welcoming, well-preserved interior, well-kept real ales, and a low-priced selection of sandwiches and pub meals make this place worth a visit while passing through Holborn.

points_of_interest.name: The Masque Haunt
points_of_interest.description: If you are into pubs and pub food, and especially the J.D. Wetherspoon concept, this is a very good spot. It is priced a notch under its more central sister pubs. The extensive menu consists of a good selection of general healthier pub food (pastas, salads, vegetarian burger, etc.), but also traditional food like potato & mash, fish & chips. For a good deal, go for the 2-for-1 at £6.99.

points_of_interest.name: Britannia
points_of_interest.address: 3 Brewer's Lane, Richmond upon Thames, Richmond, TW9 1HH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Davy's Wine Vaults
points_of_interest.description: Relaxed, wood-panelled wine bar offering over 100 varieties and a smart, British, seasonal menu. Large outdoor seating area.

points_of_interest.name: The White Hart
points_of_interest.description: Fuller's Really great pub with great mix of seating, specialist nights, interesting beers, great modern British pub food, and a nice outdoor area. Different nights including live music, quiz nights. Mixed crowd. Relaxed weekend day times, can get busy in the evenings. Decor is a mix of traditional, industrial/modern and quirky/shabby chic. Friendly staff.

points_of_interest.name: Old Fountain
points_of_interest.description: Local CAMRA Pub of the Year 2011. This traditional pub is best known for its large and varied beer selection, often from local and micro-breweries, both cask and bottled.

points_of_interest.name: The Princess of Shoreditch
points_of_interest.description: Gastropub.

points_of_interest.name: Cricketers Arms
points_of_interest.address: 24 The Green, Richmond upon Thames, Richmond, TW9 1LX, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Oliver's Jazz Bar
points_of_interest.description: Cozy and compact jazz bar with live music. Quirky decor and old furniture create a fun ambiance.

points_of_interest.name: Barrowboy & Banker
points_of_interest.description: This used to be the first branch of NatWest bank in the UK and it maintains a lot of the old bank fittings, from pillars to marble floors.

points_of_interest.name: The White Swan
points_of_interest.description: A Nicolson's free house.

points_of_interest.name: Fabric
points_of_interest.description: A massive club (think cathedral scale) that provides a more underground version of Ministry of Sound and hosts some of the biggest names in dance music, from Goldie to David Holmes to the Scratch Perverts. There are always big queues, so get down early if you can.

points_of_interest.name: The College Arms
points_of_interest.description: Pub frequented by students from nearby University College London and Birkbeck College.

points_of_interest.name: The Duke
points_of_interest.description: is a gastro pub.
points_of_interest.address: 2 Duke Street, Richmond upon Thames, Richmond, TW9 1HP, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Toomai Square
points_of_interest.description: Dishes range from yellow lobster curry and chicken Manchurian to black cod with ginger and shiitake mushrooms, and a drinks menu that includes cocktails.
points_of_interest.hours: M 3–11PM, Tu Th F 3–11:30PM, Sa noon–11:30PM, Su noon–11PM, closed W

points_of_interest.name: Brew Wharf
points_of_interest.description: This gastropub is part of Vinopolis but it is definitely beer-focussed—it even has its own microbrewery—with a large selection from around the world.

points_of_interest.name: The Grenadier
points_of_interest.description: An oddly quiet and secluded pub in the centre of the city due to being tucked away in a side street of another side street. It was built in 1720 as an officer's mess for the 1st Regiment of Foot Guards and became a pub in 1818. The pub is said to be haunted by the ghost of a junior officer who was caught cheating at cards and flogged to death.

points_of_interest.name: BrewDog Seven Dials
points_of_interest.description: BrewDog Scottish Ales

points_of_interest.name: The Nightjar
points_of_interest.description: Speakeasy-style cocktail bar. Regular live music fitting the prohibition era theme.

points_of_interest.name: The Prince's Head
points_of_interest.address: 9 Golden Court, Richmond upon Thames, Richmond, TW9 1EU, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Hare & Billet
points_of_interest.description: Popular gastro pub (suggest advance booking). Also serves selection of guest ales.

points_of_interest.name: George Inn
points_of_interest.description: This inn was built in 1676 after the original establishment was burned down in the Great London fire of 1666. The George is London's only surviving galleried coaching inn, and is one of the oldest pubs south of the Thames.

points_of_interest.name: The Star Tavern
points_of_interest.description: One of only two London pubs (and seven nationally) to feature in every edition of CAMRA's Good Beer Guide since its first publication; see The Buckingham Arms for the other one. The pub has a seedy past—it was infamous as a hangout for gang bosses and crime lords in the 1950s and 60s, and the Great Train Robbery was planned here, and celebrities of the era would come to socialise with the criminals. Today it is a safer, friendlier and more comfortable establishment that has recently been refurbished.

points_of_interest.name: The Craft Beer Co.
points_of_interest.description: A vast array of beers.

points_of_interest.name: Sosho
points_of_interest.description: Sosho is a former photographic studio and warehouse space converted into a two floor restaurant, bar, lounge and club with a 24 hour licence, midway between the city and central Shoreditch. Sosho is light and airy during the day time, candle lit and loungey in the evening. Serve carefully sourced and ''proper food'', with world class cocktails and great music on one of East London's best sound system. With a 24 hour licence it is a late night drinking and DJ bar during the week and a cutting edge clubbing venue at the weekend.
points_of_interest.hours: Tu noon-midnight; W Th noon-1AM; F noon-3AM; Sa 7PM-4AM; Su 9PM-6AM

points_of_interest.name: Captain Kidd
points_of_interest.description: Named after a pirate with a noose through the non-descript entrance.

points_of_interest.name: The Jeremy Bentham
points_of_interest.description: Named after the prominent political philosopher and early supporter of University College London, and located very near the main entrance to the college, the pub tends to attract more senior academics than does the College Arms.

points_of_interest.name: O'Neill's
points_of_interest.description: An Irish Pub

points_of_interest.name: The Hop Exchange building
points_of_interest.description: It used to supply hops to the many breweries that were based in the area in the past. Two different sister pubs now occupy the site:

points_of_interest.name: The Old Crown
points_of_interest.description: A stylish pub which closes late.
points_of_interest.hours: noon-11PM M Tu W, noon-3AM Th F Sa (closed Su)

points_of_interest.name: The Dickens Inn
points_of_interest.address: Marble Quay, St Katharine's Way, E1W 1UH

points_of_interest.name: The Lamb
points_of_interest.description: This beautifully preserved Victorian pub attracts many young and old patrons. Classic ales and some great food. Crowded after 5PM.
points_of_interest.hours: M-W noon-11PM, Th-Sa noon-midnight, Su noon-10:30PM. Food: daily noon-9:30PM

points_of_interest.name: The Princess Of Wales
points_of_interest.description: Was the changing room for the first rugby international (between England and Wales) in 1871 and the front bar dates from that time.

points_of_interest.name: The Rose Lounge
points_of_interest.description: French style afternoon tea.

points_of_interest.name: The Hercules Pillars
points_of_interest.description: with two life-sized Hercules holding up the bar.

points_of_interest.name: Prospect of Whitby
points_of_interest.description: The Pelican, Devil’s Tavern Oldest riverside tavern in London, with a pewter bar and views across the river.

points_of_interest.name: The Lord John Russell
points_of_interest.description: Authentic pub popular with university students.

points_of_interest.name: The Sun Inn
points_of_interest.description: Fullers

points_of_interest.name: Zerodegrees Microbrewery Restaurant Blackheath
points_of_interest.description: An industrial space where they brew and sell good beers. Also excellent pizzas and pasta.

points_of_interest.name: Princess Louise
points_of_interest.description: Ornately designed Victorian interior, mostly preserved from an 1891 remodelling, with wood and etched-glass partitions dividing it into smaller sections. A Grade II listed building and on CAMRA's national inventory of historic pub interiors.

points_of_interest.name: Town of Ramsgate
points_of_interest.description: A cosy pub

points_of_interest.name: Red Cow
points_of_interest.description: offers sports television, has a popular Tuesday night pub quiz and bands most Saturday nights.
points_of_interest.hours: M Tu 4-11PM, W Th noon-11PM, F Sa noon-midnight, Su noon-11PM

points_of_interest.name: The Railway
points_of_interest.description: Pub in central Blackheath village, serves food.

points_of_interest.name: The Market Porter
points_of_interest.description: A real ale pub that offers "a beer festival every day of the week". It puts new and different casks on as the previous one sell out and can have several new beers become available within a single day. Uses it early morning market licence to open with the dawn on weekdays. No bar food served on Saturdays but the restaurant upstairs is still open (M–Th noon–3PM, F–Su noon–5PM).
points_of_interest.hours: M–F 6–8:30AM and 11AM–11PM, Sa noon–11PM, Su noon–10:30PM

points_of_interest.name: The Spice of Life
points_of_interest.description: On Cambridge Circus, is a bustling middle-of-the-road gaf, with open-mic performances from talented musicians downstairs.
points_of_interest.address: 6 Moor Street, Westminster, London, W1D 5NA, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Mahogany Bar
points_of_interest.description: The Mahogany Bar was built around 1725 and has always been a public house, trading under many names over the years including the Albion Saloon and the Prince of Denmark. In 1828 it was luxuriously and elaborately refurbished with a magnificent mahogany bar and fittings which was unprecedented for a pub interior at that time and arguably set the look for the iconic Victorian pub. The fixtures and fittings of this bar have been stripped away over the years but the atmosphere lingers on. This is the charming bar inside the dilapidated Wilton's music Hall. Visit on a Monday for free live music from 8PM.
points_of_interest.address: Wilton's Music Hall, 1 Graces Alley off Ensign St, E1 8JB

points_of_interest.name: The Museum Tavern
points_of_interest.description: A very good pub, offering a wide range of real ales, and some excellent food. Can get busy in the summer months.

points_of_interest.name: White Horse

points_of_interest.name: The Royal Standard
points_of_interest.description: A locals pub which serves food, and hosts occasional live music and other events.

points_of_interest.name: The Rake
points_of_interest.description: Tiny pub that used to be a cafe, attached to Borough Market (it shares the gents' toilets) and owned by the market beer shop, Utobeer. Specialises in bottled beer, especially local and international craft beers.

points_of_interest.name: Golden Lion

points_of_interest.name: TCR Lounge Bar
points_of_interest.description: formerly, and commonly still known as, Ye Olde Surgeon A common drinking place for medical students from University College Hospital, who jostle alongside office workers. Gets exceptionally crowded after office hours.

points_of_interest.name: British Oak
points_of_interest.description: Friendly locals pub (recommend the lounge) which does Pie Minister pies, decent real ales. Regular live music.

points_of_interest.name: Old Red Lion
points_of_interest.description: A small freehouse, hidden down a passageway, with leaded windows and a red lion statue

points_of_interest.name: The Harp
points_of_interest.description: Narrow pub with stained glass windows that is enthusiastic about beer.

points_of_interest.name: Hand & Shears

points_of_interest.name: Be At One
points_of_interest.description: The chain wine bar also serves food.

points_of_interest.name: Dean Swift
points_of_interest.description: Beer specialist, which often includes casks from the local Kernel brewery as well as further afield.

points_of_interest.name: The Red Lion, Mayfair
points_of_interest.description: A beautiful Fullers pub with loads of mirrors.

points_of_interest.name: The Hope
points_of_interest.description: Grade II listed pub

points_of_interest.name: Victoria Inn
points_of_interest.description: has a cosy atmosphere

points_of_interest.name: Draft House
points_of_interest.description: A branch of the small, local chain of American-influenced pubs which "aims to do for beer what our culture has done for food and wine".

points_of_interest.name: CASK Pub & Kitchen
points_of_interest.description: One of RateBeer's Top 50 bars in the world, and only one of two in the UK (see The Craft Beer Company in Clerkenwell for the other). A specialist beer bar with a regularly changing selection of real ales and craft beer casks, plus a larger assortment of local and international bottles. Monday to Saturday, gourmet burgers are served by Forty Burgers; with traditional British roasts on Sundays.

points_of_interest.name: The Salisbury
points_of_interest.description: Beautifully preserved Victorian pub. Full of mirrors and lights, cut glass and mahogany, this place is nothing like the dark and dingy pubs that are all too common in London.

points_of_interest.name: The Jugged Hare
points_of_interest.description: A gastropub modelled on a traditional countryside drinking establishment, with a hunting theme. The tables are actually old whisky barrels and the décor features several stuffed animals and trophies. Completing the pattern, the food is heavily game-based, with some seafood. Their titular signature dish is an 18th-century stew recipe.

points_of_interest.name: Marlborough
points_of_interest.description: a family friendly pub with a large beer garden out the back (with a children's play area)

points_of_interest.name: Morpeth Arms
points_of_interest.description: Victorian pub built on the site of the cells of Millbank Prison, briefly Britain's National Penitentiary before being downgraded to a holding facility for convicts sentenced to transportation to Australia. The pub is said to be haunted by the ghosts of prisoners who didn't last long enough for the journey. For the living, the pub is next to the bank of the Thames and very close to the Tate gallery.

points_of_interest.name: The Coal Hole
points_of_interest.description: Grade II Listed

points_of_interest.name: Old Red Cow
points_of_interest.description: Small pub that serves real ale and craft beer from both major and local breweries.
points_of_interest.hours: M–Th noon–11PM; F–Sa noon-midnight; Su noon–10:30PM

points_of_interest.name: Roebuck
points_of_interest.description: It dates back to 1730. You can take your drink across the road to the Terrace which overlooks the famous view from Richmond Hill.

points_of_interest.name: Eat & Drink
points_of_interest.description: A small and fairly ordinary Chinese restaurant by day, this turns into a heaving karaoke bar in the evenings. One of the most reliable places near Liverpool St to get a drink after midnight!

points_of_interest.name: Builders Arms
points_of_interest.description: Gastropub near the Royal Marsden Hospital and just off the King's Rd.

points_of_interest.name: The Albert
points_of_interest.description: A nice, but often crowded, traditional pub, dating back to the 1860s, named in honour of Queen Victoria's husband. Portraits of British prime ministers, many of them signed, hang on the stairwell, and Chelsea pensioners (British war veterans) can often be seen propping up the bar.

points_of_interest.name: The Ship & Shovell
points_of_interest.description: Two pubs in one, either side of Craven Passage.

points_of_interest.name: Dirty Dick's
points_of_interest.description: One of the better known pubs (although definitely no tourist trap) near Liverpool St, supposedly named after a Georgian dandy who let himself go on the death of his fiancée.

points_of_interest.name: The Dysart
points_of_interest.description: Gastropub

points_of_interest.name: Chelsea Potter
points_of_interest.description: Traditional pub fare, but when warm outside, best people watching spot around. Also, Aussie and Kiwi barmen solidify the awesome environment here.

points_of_interest.name: The Cask and Glass
points_of_interest.description: Small traditional pub (one of the smallest in central London, in fact). Good beers and quaint interior.

points_of_interest.name: Light
points_of_interest.description: Stylish, ultra-modern space inside the St. Martin’s Lane Hotel. On Thursday, Friday and Saturday nights, many of London's most popular DJs are featured.

points_of_interest.name: The Old Doctor Butler's Head
points_of_interest.description: This claims to be one of London's oldest pubs, tracing it history to 1610, although it has been rebuilt since then. The eponymous Doctor Butler was a purveyor of "medicinal ale" who was appointed court physician to James I. Pubs selling his beer were allowed to display his portrait, hence the name of the establishment.

points_of_interest.name: Freud
points_of_interest.description: Frevd If you blink, you'll miss this casual cellar bar that serves up a variety of cocktails you can't find anywhere else in London. Has good mojitos, and even an Apple Pie concoction that tastes like a drink version of the real thing! Always very crowded at night on the weekends despite the fact that you need to go down a rickety metal staircase to find it.

points_of_interest.name: The Crosse Keys
points_of_interest.description: Part of the JD Wetherspoons chain in a converted bank. As is usual for the chain, it is fairly cheap with decent food and drink. The ex-bank building makes this pub a little grander and more spacious than most.

points_of_interest.name: The New Inn Ham Common
points_of_interest.description: The Grade 11 not so new inn.

points_of_interest.name: Coopers Arms
points_of_interest.description: Great pints, including Peroni on tap. Best Sunday Roast around, and more of a gastropub than a traditional pub.

points_of_interest.name: Wetherspoons
points_of_interest.description: A pub that doesn't even have its own name and may be missed by many of the 200,000 commuters and travellers who pass it each day, this place nevertheless serves good beer and food (it's part of the J D Wetherspoon chain). There is additional seating on the balconies on either side of the pub. Given its location, it also displays departure boards on its own screens.

points_of_interest.name: Halfway to Heaven
points_of_interest.description: Traditional pub owned by the night club, Heaven. Aimed more at office workers and locals than the clubbing crowd. The basement bar hosts entertainment in the evenings.
points_of_interest.hours: M–Th noon–midnight; F Sa noon–3AM; Su noon–11PM

points_of_interest.name: The Hung Drawn & Quartered
points_of_interest.description: Fullers Pub

points_of_interest.name: Windsor Castle
points_of_interest.description: Sam Smiths pub with plenty of etched glass.

points_of_interest.name: Heaven
points_of_interest.description: The most famous gay club in London, and perhaps the world. Has secret performances by the likes of Britney Spears or Kylie Minogue. Good fun, whether gay or straight.
points_of_interest.hours: M 11AM–5AM; Tu W closed; Th F 11PM–4AM; Sa 10:30PM–5AM

points_of_interest.name: Lamb Tavern
points_of_interest.description: One of several pubs in Leadenhall Market where you can listen to insurance brokers from nearby Lloyd's talk business.

points_of_interest.name: The Willow Walk
points_of_interest.description: Part of the J D Wetherspoon chain of pubs, just outside the East side of Victoria Station, a few doors down from the Apollo Victoria Theatre. Serves Real Ale and good food. Entrances on both Wilton Rd and Vauxhall Bridge Rd.

points_of_interest.name: The Retro Bar
points_of_interest.description: The antidote to gay bars: a pub-like atmosphere and great music.

points_of_interest.name: The Ship
points_of_interest.description: A Nicolson's pub rebuilt after it was burnt down during the fire of London.

points_of_interest.name: The Sterling
points_of_interest.description: A central bar that resides in the heart of the Gherkin. Catch your breath from the bustle of the City and enjoy a bit of ''al fresco'' dining. Food and drink available.

points_of_interest.name: Maggie's
points_of_interest.description: 1980s-themed nightclub. Named after 1980s prime minister Margaret Thatcher, whose speeches can be heard playing in the toilets. At the splurge level of costs, both to get in and at the bar.

points_of_interest.name: The Admiralty
points_of_interest.description: A Fullers Pub that has been decked out like a 18th century British warship.

points_of_interest.name: The Blackfriar
points_of_interest.description: A pub with an art deco church built inside.

points_of_interest.name: White Hart
points_of_interest.description: Riverside pub

points_of_interest.name: The Phoenix
points_of_interest.description: Great pints, tremendous place for a pint on a sunny day. be sure to grab one of the outdoor tables and enjoy a cool pint on a hot day here (when not raining in London).

points_of_interest.name: Queens Head
points_of_interest.description: LGBT traditional pub; real ale and standard pub food separates it from the trendier Kings Rd establishments. Karaoke every other Saturday.
points_of_interest.hours: M–Th noon–11PM; F–Sa noon–midnight; Su noon–11PM

points_of_interest.name: The Buckingham Arms
points_of_interest.description: One of only two London pubs (and seven nationally) to feature in every edition of CAMRA's Good Beer Guide since its first publication; see The Star Tavern for the other one. The building is a refitted early Victorian pub.

points_of_interest.name: Ye Olde Cheshire Cheese
points_of_interest.description: An old City pub establishment, rebuilt shortly after the Great Fire of 1666. All the monarchs who have reigned in England during the pub's time are written by the main door.

points_of_interest.name: Courtfield
points_of_interest.description: CAMRA-listed gastropub, serving food and a range of beers.

points_of_interest.name: The Sugar Loaf
points_of_interest.description: Pub that is popular with City workers. You will often find a crowd spilling out into the adjacent pedestrian area, particularly on Tuesdays-Thursdays when workers tend to come into the office more.

points_of_interest.name: The Edge Bar

points_of_interest.name: Drayton Arms
points_of_interest.description: A mix of traditional pub and bohemian nightspot. A good range of beer and slightly more upmarket than some other pubs in the area.

points_of_interest.name: Horse & Guardsman
points_of_interest.description: A McMullen pub at the top of Whitehall, close to Trafalgar Sq. with a cavalry theme worth going in foe the wall sized picture of the Scots Greys. Serves a good range of cask beers.

points_of_interest.name: Savage Garden
points_of_interest.description: Cocktail bar with 360 views of London

points_of_interest.name: Gloucester Arms

points_of_interest.name: The Red Lion
points_of_interest.description: The Prime Minister's Local A good place to see politicians and political commentators. The pub television shows (muted) debates from the House of Commons, and division bell rings here to summon Members of Parliament to vote on important issues in Parliament.

points_of_interest.name: El Vino
points_of_interest.description: Wine bar.

points_of_interest.name: The Prince of Teck
points_of_interest.description: Traditional pub downstairs with a dining area on the first floor.

points_of_interest.name: The Speaker
points_of_interest.description: A pub for local workers, including many civil servants and the odd Parliamentarian. The Parliament theme includes political caricatures on the walls. Markets itself as a real pub, with no fruit machines, music or television screens. Guest beers change every month.

points_of_interest.name: Vinoteca
points_of_interest.description: Wine bar and shop.

points_of_interest.name: St Stephen's Tavern Pub
points_of_interest.description: Victorian pub established in 1875 directly opposite the Palace of Westminster and the closest pub to "Big Ben" (from which it gets its name—while now officially known as Elizabeth Tower, Victorian journalists nicknamed it St Stephen's Tower). Often busy with tourists and other visitors to Parliament.

points_of_interest.name: Troubadour Wines
points_of_interest.description: This cozy wine bar is a quieter alternative to the buzz next door. With a great selection of wines from around the world, many of which are not available anywhere else in London, this is a peaceful oasis where you can discover delicious and good value wines. Drink in or take home.

points_of_interest.name: Zetland Arms
points_of_interest.description: Traditional pub near South Kensington station.

points_of_interest.description: Popular Danish café.

points_of_interest.name: The Antelope

points_of_interest.name: The Hour Glass
points_of_interest.description: This small, triangular, very easy-going pub just a little away from the main street bustle is a favorite among the locals, above all because the seating inside is designed to prevent overcrowding, but also for its pavement seating and upscale gastropub fare.

points_of_interest.name: Le Gourmet
points_of_interest.description: Lebanese

points_of_interest.name: Cockneys Pie & Mash Shop
points_of_interest.description: For a cheap lunch and to encounter traditional London food, this is a good place. For £4 you get a hot mince pie with mashed potatoes and liquor (a parsley sauce). It's good value and a place to be with the locals.

points_of_interest.name: Al Forno Wimbeldon

points_of_interest.description: Lebanese food, courtyard garden.

points_of_interest.description: Great burger restaurant.

points_of_interest.description: One of the best cheap eats in London. Authentic Afghan food which is a hugely better than you expect when looking at the place!

points_of_interest.description: Vegan takeaway/delivery only restaurant. Vegan burgers, dessert, sauces and sides for takeaway or home delivery. UK-wide delivery for vegan afternoon tea picnic hampers and DIY burger kits.

points_of_interest.name: Gallipoli Cafe & Bistro
points_of_interest.description: Well known and serve great Turkish meals, for very reasonable prices. Another branch nearby.

points_of_interest.description: Cosy, romantic French restaurant split amongst three floors. Typical French cuisine at low prices.

points_of_interest.name: Wasabi Sushi & Bento
points_of_interest.description: Japanese

points_of_interest.name: Lahore Karahi
points_of_interest.description: BYO, Halal. Pakistani restaurant serving great food at decent prices, albeit in very basic premises with cheap furnishing. No alcohol is served but you can bring your own at no charge.

points_of_interest.name: Tortilla
points_of_interest.description: Californian and Mexican take-away, serves fajitas/burritos/etc and Mexican beers. The food is fresh and mostly organic. Well priced, very friendly staff, open kitchen. Small number of benches for eating in.

points_of_interest.name: Lahore Spices Tooting

points_of_interest.description: Italian.
