points_of_interest.name: Cookies and Scream
points_of_interest.description: Vegan and gluten-free cafe. It's a bit pricey though cakes are delicious and without compromise, despite the limitations.

points_of_interest.name: Lokkanta
points_of_interest.description: Turkish

points_of_interest.name: Sumi
points_of_interest.description: A branch of Endo in Shepherd's Bush, opened in 2021, serving Japanese standards.
points_of_interest.hours: Tu–F noon–2:30PM & 5:30–10PM, Sa noon–10PM, closed Su M

points_of_interest.name: Ma Goa
points_of_interest.description: Fine Indian cuisine.

points_of_interest.name: Slurp
points_of_interest.description: Good Chinese and Japanese noodle bar, great value. Try the bento box.

points_of_interest.name: Iberia
points_of_interest.description: Charming Georgian restaurant serving unsophisticated, but incredibly tasty, national cuisine: stews, pies, dumplings, breads. An all-Georgian wine list, with the bottles stacked cellar-fashion (floor to ceiling) against the back wall, complete the experience. The slow pace of dining, either inside or on the terrace, is a welcome deviation from the London norm.

points_of_interest.name: Albina
points_of_interest.description: Tasty Ukrainian food in a rustic restaurant. Try the golubtsi (cabbage rolls) and the cutlets.
points_of_interest.hours: W Th 3-11PM, F Sa 3PM-1:30AM, M Tu closed

points_of_interest.name: Lahore Biryani
points_of_interest.description: A Pakistani restaurant

points_of_interest.name: Maoz
points_of_interest.description: The best place for a light fast-food style vegetarian/vegan meal, one of the few places in Soho where a fiver (April 2021) can get you sated.

points_of_interest.name: Kahn's
points_of_interest.description: Very popular and large Indian restaurant, probably not as good as the Standard though.

points_of_interest.name: Mirch Masala
points_of_interest.description: BYO, Halal. This place would not win points for interior design, but despite the canteen-style furnishings you have the advantage of an open kitchen, so you can see exactly what they are doing to your food. The staff are numerous, fast and friendly, and you are barely sat down before a plate of poppodoms appear in front of you like magic. The menu caters very well for vegetarians, but still offers plenty of lamb, chicken and fish dishes, all generous portions and very reasonably priced.

points_of_interest.name: Thai Tho Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Thai.
points_of_interest.hours: W Th noon–10PM, F Sa 11AM–11PM, Su noon–10PM

points_of_interest.name: Kalendar
points_of_interest.description: Stands out as a bohemian deli/cafe with beautiful if not cheap food. Excellent for brunch/long weekend lunches. Chunky rustic furniture, specials on blackboards, free newspapers. Quite child friendly.

points_of_interest.name: Kebabish
points_of_interest.description: Does a nice kebab and also tasty Indian food.

points_of_interest.name: La Creperie de Hampstead
points_of_interest.description: A crepe stall in front of the King William IV pub. A wide variety of tasty sweet and savoury crepes for under a fiver. Queues can get long at the weekends. Been around a long time and passes the longevity test.

points_of_interest.name: Montagu Pyke - JD Wetherspoon
points_of_interest.description: Offers real ales and two-for-one offers on a variety of meals.

points_of_interest.name: e&o Notting Hill
points_of_interest.description: Pan Asian food. Japanese-influenced restaurant with a stylish bar attached. Great cocktails.

points_of_interest.name: Preto
points_of_interest.description: Brazilian steakhouse, with a great-value buffet (£17 with meat cooked to your liking).

points_of_interest.name: Masala Zone
points_of_interest.description: This hip Indian restaurant chain's Angel branch. Good value Indian food, try a Thali for a good sized meal with a variety of flavours.

points_of_interest.name: Thainese
points_of_interest.description: Halal Singaporean Chinese and Thai, black pepper crabs, chilli lobster, private rooms, prayer rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Jin Kichi
points_of_interest.description: Really good value, no frills sushi restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: La Porchetta Pollo Bar
points_of_interest.description: Italian cuisine

points_of_interest.name: The Ledbury
points_of_interest.description: A 2* Michelin restaurant, with exquisite dishes rustled up by talented Aussie chef Brett Graham. Features highly-by food critics, so don't expect cheap bites! Easy to drop £100 in here!.

points_of_interest.name: Radha Krishna Bhavan
points_of_interest.description: Fully licensed. The decor is charmingly ''eccentric'', which just means it is a bit bonkers. Sunset palm trees on the walls and large masked figures glare back at you. The specialty here is South Indian (unlike Brick Lane which is mainly Bangladeshi), so you may discover plenty of dishes you have never heard of before. The poppodoms have some very tasty dips and every dish is very cheap for London, meaning you can try loads of different dishes between a large group. Highly recommended.
points_of_interest.hours: Su W Th noon–3PM & 6–10PM, F Sa noon–3PM & 6–10:30PM, closed M Tu

points_of_interest.name: Station 26
points_of_interest.description: Gluten-free restaurant.
points_of_interest.address: Coldharbour Lane, Unit 26 Brixton Village Market, SW9 8PR
points_of_interest.hours: W-F noon-10PM, Sa 11AM-10PM, Su 11AM-4PM, M Tu closed

points_of_interest.name: Mem & Laz
points_of_interest.description: Large menu of great Mediterranean food, friendly staff, very reasonably priced. Their lunchtime two-course special around £7 is available to 6PM, an excellent option for an early dinner.

points_of_interest.name: Supperclub.tube
points_of_interest.description: Enjoy a Latin American feast on board an old Tube carriage! Chef Beatriz (Bea) Maldonado, originally from Bogotá, takes you on a six-course culinary tour of her continent of birth, while you soak up the convivial and surprisingly romantic atmosphere of a Victoria Line 1967 stock. Although following a set menu, Bea can arrange substitute courses to suit dietary needs.

points_of_interest.name: Nautilus
points_of_interest.description: A very well known fish and chip shop. The great British invention to either take away or eat in. Locals travel a long way to buy here.

points_of_interest.name: Wong Kei
points_of_interest.description: A Chinatown institution. Popular with Londoners and visitors alike and possibly the best value Chinese restaurant in the whole of London. Spread across four floors, this restaurant is infamous for its surly, abrupt service and this has become part of the experience of dining there. Depending on how drunk you look, the higher up the building you will be sent. Tea is complimentary, though somewhat bland. Set meals present excellent value for money, some being under £5. The sweet and sour pork is remarkably good.

points_of_interest.name: Thai Girder
points_of_interest.description: A Thai restaurant with an iron girder running through the middle of the place.

points_of_interest.name: Franco Manca
points_of_interest.description: Once named Timeout's #1 cheap eat in all of London and is always ludicrously busy. Authentic Italian sour dough pizza for very cheap prices. Top tip for Saturday dining: Turn up at 11:45AM, 15 minutes before it opens. You queue 15 minutes guaranteed, but can over an hours wait if you turn up at 12:15AM.

points_of_interest.name: St. John's Tavern
points_of_interest.description: Expensive gastro pub. Quite pleasant.

points_of_interest.name: Deeney's
points_of_interest.description: Café serving coffee, brunch and their famous Scottish haggis toasties.

points_of_interest.name: Parliament Hill Café
points_of_interest.description: The only cafe actually on Hampstead Heath, and a nice place to stop for a drink or quick bite after exploring the heath.
points_of_interest.address: 170 Highgate Road, Camden, London, NW5 1EJ, United Kingdom
points_of_interest.hours: 9AM to between 4 and 9PM depending on the season

points_of_interest.name: Mr Wu
points_of_interest.description: MW Buffet A buffet restaurant

points_of_interest.name: Darna Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Hookah Bar

points_of_interest.name: Jack and Beyond
points_of_interest.description: Cake and coffee shop.

points_of_interest.name: Asmara
points_of_interest.description: Small friendly restaurant serving interesting Eritrean food.

points_of_interest.name: Sunderban
points_of_interest.description: Delicious North Indian/Bangladeshi cuisine and a good value. One of the best curries in London.

points_of_interest.name: The Pantry Café
points_of_interest.description: Traditional British café. Different menu options are placed on the wall to make ordering easier "I want a 4, I'd like a 9" but the friendly owner will of course accept any variation you want. This café beats the chain hotel breakfasts for price and quality. Stay away if you want haute cuisine.

points_of_interest.name: Caffe Nero
points_of_interest.description: Modern coffee shop chain just around the corner from Hampstead tube station. Serves decent coffee with cakes and savoury snacks at slightly lower prices than elsewhere in Hampstead Village. Part of a large chain.

points_of_interest.name: Misato
points_of_interest.description: Japanese

points_of_interest.name: Azmar
points_of_interest.description: Middle-Eastern cuisine

points_of_interest.name: Tongue & Brisket
points_of_interest.description: Salt Beef

points_of_interest.name: Chez Bruce
points_of_interest.description: Michelin star restaurant serving Modern European cuisine. Despite the award, unpretentious, great food and service; situated across the road from Wandsworth Common.

points_of_interest.name: Eco Pizza
points_of_interest.description: formerly Pizzeria Franco Tasty reasonably priced pizzas, calzones and sandwiches using fresh ingredients.
points_of_interest.address: 162 Clapham High St, Clapham Town, SW4 7UG

points_of_interest.name: Sweet Handz
points_of_interest.description: Delicious Ghanaian food.

points_of_interest.name: The Ferry Boat Inn
points_of_interest.description: Large yet cosy venue for scrummy pub grub, with roaring fires and a décor which harks back to when Tottenham was just a Middlesex village. Good place to end a walk through the Lea Valley Regional Park., A quaint country-style pub in a lovely river side setting.

points_of_interest.name: Carluccio's
points_of_interest.description: Serves cheap and decent, if not terribly inspired, Italian food. Good value for this area. Also has a deli attached. Part of a large chain.

points_of_interest.name: Kalamaras
points_of_interest.description: '''Temporarily closed as of May 2022'''. Markets itself as London's oldest Greek restaurant. Not sure if that is true but it has been around a long time in this quiet mews in Bayswater and is a favourite with local residents. Counts several celebs amongst its regular clientele. Try the taramasalata and keftedes.

points_of_interest.name: The Kati Roll Company
points_of_interest.description: Hot Indian wraps

points_of_interest.name: Thai Square
points_of_interest.description: Thai bar/restaurant. Good, if expensive food, impressive decor, great view of the Thames river.

points_of_interest.name: Gandhi's Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Traditional Indian restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Laza
points_of_interest.description: Generous servings of Eritrean food with warm, friendly service. Like the cuisine of neighbouring Ethiopia, Eritrean food is served on ''injera'' flatbread and eaten with the fingers. Good vegetarian and vegan options.

points_of_interest.name: Bohemia House
points_of_interest.description: formerly Czechoslovak Serves traditional Czech-Slovak dishes such as svíčková (beef steak in a creamy sauce) and guláš (goulash) with knedlíky (boiled bread dumplings) at reasonable prices, also has plenty of memorabilia on display particularly from World War II.
points_of_interest.address: 74 West End Ln, West Hampstead, NW6 2LX
points_of_interest.hours: M: Closed, Tu-F: 5PM-10:30PM, Sa: noon-10:30PM, Su: noon-10PM

points_of_interest.name: The Waterway
points_of_interest.description: Stylish bar and restaurant alongside the canal at Little Venice. Has an alfresco dining area right by the water during summer. Mixed European food

points_of_interest.name: LEON Regent Street
points_of_interest.description: Mediterranean restaurant with counter service

points_of_interest.name: Bar Italia
points_of_interest.description: A cafe with a lot of character.

points_of_interest.name: Ichiban Sushi
points_of_interest.description: Great freshly prepared sushi and tofu dishes.

points_of_interest.name: Kipferl
points_of_interest.description: Austrian restaurant and patisserie. Vegetarian/vegan options available. Try the Sachertorte!

points_of_interest.name: Freemason's Arms
points_of_interest.description: A gastro pub offering both homely dishes and some more ambitious options. Good location only one minute walk from Hampstead Heath. Has a large open garden with many tables which is lovely in the summer.

points_of_interest.name: The Moon Under Water - JD Wetherspoon
Il Gusto
points_of_interest.description: An inexpensive casual Italian restaurant serving pasta, pizza and seafood. Also has an extensive dessert menu.

points_of_interest.name: The Limehouse
points_of_interest.description: Lunchtime menus include a mixture of continental and international meals. A snack menu is available in the evening. Two mezzanine areas at the bar for private party bookings.

points_of_interest.name: Benito’s
points_of_interest.description: A casual Mexican restaurant

points_of_interest.name: Taro
points_of_interest.description: Noodles, sushi, bento boxes and assorted other Japanese goodies. Good cheap eats and reliable quality.
points_of_interest.hours: M–Th noon–10:30PM, F Sa noon–11PM, Su 12:30–9:30PM

points_of_interest.name: Negril
points_of_interest.description: Jamaican restaurant that serves traditional Jerk chicken and Caribbean curries. Most of the food is organic and they make their own fresh fruit juice. Reasonably priced and has lovely patio area.

points_of_interest.name: Mildreds
points_of_interest.description: International all plant based menu, can be busy. Part of a small chain.

points_of_interest.name: Little Bay Kilburn
points_of_interest.description: A great modern European restaurant in the West Hampstead/Kilburn area serving high quality food at great value for money prices. They have a party offer for groups of 12 or more., European cuisine.

points_of_interest.name: Leong's Legend
points_of_interest.description: Serves Taiwanese fare. Chilli crab and omelette dishes are specialities.

points_of_interest.name: Four Seasons Chinese Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: One of London's most esteemed Chinese restaurants, known internationally for its Cantonese-style roast duck.

points_of_interest.name: Hare Krishna cart
points_of_interest.description: Shows up on the edge of Houghton St regularly on weekdays offering free vegan food, if you don't mind the sogginess and queue.

points_of_interest.name: Gaucho Grill
points_of_interest.description: The Argentinian cowboy, the gaucho, made famous the tradition of cooking fresh meat over charcoal grills. The large horseshoe bar offers traditional South American cocktails and beer.

points_of_interest.name: Coco di Mama - Italian To Go - Margaret St
Balan's
points_of_interest.description: Almost a Soho institution, this 24-hour eatery in the heart of the gay village offers a wide range of British and world cuisine in a stylish atmosphere. Has now gone international with branches in Miami, but the original Old Compton Street Balans is still be best, attracting clientele as diverse as the late TV presenter Dale Winton and politician and former mayor Ken Livingstone among its regulars.

points_of_interest.name: The Pepper Tree
points_of_interest.description: A long-established and very popular Thai restaurant serving good food in rather spartan surroundings, alongside Clapham Common. Good value. Expect to queue in the peak period.

points_of_interest.name: Manna
points_of_interest.description: The UK's oldest vegetarian restaurant which has been in operation since 1966. That says a lot about the quality of the food, and the presentation and service are also top notch.

points_of_interest.name: The Kings Head
points_of_interest.description: Redeveloped pub. Trendy crowd, with comedy on a Monday night.

points_of_interest.name: C&R Cafe Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Worth checking out for cheap Malaysian-Singaporean eats.

points_of_interest.name: Whitecross Street Market
points_of_interest.description: Eclectic street-food market.

points_of_interest.name: Plateau Restaurant Bar and Grill
points_of_interest.description: Modern French restaurant, part of the Conran restaurants group. More informal Bar and Grill includes steak grills and hearty regional French dishes. Two bars.

points_of_interest.name: Busaba Eathai
points_of_interest.description: One of the best choices on a street with any number of fantastic restaurants. You will find a laid back atmosphere with big low wooden tables (expect to share if your party is small). The menu features among other dishes a fine butternut squash curry.

points_of_interest.name: Satay Bar
points_of_interest.description: Brixton's longest-running restaurant, specialising in Indonesian, Malaysian and Thai cuisine. Also has a cocktail bar and lounge with an extensive cocktail list and premium drinks menu. Located next to the Ritzy Cinema. Probably Brixton's busiest restaurant and it runs many specials including a lunch special at £4.95.

points_of_interest.name: Mimmo la Bufala
points_of_interest.description: Italian bistro with an extensive menu of pizzas and grill items.
points_of_interest.hours: M-F noon-3PM and 6-11PM, Sa Su noon-11PM

points_of_interest.name: O's Thai Café
points_of_interest.description: Good quality reasonably priced Thai food. Buzzy atmosphere.
points_of_interest.hours: Su Tu W 3–10PM, Th–Sa 2–10PM, closed M

points_of_interest.name: Necco
points_of_interest.description: Japanese cafe bar with home-made sushi and a range of bento-box combinations. Friendly staff.

points_of_interest.name: Quadrato
points_of_interest.description: International classics for breakfast and northern Italian cuisine for lunch and dinner. The Tuscan Sunday Brunch and cocktails at bar Quadrato should not be missed. Watching chef Sebastiano Spriveri at work is a main attraction.

points_of_interest.name: The Duke of Argyll
points_of_interest.description: This Victorian-themed pub serves meals upstairs. The updated pup food includes a surprising range of vegetarian (some vegan) options. Order at the bar, they serve at your table. Cheap, interesting draught beers (see ''Drink''). The real fireplace adds atmosphere, and a smoke scent to your clothing. Photos of the local area 100+ years ago teach history lessons. They have a no-electronics policy: put away your phone and interact with people instead.

points_of_interest.name: Trinity Upstairs
points_of_interest.description: Michelin Bib Gourmand winning restaurant in the unlikeliest of locations. A non-descript door buzzer in what looks like a flat leads you up to a cosy bar serving delicious cocktails before you ascend again to the tiny restaurant. The food is delicious and though expensive, very reasonably priced for such upmarket cuisine with very attentive staff. Not a place for every day, but a great choice for a treat.

points_of_interest.name: Odette's
points_of_interest.description: Modern European cooking in the Primrose Hill district. Interesting set degustation menu for £60 per head.

points_of_interest.name: Falafel Feast
points_of_interest.description: High quality and affordable authentic middle-eastern specialties - including sabich, shakshuka and falafel - served by friendly staff.

points_of_interest.name: The Portrait Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Offers spectacular food accompanied by spectacular art on the 5th floor of the National Portrait Gallery. A must-do dining experience.

points_of_interest.name: Snak Express
points_of_interest.description: Cheap and wholesome

points_of_interest.name: Royal China
points_of_interest.description: Popular restaurant with a great view of the Thames River. Decorated with Royal China gives a contemporary feel. Enjoy dim-sum and an extensive menu.

points_of_interest.name: Maroush
points_of_interest.description: A chain of Middle Eastern food; belly dancing at night.

points_of_interest.name: Mildred's
points_of_interest.description: Mostly-vegan, all-vegetarian, interesting menu and very tasty food, since 1988.

points_of_interest.name: The Kings Arms
points_of_interest.description: This pub is well situated for the tourist attractions in Greenwich and does good bar food.

points_of_interest.name: Wang Fa
points_of_interest.description: Authentic Chinese and Japanese cuisine. Bento boxes, pad Thai, mizo, spare ribs.

points_of_interest.name: Cafe Japan
points_of_interest.description: Very good food. Zagat rated. Book in advance as they get very busy.
points_of_interest.hours: W Th 5–9PM, F noon–2PM & 5–9PM, Sa Su noon–2:30PM & 5–9PM

points_of_interest.name: Tokyo Diner
points_of_interest.description: Offers excellent and well-priced Japanese food.

points_of_interest.name: LSE Students' Union bar
points_of_interest.description: They sell tasty lunchtime meals
points_of_interest.address: Saw Swee Hock Student Centre, 1 Sheffield St

points_of_interest.name: Zizzi
points_of_interest.description: Serves authentic pastas and pizzas. During the summer a large riverside terrace affords sweeping views over the River Thames. A chain restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: W6 Garden Centre and Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Set in the District Line viaduct that cuts through Ravenscourt Park. It has a good assortment of vegan and gluten-free cakes.

points_of_interest.name: Paul Marylebone
points_of_interest.description: French patisserie and bakery with some seating available.

points_of_interest.name: St Moritz
points_of_interest.description: A slice of the Swiss Alps in central London, offering fondue, raclette and other winter comfort foods amongst giant alpine horns and cowbells.
points_of_interest.hours: M-F noon-3PM and 6PM-11:30PM, Sa noon-11:30PM, Su noon-10:30PM

points_of_interest.name: The Mogul Tandoori
points_of_interest.description: This restaurant provides excellent Nepalese and Northern Indian cuisine in an unusual and interesting setting (as long as you get seated downstairs, below street level).

points_of_interest.name: L'artista
points_of_interest.description: Superb Italian food - generous portions, large varied menu; perhaps one of the best Italian restaurants in London whether a quick pizza or party. Somewhat noisy esp. in evenings from adjacent railway and staff celebrating diners' birthdays with clashing cymbals and parades, quieter in back and in the covered outdoor area.

points_of_interest.name: Vantra Vegan
points_of_interest.description: Friendly, quiet vegan restaurant near the edge of Chinatown. Try the mock meats.

points_of_interest.name: Wright's Bar
points_of_interest.description: Excellent value little cafe with friendly Italian family serving, tasty sandwiches and coffee. Gets crowded with LSE students come lunch.

points_of_interest.name: The Greedy Cow
points_of_interest.description: A cosy restaurant serving burgers with unusual and exotic ingredients, along with more traditional fare such as chicken or beef. Salads and steaks also available.

points_of_interest.name: Abu Zaad
points_of_interest.description: Authentic Syrian fare. Great value.

points_of_interest.name: Sea Shell of Lisson Grove
points_of_interest.description: A premium fish and chip shop that has some seating as well as dishing up hundreds of take-away packages every day. Londoners travel miles to order here. The effort is well and truly worth it.

points_of_interest.name: Koya
points_of_interest.description: Cozy Japanese restaurant serving freshly made udon noodles, walk-ins only.

points_of_interest.name: YouMeSushi
points_of_interest.description: '''Temporarily closed as of May 2022'''. Founded in 2008, YouMeSushi has gone from strength to strength with the opening of three additional venues. Eat in, take away or have sushi delivered straight to your door (within a 3-mile radius).

points_of_interest.name: Tai Won Mein noodle houses
points_of_interest.description: Offers budget Chinese cuisine, at a budget price if you're after a bargain rather than quality. They only take cash. '''Noodle Time''' and '''Saigon''' are located around the street, facing each other, and offer similar fare/price.
points_of_interest.address: 10-11 Nelson Road, Greenwich, London, SE10 9JB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The restaurants and food shops of the Harringay stretch of Green Lanes
points_of_interest.description: One of London's great collections of restaurants, with a predominance of Turkish food.
points_of_interest.address: 375-377 Green Lanes, Haringey, London, N4 1ES, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Golden Gate Cake Shop
points_of_interest.description: Place Chinese cakes on a tray and take them to the cashier.

points_of_interest.name: Oddono's Chiswick
points_of_interest.description: An Italian gelato chain, the ice cream is delicious.

points_of_interest.name: atis Old Street
points_of_interest.description: Bowls and salads with ingredients like quinoa, kale, and edamame, striking an impressive balance of healthy, tasty, and reasonably priced.

points_of_interest.name: The Crown
points_of_interest.description: Remarkable gastropub.

points_of_interest.name: Raj of India
points_of_interest.description: Very reasonable prices and good service at this popular Indian restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Neat Burger
points_of_interest.description: Vegan burgers, fries, and shakes with retro decor.

points_of_interest.name: Green Papaya Xi'Viet
points_of_interest.description: Offering great Vietnamese food for vegetarians and meat eaters alike.
points_of_interest.hours: Tu–F noon–3PM & 5–11PM, Sa 1–11PM, Su 1–10:30PM, closed M

points_of_interest.name: Old Brewery
points_of_interest.description: Part of the local Meantime Brewery's growing empire with a massive enclosed outdoor area - great in the summer months. Part of the same building as the tourist information centre, and perhaps more popular with tourists than locals although there is a mix of both. A cafe, and a pub/restaurant - the latter serves good if relatively expensive food (£13.50 for a burger) and a range of good Meantime beers, which are still brewed a couple of miles away. Service can be a little slow when it's busy.

points_of_interest.name: High Road Brasserie
points_of_interest.description: Highly reviewed in the local and national press. The menu includes brasserie classics, seafood platters, and fancy sandwiches.

points_of_interest.name: Mola Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Cheery cafe serving breakfast and lunch.

points_of_interest.name: Red Sea Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: All manner of Middle Eastern food with Eritrean and Ethiopian also town in! All at very reasonable prices.

points_of_interest.name: Carluccio's
points_of_interest.description: Creative Italian cuisine, enjoy a bottle of pinot grigio at the bar while waiting for a table to free.

points_of_interest.name: Andrew Edmunds Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Top quality restaurant, great romantic spot. Bookings recommended.

points_of_interest.name: Mess Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Great quality caf breakfasts.

points_of_interest.name: Bibimbab Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Korean

points_of_interest.name: Greenwich Market Food Court
points_of_interest.description: Expanded in 2016, Greenwich Market's outdoor food court is now a dedicated section of the market. Dozens of street food stalls offer a range of cuisines from around the world. Seating is limited, so it is best to buy your food and eat it either in Greenwich Park or next to the river by Cutty Sark.

points_of_interest.name: La Trompette
points_of_interest.description: Probably the best restaurant in West London, great value French cuisine, excellent wine list.

points_of_interest.name: Blue Lion
points_of_interest.description: Offers good food in an easy pub atmosphere.

points_of_interest.name: Orange Room
points_of_interest.description: A good place for chilled-out lunches.

points_of_interest.name: Fiesta Havana
points_of_interest.description: Latin themed restaurant with live DJs and staff who will give you Salsa classes in between courses! The set tapas menu for £10 is very popular.

points_of_interest.name: Giraffe Burgers and Cocktails
points_of_interest.description: World food at great prices. Great for children
points_of_interest.address: 35 James Street, Westminster, London, W1U 1EA, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: L'Escargot
points_of_interest.description: This French restaurant has been serving up refined cuisine to the Soho faithful since 1927. It is owned and run by celebrity chef Marco Pierre White. The brasserie downstairs is slightly less formal than the Michelin-starred upper level.

points_of_interest.name: Sông Quê Café
points_of_interest.description: Rated by Zagat as the best Vietnamese on Kingsland Rd.
points_of_interest.hours: M–F noon–3PM & 5:30–11PM, Sa noon–11PM, Su & holidays noon–10:30PM

points_of_interest.name: Seoul Bakery
points_of_interest.description: Korean

points_of_interest.name: The Hollyhock Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Great location in the gardens. It sells mainly coffee and cakes and a few lunch dishes.

points_of_interest.name: Buenos Aires Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Casual Argentinian cafe with steaks, Spanish-themed food and brunch. Relaxing orangery and garden at the rear.

points_of_interest.name: Karamel London N22
points_of_interest.description: Global fusion homemade cuisine and music venue.

points_of_interest.name: Old Pack Horse
points_of_interest.description: Despite being a Victorian Fuller's pub at the front, there is a Thai restaurant at the back. The menu is extensive, and vegan-friendly with the allergens clearly marked.

points_of_interest.name: My Old Dutch
points_of_interest.description: Pancake house. Offers £5 for any pancakes, but only on Monday. Nice selection of Dutch and European beers.

points_of_interest.name: Azou
points_of_interest.description: Algerian restaurant with an emphasis on tajines. The winner of [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qFIlGLnjn7g Gordon Ramsay's Best Restaurant 2010 competition] for best North African restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Tapa Room
points_of_interest.description: With the more formal ''Providores restaurant'' upstairs.

points_of_interest.name: Quo Vadis
points_of_interest.description: Bit of a Soho institution that used to be owned by Marco Pierre White. Now under new management but little has changed. Top notch British grill style food in a very smart environment.

points_of_interest.name: Viet Hoa
points_of_interest.description: You must try the salted prawns!

points_of_interest.name: PaStation
points_of_interest.description: Italian cuisine

points_of_interest.name: Cafe Nano
points_of_interest.description: Lovely food & Italian coffee full of aroma & flavour.

points_of_interest.name: Rivington Greenwich
points_of_interest.description: Modern British food with seasonal ingredients. Next door to the Greenwich Picture House.

points_of_interest.name: Vrisaki
points_of_interest.description: Authentic Greek (Cypriot) food. Highly recommended by Haringey and Enfield residents.
points_of_interest.hours: Tu–Sa noon–11PM, Su noon–9PM, closed M

points_of_interest.name: At Thai
points_of_interest.description: Inexpensive Thai food with the same menu as Angrid Thai in Oxford.

points_of_interest.name: Tinseltown
points_of_interest.description: Halal American-style diner, serving burgers, steaks, and grilled meat. Good for Muslims on a budget and hungry, early-morning clubbers.
points_of_interest.hours: M-Th noon-5AM; F Sa noon-4AM; Su noon-3AM

points_of_interest.name: Bengal Village
points_of_interest.description: Good food, good value, pleasant atmosphere and good service.

points_of_interest.name: William IV
points_of_interest.description: Pub with rooms, it's the food the gets the great reviews.

points_of_interest.name: MEATliquor
points_of_interest.description: American dive bar offering great burgers. No reservations.

points_of_interest.name: Vasco and Piero's Pavilion
points_of_interest.description: Umbrian food prepared with the very best ingredients by chef Vasco. All the pasta is freshly made on the premises. The calve's liver is especially famous. Has been in business here for 40 years.

points_of_interest.name: Victoria Park Market
points_of_interest.description: Lots of street food from around the world at a weekly outdoor market.

points_of_interest.name: Cafe Metro Express
points_of_interest.description: Moroccan cuisine

points_of_interest.name: Richmond Thai Kitchen
points_of_interest.description: Thai cuisine.

points_of_interest.name: Goddards at Greenwich
points_of_interest.description: Open since 1890, London's most famous pie and mash restaurant. Enjoy the capital's traditional meal - handmade fresh every day. Footballer David Beckham is known to be a fan and makes occasional visits.

points_of_interest.name: Southbank Centre Food Market
points_of_interest.description: Dozens of market stalls selling fresh food. Each trader at this market is required to produce both ethical and sustainable products.

points_of_interest.name: Carnevale
points_of_interest.description: Small vegetarian restaurant with integral deli.

points_of_interest.name: Brick Lane Beigel Bake
points_of_interest.description: A local institution, Beigel Bake is more celebrated of the two and rated by some as the freshest most delicious beigel you will ever have. Their salt beef is more highly rated than Beigel Shop and a salt beef beigel with mustard and pickle is highly recommended for a post-clubbing snack.

points_of_interest.name: The River Café
points_of_interest.description: Classy Italian and modern gourmet cuisine at Rainville Rd, Fulham, (not to be confused with the cafe at Craven Cottage which is open non-matchdays and nice for a quick bite or afternoon tea). A 3-course meal will set you back from £60-100, with lovely views of the Thames, you can often glimpse a celeb or two dining here.

points_of_interest.name: Hard Rock Cafe
points_of_interest.description: The original cafe that spawned a global franchise, established in 1971. The food and drinks - burgers, fries and cocktails - are certainly overpriced, but the real stars are the memorabilia items: Elvis Presley's coat, John Lennon's glasses, an antique chair owned by Freddie Mercury, and more famous guitars than Guns 'n' Roses has had members.

points_of_interest.name: Maison Bertaux
points_of_interest.description: Slightly tatty but utterly and deliciously French, since 1871. Take away or sit at one of their sidewalk tables.

points_of_interest.name: Sutton and Sons
points_of_interest.description: Fish and chips to eat in or take away. Offers an excellent vegan menu including "fish" made from banana blossom. In addition to the flagship restaurant in Stoke Newington, has two branches at 218 Graham Rd in Hackney Central and 356 Essex Rd in Islington.

points_of_interest.name: Siam Central
points_of_interest.description: A Thai restaurant

points_of_interest.name: Tide Tables
points_of_interest.description: Vegetarian cafe in a great location with a large outdoor area overlooking the river and towpath. It does very good fairtrade coffee, juices etc and vegetarian food such as foccacia and quiches. Licensed.
points_of_interest.address: Richmond Bridge, Richmond upon Thames, Richmond, TW10 6TS, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Blue Nile
points_of_interest.description: Eritrean-Italian café and restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Lower Marsh Street
points_of_interest.description: Lower Marsh Street has diverse food stalls, including Korean, Cuban, Nigerian, Peruvian and Ethiopian cuisines.
points_of_interest.address: 111 Lower Marsh, Lambeth, London, SE1 7AE, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Green
points_of_interest.description: Easygoing gastro-pub with good quality, reasonably priced lunch menu, and tapas in the evening.

points_of_interest.name: Britain's First & Best Beigel Shop
points_of_interest.description: While less celebrated than its near neighbour, Beigel Shop is still well worth a visit. While Beigel Bake is a local institution, it is reflected in its limited range. As a result, Beigel Shop works harder for your cash, providing a wider range of fillings and an excellent sausage roll, making it the preferred destination for those who aren't enamoured with salt beef.

points_of_interest.name: Harwood Arms
points_of_interest.description: London's first Michelin-starred pub. The 3-course menu runs £50 per person, but that is value for money.

points_of_interest.name: Grazing Goat
points_of_interest.description: Lively pub with cafe, restaurant on first floor, and 8 rooms up lots of steps.

points_of_interest.name: Patisserie Valerie
points_of_interest.description: The original location of this very successful business (locally nicknamed as "Pat Vals") which has expanded across London with numerous outlets now around the West End. Wonderful French cakes and pastries. Breakfast here is notably good. Has a large seating area upstairs.

points_of_interest.name: Black Cat Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Independent vegan café.

points_of_interest.name: Al Boccon di'vino
points_of_interest.description: An Italian restaurant with no menu. The chef brings out dishes that he wants to cook.
points_of_interest.address: 14 Red Lion Street, Richmond upon Thames, Richmond, TW9 1RW, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Zaibatsu
points_of_interest.description: Japanese fusion restaurant. Food more impressive than the basic decor. You can bring your own alcohol.

points_of_interest.name: Marie's Cafe
points_of_interest.description: A favourite with locals, don't be put off by the shabby exterior of this greasy spoon/Thai cafe hybrid. The Thai menu is authentic and very tasty and service is quick. Very close to the Old Vic and around 10 minutes walk from the Southbank Centre.

points_of_interest.name: Isolabella
points_of_interest.description: Italian restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: New Tayyabs
points_of_interest.description: Long established and arguably the best South Asian restaurant in the Whitechapel area. Serves traditional food in a pleasant if slightly frenetic atmosphere. Good value and fast efficient service. Particularly recommended are the mixed grills to share and the delicious mango or banana lassi drinks which are similar to milkshakes. Book or arrive early on Friday or Saturday as the restaurant is so popular you may have to queue.

points_of_interest.name: The Wolseley

points_of_interest.name: The Laughing Halibut
points_of_interest.description: The classic shop for fish and chips.

points_of_interest.name: Scoop
points_of_interest.description: Natural Luxury Gelato This place is popular among the university students in London. Come here for some genuine Italian gelato or coffee and cake. Try their hazelnut gelato, which is simply amazing.

points_of_interest.name: Lazio
points_of_interest.description: Italian cuisine

points_of_interest.name: Newens {{!}} The Original Maids of Honour
points_of_interest.description: Traditional bakery and tea shop, famous for its Maids of Honour cakes, which has been established for over 150 years.

points_of_interest.name: TAS Pide
points_of_interest.description: Delightful Turkish restaurant specialising in "pide", boat-shaped flatbreads. Plenty of vegetarian options. Sample the free Turkish delights at the front desk.

Unless you are an avid star-gazer, go at a time when celebs are unlikely to be around.

Steaks and chops are superb. Favoured by lots of celebs and booking essential, especially pre- and post theatre.

points_of_interest.name: HOP Vietnamese

points_of_interest.name: Rules
points_of_interest.description: Claims to the oldest restaurant still-going in London dating back to 1798. It's high-class decor matches its posh diners. Rules has a dress code: "jacket or tie not required, but smart casual preferred. No shorts."

points_of_interest.name: The Orange
points_of_interest.description: Modern gastropub, you can eat in the ground-floor bar but the best dining is in the first-floor restaurant. With four comfy en suite bedrooms.

points_of_interest.name: Pilpel
points_of_interest.description: A falafel restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Quaglinos

points_of_interest.name: Eataly London
points_of_interest.description: An Italian food hall and eatery opened in 2021 along the lines of the Turin original. It's east side of Liverpool St station.

points_of_interest.name: Zizzi

Pizzas between £12 - £16, and various pasta dishes and salads. Fairly large portions, so one main dish per person suffices for a meal. Suitable for families with kids.

points_of_interest.name: Polo Bar
points_of_interest.description: An unpretentious cafe serving fried breakfasts and similar basic food 24 hr a day, and a great place for a late snack after you leave the Eat & Drink. Liverpool St is a safe area anyway but you cannot get safer than this for a late night meal, as at night you'll often see police from the nearby City of London police station. There are no toilets, however, so you need to use those at nearby Liverpool St Station.

points_of_interest.name: The Cinnamon Club
points_of_interest.description: Indian restaurant. Housed in a converted Grade II listed library.

points_of_interest.name: Simpson's Tavern
points_of_interest.description: A traditional old style English eatery which has been in business here since 1757. Most of the food is cooked on an open grill in the corner. A very City of London experience!

points_of_interest.name: Hunan
points_of_interest.description: Chinese restaurant with no menu. Diners tell the staff what they don't like and how spicy they want it; the kitchen prepares a range of dishes to match. The food comes in a long series of tiny portions.

points_of_interest.name: Wiltons
points_of_interest.description: Oyster bar, game and seafood restaurant. Traditional fine English dining in a restaurant established in 1742.

points_of_interest.name: Comptoir Gascon
points_of_interest.description: '''Temporarily closed as of May 2022'''. French restaurant and delicatessen.

points_of_interest.name: Smiths of Smithfield
points_of_interest.description: Smiths of Smithfield is a Grade II listed four-floor restaurant serving great British food., Grade II listed four-floor restaurant in Smithfield Market.

points_of_interest.name: Wood Street Bar and Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Real ale, nice food and a relaxed atmosphere.

points_of_interest.name: Apulia
points_of_interest.description: Italian restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: To A Tea
points_of_interest.description: Tearoom.

points_of_interest.name: Boisdale of Bishopsgate

points_of_interest.name: La Delizia 1986
points_of_interest.description: Quaint Italian bistro offers 18 different pizzas, three risottos, various pasta dishes, gnocchi and other traditional Italian entrees. It’s top-notch food at a great value.

points_of_interest.name: Club Gascon
points_of_interest.description: Fine French dining at this Michelin-starred restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Comptoir Libanais South Kensington
points_of_interest.description: Delicious Lebanese food, served without fuss, and fairly promptly considering the crowds. Wide range of vegetarian choices. The pretty, colourful dining room includes several long tables, where you will be seated next to other diners. Part of a moderate-sized chain across London, and beyond.

points_of_interest.name: Duck and Waffle
points_of_interest.description: All day dining on the 40th floor of the Heron Tower. Popular in the very late night for a bite after going out and waiting to watch the sunrise over the rest of London.

points_of_interest.name: Côte Brasserie
points_of_interest.description: Modern restaurant/bar at the '''Sloane Square Hotel''' serving French cuisine. Popular lunch place for people working in the area.

points_of_interest.name: Angler
points_of_interest.description: One Michelin-starred British seafood restaurant with views over the City.
points_of_interest.hours: W 6PM-9:30PM; Th F noon-2:30PM, 6PM-9:30PM; Sa noon-3PM, 6PM-9:30PM; Su noon-3PM

points_of_interest.name: Da Mario
points_of_interest.description: Popular family-run ristorante with great pizzas and Italian dishes. Come early or get on the waiting list or book in advance.

points_of_interest.name: Café and Terrace at Harvey Nichols
points_of_interest.description: Fifth Floor Café The aptly name café on the fifth floor of '''Harvey Nichols'''. A roof terrace gives a view of the rooftops of Knightsbridge.

points_of_interest.name: Great India Tandoori
points_of_interest.description: One of Chelsea's most popular restaurants. Established by Satir Ahmed in 1960.

points_of_interest.name: Kensington Creperie
points_of_interest.description: Cafe Creperie A small, cute, often crowded cafe and authentic French creperie, popular with the local French and various other South Ken expats. Given its location near the tube, it is a fine place to sit outside and watch the fashionable young people pass by.

points_of_interest.name: Gordon Ramsay
points_of_interest.description: The original, flagship branch of the Ramsay empire. You are highly unlikely to find the man himself behind the stove these days, but this triple Michelin-starred eatery deserves its reputation as one of the finest on the planet. The lunch menu is just about affordable, but getting a reservation is problematic. Dress code applies.
points_of_interest.hours: Lunch M-F noon–2:30PM, dinner: M-F 6:30PM-11:30PM, closed weekends

points_of_interest.name: Lord's Cricket Ground
points_of_interest.description: The home of cricket, Lord's usually hosts two international five-day Test matches each summer (which sell out), as well as limited-overs One Day International and Twenty20 cricket. It's the usual stadium for Middlesex County Cricket Club, who were relegated in 2023 and now play in Division Two of the County Championship - these games last 3-4 days. Also here are London Spirit men's and women's teams playing in The Hundred short game. Lord's houses the Marylebone Cricket Club Museum, with a vast collection of cricket memorabilia - tours are usually available daily except on match days.

points_of_interest.name: Dominion Theatre
points_of_interest.description: A large London theatre that tends to show mainstream blockbuster-type musical productions., Home of Queen musical ''We Will Rock You''.

points_of_interest.name: Queens Ice and Bowl
points_of_interest.description: Queens is an entertainment centre with 50,000 sq ft of activities including ice skating, 12 lanes of ten pin bowling, karaoke rooms, bar, food and video games.

points_of_interest.name: London Palladium
points_of_interest.description: Famous old London music hall whose boards have been trodden by many legendary names. These days it shows mostly blockbuster musical productions for the masses.

points_of_interest.name: London Underground Tours
points_of_interest.description: Guided tours that cover the tube's 150-year-history in two hours, including its construction, design and social history. Meet at the Sherlock Holmes Statue.
points_of_interest.address: 8 Marylebone Road, Westminster, London, NW1 5LD, United Kingdom
points_of_interest.hours: W, Th, F, Sa (and bank holidays): 11AM

points_of_interest.name: Wimbledon – Lawn Tennis Championships
points_of_interest.description: It is one of the four Grand Slam tennis tournaments, held each year over a two week period in late June & early July.
points_of_interest.address: The All England Lawn Tennis Club, Church Road, Wimbledon, SW19 5AE

points_of_interest.name: Cecil Sharp House
points_of_interest.description: English Folk Dancing.
points_of_interest.address: 2 Regent's Park Rd, Primrose Hill, London NW1 7AY

points_of_interest.name: Go Boat
points_of_interest.description: 8-person boat hire for self-drive journeys around London canals.

points_of_interest.name: Clapham Picturehouse
points_of_interest.description: Repertory/arthouse cinema with a very varied programme.

points_of_interest.name: Wimbledon Village Stables
points_of_interest.description: Lessons and horse riding on Wimbledon Common.

points_of_interest.name: Almeida Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Theatre with a reputation for daring and innovative productions.

points_of_interest.name: Shaw Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Theatre named after George Bernard Shaw and famous for showing high-quality non-mainstream productions.

points_of_interest.name: Paddington Central
points_of_interest.description: Sheldon Square Checkout constantly changing events at the Paddington Central development with the amphitheatre in Sheldon Square, or visit for the food, shopping and atmosphere.

points_of_interest.name: Electric Cinema
points_of_interest.description: A restored cinema boasting all leather armchairs (most with footstools) and a bar in the theatre - this is definitely a Notting Hill experience. The Electric shows a wide range of films from cinema classics, cult and independent films, to regular Hollywood blockbusters. They also have the ''Electric Scream'' session, specifically for parents with screaming babies! Ticket prices vary depending on how fancy your seat is. More expensive than a normal cinema but a fun experience.

points_of_interest.name: New Wimbledon Theatre
points_of_interest.description: The theatre is a Grade II Listed Edwardian theatre showing West End plays and musicals.

points_of_interest.name: Arsenal FC
points_of_interest.description: Arsenal play in the Premier League, the top tier of English football: they're one of the leading clubs and routinely qualify for European tournaments, and also hold the record for most number of consecutive seasons in the top division. Perhaps their biggest claim to fame was going through the entire 2003-04 Premier League season unbeaten on their way to the title. Their home ground is Emirates Stadium (capacity 60,000) and they play to near-capacity crowds, especially against local rivals Tottenham Hotspur. Their women's team plays in the Women's Super League, with home games at Borehamwood.

points_of_interest.name: Puppet Theatre Barge
points_of_interest.description: A floating puppet theatre on a converted barge. Varied schedule of performances.
points_of_interest.address: 36 Blomfield Road, Westminster, London, W9 2PF, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Gate Picturehouse
points_of_interest.description: Repertory/art-house cinema with a very varied programme.

points_of_interest.name: Putney Arts Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Comes recommended for anyone interested in anything to do with theatre. They run drama courses for adults and children and around eight shows a year are produced by adults and children alike. Putney Theatre company offers opportunities for anyone interested in any type of theater work from acting to writing to set design. Group 64 is the youth drama group for kids, they run weekly classes, holiday projects but also put together shows.

points_of_interest.name: Odeon Cinema
points_of_interest.description: A large modern multiplex in Central Wimbledon with 12 screens and IMAX screen.
points_of_interest.address: Odeon Wimbledon, The Piazza, The Broadway

points_of_interest.name: Everyman Screen on the Green
points_of_interest.description: formerly Screen on the Green One of the leading art house cinemas in London. Refurbished.

points_of_interest.name: Putney Leisure Centre
points_of_interest.description: All-year warm swimming pool and sauna session.

points_of_interest.name: Brixton Academy
points_of_interest.description: Live music venue for audiences as large as 4,000 in a beautiful Art Deco building. It is often considered one of the best concert halls in the world.

points_of_interest.name: Polka Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Children's theatre.
points_of_interest.hours: Telephone bookings: M 9:30AM-4:30PM, Tu-F 9:30AM-6PM, Sa 10AM-5PM; box office opening hours: Tu-F 9:30AM-4:30PM, Sa 11AM-5:30PM

points_of_interest.name: Vue Islington
points_of_interest.description: Multiplex cinema.

points_of_interest.name: Odeon Leicester Square
points_of_interest.description: Includes the Odeon Mezzanine and Odeon West End. This particular Odeon is famous for its red-carpet film premieres.

points_of_interest.name: The Palace Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Performances of ''Harry Potter and the Cursed Child''.

points_of_interest.name: The Bill Murray
points_of_interest.description: Comedy club.

points_of_interest.name: Brockwell Lido
points_of_interest.description: Outdoor swimming pool that's empty during cold days and has queues around the block whenever the sun is out.
points_of_interest.address: 56 Dulwich Road, Lambeth, London, SE24 0PA, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Union Chapel
points_of_interest.description: Voted London's Best Live Music Venue by readers of Time Out magazine in 2002, 2012 and in 2014.

points_of_interest.name: Curzon Soho Cinema
points_of_interest.description: Voted "London's Number 1 Cinema" by ''Time Out'' readers, great bar and a fantastic art-house program.

points_of_interest.name: Green Bridge
points_of_interest.description: Walk over the Green Bridge, a unique structure that joins Bow Common to Mile End Park with its urban nature reserve, taking the park over the busy A11 road, ensuring uninterrupted greenery for several miles, from the bottom of Bow Common to the top of the beautiful Victoria Park.
points_of_interest.address: 383-387 Mile End Road, Tower Hamlets, London, E3 4QS, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Curzon Mayfair
points_of_interest.description: Retro 1970s decor, a relaxing bar area and comfortable seating combine with a great art-house billing, easily one of the best cinemas in London.

points_of_interest.name: Greenwich Heritage and Meridian Tours
points_of_interest.description: Operated by the Greenwich Tour Guides Association, the original guiding organisation that has operated in Greenwich for 25 years. Walking tours take place twice a day (every day, excluding 24-26 Dec, 1 Jan and London Marathon Day). No need to book in advance, buy tickets on the day from the meeting point at the Discover Greenwich Tourist Information Centre. Runs two tours: '''The Meridian Tour''' (noon) which includes a scenic walk to the top of the hill in Greenwich Park - more energetic of the two walks but doesn't go into any attractions. '''The Greenwich Highlights Tour''' (2:15PM) which doesn't go up the hill but enters the chapel of the Royal Naval College.
points_of_interest.address: 2 Cutty Sark Gardens, Greenwich, London, SE10 9LW, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Tooting Bec Common
points_of_interest.description: A real gem, with tennis courts, football fields and plenty of open space. Sports facilities include Tooting Leisure Centre and Pool, golf, horse riding, Tooting Bec Lido (the biggest open air pool in the UK), athletic track and the nearby Streatham Ice Rink.
points_of_interest.address: Dr Johnson Avenue, Wandsworth, London, SW17 8AR, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The National Theatre
points_of_interest.description: The Royal National Theatre is one of the UK's two most prominent publicly funded theatre companies. The controversial building is "an aesthetic of broken forms" meaning a concrete monster. The riverside forecourt has outdoor performances in the summer.

points_of_interest.name: Theatre Royal Stratford East
points_of_interest.description: Watch a live performance: comedy, music and more.

points_of_interest.name: Prince Charles Cinema
points_of_interest.description: The cheapest and in some ways most interesting cinema in the area. They screen the latest films, and also have an interesting selection of foreign and art house films. They often have theme nights. Get hold of the program at the door or on the internet and consider buying the discount-granting yearly membership if you plan to come back a few times.

points_of_interest.name: Bush Hall
points_of_interest.description: Built as a dance hall, this venue now hosts regular events such as live music and burlesque performances.

points_of_interest.name: Greenwich Royal Tours
points_of_interest.description: Runs a range of more in-depth tours including Greenwich Day Tour, Greenwich Highlights Half Day Tour, Greenwich Food Tour and National Maritime Museum Tour. Tickets must be booked in advance and tours leave from outside the Greenwich Visitors Centre. Pub lunches are generally included, as is admission to attractions.
points_of_interest.address: 2 Cutty Sark Gardens, Greenwich, London, SE10 9LW, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Tooting & Mitcham United Football Club
points_of_interest.description: The 'Stripes' are a football club based at Imperial Fields. They play in BetVictor Isthmian League South Central Division and normally play their league games on Tuesday evenings and Saturday afternoons. The club has a café/bar with real ale and with big screen TV (Sky Sports) and has a gym.
points_of_interest.address: Imperial Fields, Bishopsford Rd, Mitcham, SM4 6BF

points_of_interest.name: The Old Vic
points_of_interest.description: Kevin Spacey has been the artistic director here since 2003 receiving considerable media attention and starring in a number of the shows himself. Great for something a bit different, and further up the cut you can check the Young Vic which focuses on productions of a younger generation.

points_of_interest.name: West Ham United
points_of_interest.description: "The Hammers" play soccer in the Premier League, England's top tier. Their home ground is London Stadium, capacity 60,000, in the Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park. Their women's team play in the Women's Super League, their top tier, with home games at Victoria Road (aka Chigwell Construction Stadium) in Dagenham.

points_of_interest.name: TKTS
points_of_interest.description: half-price ticket booth Tickets can only be bought in person so do not try to contact by telephone. At times, there may well be long queues, so be prepared.

points_of_interest.name: Hammersmith Apollo
points_of_interest.description: Eventim Apollo Art Deco music venue dating from 1932. It has hosted everyone from Buddy Holly to Kanye West, via the Beatles, Johnny Cash, Black Sabbath, Blondie, Queen, Kylie Minogue, and Prince. In the 21st century, it has gained a reputation for comedy, being among other things the host venue for the BBC's flagship stand-up show ''Live at the Apollo''.

points_of_interest.name: The Oval
points_of_interest.description: The Britoval, Kennington Oval The second home of English cricket in London after Lords - these Test matches sell out early. Surrey CCC play here in Division One of the County Championship and tickets are readily available. Also here are Oval Invincibles men's and women's teams playing in The Hundred short game.

points_of_interest.name: ExCeL London
points_of_interest.description: Exhibition and conference centre. The venue hosts such public events as the London Boat Show, the British Motor Show, MCM London Comic Con, the London Triathlon, Eurogamer Expo (EGX) and many others. It was a venue for the 2012 Olympics and Paralympics for sports such as boxing, table tennis, and fencing.

points_of_interest.name: Everyman Cinema
points_of_interest.description: One of London's most notable art house cinemas which offers a high quality experience. You pay for it, but the environment is very classy indeed. Has a sister cinema just down the hill in Belsize Park - The Everyman Belsize Park.

points_of_interest.name: O2 Shepherd's Bush Empire
points_of_interest.description: Built in 1903 and at the centre of the entertainment scene ever since, the Empire is one of London's premier live music venues, with an emphasis on contemporary rock and pop.

points_of_interest.name: Regent's Park Open Air Theatre
points_of_interest.description: During the summer, a perfect afternoon can be had by taking a picnic in Regent's Park followed by seeing a production at the Theatre.
points_of_interest.address: Inner Circle, Westminster, London, NW1 4NU, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Meantime Brewery Tours
points_of_interest.description: Since being founded in Greenwich in 2000, beers from the award-winning Meantime Brewery have spread across the country. Still produced in Greenwich, tours of the site are available and include a tasting session. A bar and shop on site mean that you can continue sampling beers after the tour has finished.
points_of_interest.address: Unit 4-5 Lawrence Trading Estate, Blackwall Lane SE10 0AR

points_of_interest.name: London Royal Docks
points_of_interest.description: Open water swimming in the docks operated by Love Open Water. Swimmers must have a valid NOWCA membership.
points_of_interest.address: 27 Western Gateway, Newham, London, E16 1FA, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Hampstead Theatre
points_of_interest.description: A repertory theatre that is about as far removed from glitzy west end productions as you could imagine. Dedicated to exposing new writing talent. Harold Pinter gained some of his earliest experience here.

points_of_interest.name: Kiln Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Tricyle Theatre Renowned theatre and cinema, noted for its 'reality' plays such as ''The Riots'' (2011) and ''Bloody Sunday: Scenes from the Saville Inquiry'' (2005).

points_of_interest.name: Irish Cultural Centre
points_of_interest.description: Regular performances of Irish music, film and literature, plus Irish art exhibitions.

points_of_interest.name: The O2
points_of_interest.description: The former Millennium Dome has been transformed into a major entertainment complex consisting of a large arena which plays host to a number of world class perfomers, a cinema which includes the largest screen in the UK, and numerous bars and restaurants. Tickets can be purchased in advance to join tours walking over the top of the dome, providing unique views.

points_of_interest.name: Leyton Orient F.C.
points_of_interest.description: They were promoted in 2023 and now play football in League One, the third tier. Their home ground is Brisbane Road (capacity 9200) and is shared with Tottenham Hotspur women's team.
points_of_interest.address: 75 Oliver Road, Waltham Forest, London, E10 5LG, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Pentameters Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Small, intimate theatre known for edgy, high quality productions. Located above The Horseshoe pub.

points_of_interest.name: Conway Hall
points_of_interest.description: Theatre and concert hall. Home of the National Secular Society and the South Place Ethical Society: often hosts lively debates on religion, politics and secularism.

points_of_interest.name: Mayhem Paintball
points_of_interest.description: Paintballing centre.

points_of_interest.name: Lyric Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Beautiful grand auditorium dating to 1895 hidden inside a 1970s concrete box. Hammersmith home for "serious" theatre, mixing old favourites such as Kafka and Shakespeare with premieres of original productions. Usually hosts a popular pantomime over the extended festive season.

points_of_interest.name: Richmond FC
points_of_interest.description: They play rugby union; they were relegated in 2023 and now play in National League 1, the third tier. They play at the athletic grounds half a mile south of Kew Gardens.
points_of_interest.address: 22 Kew Foot Road, Richmond upon Thames, Richmond, TW9 2SS, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Trinity Laban Conservatoire of Music and Dance
points_of_interest.description: An internationally renowned school for music and dance training based in the Old Royal Naval College and a contemporary site by Deptford Creek. Put on musical and dance performances across Greenwich throughout the year - many of them free.
points_of_interest.address: 8 Straightsmouth, Greenwich, London, SE10 9LB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Chocolate Factory
points_of_interest.description: Converted sweets factory now used by local artists; there are regular shows and events here. The annual Open Studios is on the second weekend in November.

points_of_interest.name: Gillian Lynne Theatre
points_of_interest.description: New London Theatre

points_of_interest.name: Mudchute Park and Farm
points_of_interest.description: Mudchute City Farm City farm with a shop and a café.
points_of_interest.address: The Globe Rope Walk, Tower Hamlets, London, E14 3BG, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Bush Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Home of the Alternative Theatre Company, it's dedicated to breaking new plays and new writers.

points_of_interest.name: Hackney Empire
points_of_interest.description: Historic theatre and music hall, offering an eclectic mix of entertainment.

points_of_interest.name: St. Alfege Church
points_of_interest.description: A beautiful Baroque church designed by Nicholas Hawksmoor (and is rumoured to have links with Occultists, Freemasons and such-like). Hosts classical music concerts and organ recitals. Its Christmas choir is enjoyable also.

points_of_interest.name: Cinemas
points_of_interest.description: There are two cinemas on this road, a Vue and a Cineworld.

points_of_interest.name: Noel Coward Theatre
points_of_interest.description: The Albery

points_of_interest.name: London School of Economics
points_of_interest.description: LSE hosts a prestigious public lectures programme, which is nearly always free to attend, but may require a ticket in advance for a lecture by a Head of State or Nobel Prize winner.
points_of_interest.address: Conference and Events Office, Houghton St, WC2A 2AE

points_of_interest.name: Shoreditch Street Art Tour
points_of_interest.description: A tour of the constantly changing street art around this part of the East End. Saturday times may vary.

points_of_interest.name: Riverside Studios
points_of_interest.description: Riverside Studios is a production studio, theatre and independent cinema on the banks of the River Thames in Hammersmith.

points_of_interest.name: Greenwich Picturehouse
points_of_interest.description: Tends to show art-house films.

points_of_interest.name: Novello Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Home of ''Mamma Mia'' since 1999.

points_of_interest.name: Peacock Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Owned by LSE, and part of their campus, this theatre is leased to Sadler's Wells as "Sadler's Wells in the West End".

points_of_interest.name: Vue Cinema Fulham Broadway
points_of_interest.description: Modern multiplex showing the latest mainstream films.
points_of_interest.address: Fulham Broadway Shopping Centre, Fulham Rd, SW6 1BW

points_of_interest.name: London Fields Lido
points_of_interest.description: Lovely old-fashioned outdoor swimming Lido with a 50-metre pool run by Better.

points_of_interest.name: Birkbeck Institute for the Moving Image
points_of_interest.description: BIMI Cinema owned by Birkbeck, University of London, featuring screenings and lectures. Most events are free but pre-booking is advised.
points_of_interest.address: 43 Gordon Sq, Birkbeck, University of London, WC1H 0PD

points_of_interest.name: Curzon Cinema
points_of_interest.description: Arthouse cinema.

points_of_interest.name: Odeon
points_of_interest.description: The large Odeon multiplex has 18-screens, but is a bit out-of-the way, at Bugsby Way, on the way to the O2 Arena.

points_of_interest.name: London Broncos
points_of_interest.description: They were relegated in 2024 and play in the Championship, the 13-a-side game's second tier, with a playing season Feb-Oct. Their home ground is Ealing Trailfinders Sports Club, capacity 4000.

points_of_interest.name: Sadler's Wells Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Leading dance production theatre with an amazing history back to the 1690s. Everything from classical ballet to hip hop. For ballet fans, you have often got a much better chance of securing a ticket here than in the Covent Garden venues. Also attached is the Lilian Baylis Theatre, primarily performances by students.

points_of_interest.name: Vue Cinema Westfield
points_of_interest.description: Modern multiplex at the top of the Westfield London mall that shows the latest mainstream films.
points_of_interest.address: Westfield Shopping Town, White City, W12 7GF

points_of_interest.name: Rio Cinema
points_of_interest.description: A splendid old cinema dating back to the 1900s. Specialises in foreign language films, offbeat arthouse productions and children's programming.

points_of_interest.name: Bloomsbury Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Theatre owned by University College London staging both student and professional productions. Broad range of performances.

points_of_interest.name: Orange Tree Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Offers ''theatre in the round'', where the audience surrounds the stage.

points_of_interest.name: Tottenham Hotspur
points_of_interest.description: New White Hart Lane Spurs play soccer in the Premier League, England's top tier. Their new ground on the site of the former White Hart Lane stadium opened in 2019, capacity of 62,000: see club website for stadium tours. Matches with local rivals Arsenal tend to attract the most attention from fans. This has two pitches - a retractable grass pitch for Spurs games, and an artificial pitch for American football games - the National Football League occasionally plays here. Spurs women's team play in the Women's Super League, their top tier, with home games at The Hive, shared with Barnet FC.

points_of_interest.name: The Hippodrome Casino
points_of_interest.description: A former theatre, now home to a large casino with live cabaret shows and a steakhouse restaurant. Also sells souvenirs, poker chips and plaque keyrings that can be purchased from the cashier. If you stay here long have a look at the Hippodrome Rewards card.

points_of_interest.name: Chelsea FC
points_of_interest.description: Despite the name, this club is actually in Fulham. Chelsea plays soccer in the Premier League, England's top tier, and usually qualifies for European tournaments. Stamford Bridge stadium (capacity 41,000, and not to be confused with the 1066 battlefield near York) has tours on non-matchdays. It's among the best-supported teams in the country, so buy tickets early. The club plans to rebuild the stadium in 2023/24. The women's team play in the Women's Super League, their top tier, with home games at Kingsmeadow in Kingston upon Thames.

points_of_interest.name: Richmond Theatre
points_of_interest.description: See a pre-West End play at this pretty Victorian theatre.

points_of_interest.name: Up The Creek Comedy Club
points_of_interest.description: Comedy club. Hosts hilarious stand-up as well as music nights.

points_of_interest.name: Fulham FC
points_of_interest.description: Fulham was promoted in 2022, so they play soccer in the Premier League, the top tier. Tours of their quirky old stadium (capacity 25,000) on non-matchdays are fun.

points_of_interest.name: The Castle Cinema
points_of_interest.description: Independent cinema with two screens, and an art deco bar.

points_of_interest.name: London Mathematical Society
points_of_interest.description: Based on Russell Square, they give lectures and exhibitions, for those numerically inclined.
points_of_interest.address: De Morgan House, 57-58 Russell Square, WC1B 4HS

points_of_interest.name: Ham Polo Club
points_of_interest.description: Selected Friday nights and weekends during the summer
points_of_interest.address: 44 Meadlands Drive, Richmond upon Thames, Richmond, TW10 7EE, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Blackheath Halls
points_of_interest.description: Concert Hall

points_of_interest.name: Drumsheds
points_of_interest.description: Nightclub in a former IKEA store.
points_of_interest.address: 6 Glover Drive, London, N18 3HF, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Ealing Comedy Festival
points_of_interest.description: Ealing hosts an annual comedy festival in the summer. Speaking of comedy in Ealing, in the late 1940s and 1950s Ealing was famous for a series of comedy movies filmed there.

points_of_interest.name: Queen's Park Rangers FC
points_of_interest.description: QPR plays in the Championship, the second tier of English football. Loftus Road stadium (capacity 18,000) is a quarter mile west of White City or Wood Lane Underground stations.
points_of_interest.address: Loftus Rd Stadium, South Africa Rd, W12 7PJ

points_of_interest.name: Arcola Theatre
points_of_interest.address: 20 Arcola Street, Hackney, London, E8 2DJ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Renoir
points_of_interest.description: Cinema showing arthouse and foreign language films.

points_of_interest.name: Ham & Petersham Rifle & Pistol Club
points_of_interest.description: Guest mornings on selected Sundays,

points_of_interest.name: Blackheath Heath Fireworks Display
points_of_interest.description: Every Guy Fawkes night (5th of November) Lewisham council put on a spectacular free fireworks display. In the past few years crowds of over 100,000 have amassed, so arrive early to secure a good spot. The heath also hosts funfairs and circus at various times of the year.
points_of_interest.address: 10 Duke Humphrey Road, Lewisham, London, SE3 0TY, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Finsbury Park
points_of_interest.description: One of North London's green lungs - boating on the lake, start a walk of Parkland Walk to Highgate along the route one of London's former railway lines.
points_of_interest.address: 3 Endymion Road, Haringey, London, N4 1EE, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: St Martin's Theatre
points_of_interest.description: The theatre which has been showing Agatha Christie's ''The Mousetrap'' continuously since 1952!

points_of_interest.name: Questors
points_of_interest.description: The cinema is under reconstruction, said to include over 10 screens!

points_of_interest.name: Olympia London
points_of_interest.description: An exhibition centre hosting a diverse range of conventions, fairs and events. Olympia has four halls and a conference centre, with a mix of trade shows and public events, so there is almost always something to see. Times and prices vary. The grand hall, with its cavernous Victorian arched iron-and-glass roof, has hosted many historical events: the first world scout jamboree in 1920; the first – and last – mass rally of British fascists in 1934 which ended in rioting; and "Christmas on Earth 1967", a psychedelic rock concert which, despite boasting an insane lineup (Pink Floyd, The Jimi Hendrix Experience, The Who...), almost failed to attract a single audience member due to ineffective publicity.

points_of_interest.name: Cafe Oto
points_of_interest.description: Intimate venue hosting free jazz, experimental and free improvisation performances.

points_of_interest.name: Greenwich Tall Ships Festival
points_of_interest.description: Sail Royal Greenwich Annual festival held at the start of July. Tall sailing ships cruise down the Thames from Woolwich, with Greenwich town centre being a fantasic place to view them. Each evening of the festival concludes with a spectacular fireworks display on the river. Packages can be bought for trips aboard the ships.
points_of_interest.address: 3 Welland Street, London, SE10 9ED, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Watermans Arts Centre
points_of_interest.description: The Watermans Centre is one of West London's finest arts and cultural venues. Watermans is especially noted for its promotion of Asian arts, particularly in the fields of visual arts, theatre and comedy. It also houses a leading independent cinema, gallery spaces and a noted Indian restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: MOTH Club
points_of_interest.description: Intimate venue hosting live music, club nights and comedy.

points_of_interest.name: London Marathon
points_of_interest.description: The London Marathon takes place annually, usually on the last Sunday of April. For both wheelchair racers and runners (elite, club and fun - many in fancy dress), it starts from the south side of Greenwich Park, on the common at Blackheath, then routes eastwards towards Charlton and Woolwich before turning west through Greenwich, past the Old Royal Naval College and Maritime Museum, and doing a loop around the Cutty Sark before heading off towards Deptford. Roads are closed. Many pubs and cafes open early, some with live music, serving spectators who line the route to cheer participants along.
points_of_interest.address: 18 Dinsdale Road, Greenwich, London, SE3 7RL, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Brentford FC
points_of_interest.description: "The Bees" play soccer in the Premier League, the game's top tier. They play at Brentford Community Stadium, capacity of 17,250. In 2022 the stadium hosted games in the UEFA Women's Euro Finals, postponed from 2021.
points_of_interest.address: Brentford Community Stadium, 166 Lionel Road North TW8 9QT

points_of_interest.name: Churchill Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Offers a range of theatrical performances, including touring productions, performances by (very good) local amateur groups, and pantomime during the Christmas and New Year period (usually starring somebody who used to be in Neighbours). '''[http://www.bromleylittletheatre.org/ Bromley Little Theatre]''' is close to the North Station. Bromley also has a medium-sized Odeon cinema.
points_of_interest.address: 110 High Street, Bromley, BR1 1HG, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Hackney Picturehouse
points_of_interest.description: Cinema with six screens, and a bar serving food. Has accessible screenings, accommodating those with autism or dementia, and sometimes puts on dog friendly screenings.

points_of_interest.name: Charlton Athletic FC
points_of_interest.description: They play soccer in League One, England's third tier. The women's team play in the Championship, their second tier, at Bexleyheath in Dartford.

points_of_interest.name: Quaser
points_of_interest.description: a laser-tag arena, which is good fun for the kids or a rainy afternoon.

points_of_interest.name: NG1 Golf
points_of_interest.description: Urban driving range against the spectacular backdrop of Canary Wharf. Restaurant and bar on site. 18 years + age policy after 6PM.

points_of_interest.name: Royal Opera House
points_of_interest.description: One of the world's ''great'' opera and ballet venues. Peak time tickets are like gold dust and it is very unlikely that a casual visitor will be able to obtain one. However, at least 65 tickets per performance are held off for on-the-day in person sales from 10AM, and tickets are sometimes available for off peak (especially matinee) performances and can be surprisingly affordable. Check the website or at London ticket agencies. Whilst there's no formal dress code for attending a performance, dressing smartly is advised.
