Casual styles (jeans, trainers) may get you disapproving looks from other attendees.

points_of_interest.name: Crystal Palace FC
points_of_interest.description: Palace play soccer in the Premier League, the top tier in England. Their stadium is Selhurst Park, capacity 26,309 (all seated), where it has been based since 1924.
points_of_interest.address: Selhurst Park Stadium, Whitehorse Lane, SE25 6PU

points_of_interest.name: Bunker 51 laser tag and paintball
points_of_interest.description: Let off some steam for a couple of hours with laser tag or paintball at an underground Cold War themed bunker in part of industrial Greenwich. Great for kids (or just your inner-kid!). Next to the Thames Barrier - which keeps the city safe from flooding - be sure to go and take a look at this giant structure in the river whilst you're here.

points_of_interest.name: Old Vic Theatre
points_of_interest.description: One of the oldest theatres in London, once under the artistic direction of Kevin Spacey.

points_of_interest.name: English National Opera
points_of_interest.description: A little easier to get tickets here than it is at the Royal Opera House but still difficult for the most notable productions. Look for last minute availability and off peak performances.
points_of_interest.address: London Coliseum, St. Martin's Lane, WC2N 4ES

points_of_interest.name: Walk the Thames Path
points_of_interest.description: Greenwich is home to the last 4 miles (6.4 km) of the 184-mile-long Thames Path, organised by National Trails. From Cutty Sark, the path follows the river up and around the Greenwich Peninsula before ending at the Thames Barrier. The trail affords great views of Canary Wharf and passes sights including the Old Royal Naval College, the O2 Arena and the Greenwich Peninsula Ecology Park while passing some fantastic pubs for drinks or lunch along the way. '''End point''' The path's end point at the Thames Barrier has an information centre about the structure and a cafe (Th-Su 11AM-3:30PM; closed M Tu W). To get back to North Greenwich station, take bus route 472 or 161 - a ten-minute walk away. The 117 or 118 bus route will return you to Greenwich town centre. '''Alternative route''' The last 2 miles of the walk pass through more industrial areas, which are quite interesting in themselves, but some visitors might prefer to end the walk at the O2 Arena or by Emirates Air Line cable-car, both of which are close to North Greenwich tube station.
points_of_interest.address: 3 Welland Street, Greenwich, London, SE10 9ED, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Shakespeare's Globe
points_of_interest.description: Sam Wanamaker's largely authentic reconstruction of Shakespeare's Globe Theatre, built using traditional techniques, stages plays in the summer months. Around the year, there is an exhibition ending with either a tour of the theatre (in winter, and mornings in the summer), or a virtual tour (summer afternoons). Tickets for plays are often available on the day, particularly if you are prepared to stand in the yard.

points_of_interest.name: Surrey County Cricket Club
points_of_interest.description: Surrey County C.C is one of the 18 professional county clubs which make up the English domestic cricket structure. They play four home games away from the Oval (Kennington, Lambeth/South London) each season. Two of these games are played at the Whitgift School, the other two games are played in Guildford.
points_of_interest.address: Whitgift School, Haling Park, South Croydon, CR2 6YT

points_of_interest.name: Young Vic Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Fab theatre on The Cut which is home to younger theatre artists, especially directors. Presents plays for audiences of all ages and backgrounds. Lively bar and restaurant too.

points_of_interest.name: Changing of the Guard
points_of_interest.description: Each morning between May and July at 11:30AM the guard changes outside Buckingham Palace. The rest of the year, the guard changes on alternate days, weather permitting. A board is placed outside the palace in the morning to say whether the Changing of the Guard ceremony will take place or not. There is no charge to view the Changing of the Guard—simply turn up and stand at the fence in front of the Palace, but it is worth getting there early to ensure a good view, particularly when the weather is fine.
points_of_interest.hours: May-Jul 11:30AM daily; for other times, see website

points_of_interest.name: BRIT School
points_of_interest.description: Performing Arts and Technology school owned by the BRIT Trust (known for the BRIT Awards).
points_of_interest.address: 60 The Crescent, Croydon, CR0 2HN, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Trooping the Colour
points_of_interest.description: The King's Birthday Parade A ceremony performed by regiments of the British and Commonwealth armies to mark the official birthday of the King. The King travels by carriage down The Mall from Buckingham Palace to Horse Guards Parade, where he inspects the troops and then entire Household Division performs a march past the King as he receives their salute. Tickets to Horse Guards Parade are awarded by ballot but the parade along the rest of the route can be watched for free. Up to three tickets can be requested by sending a letter (this is by post only), enclosing a self-addressed envelope, to the Brigade Major of the Headquarters Household Division, in January or February; these will be entered into the ballot and those chosen will be sent offer letters which contain payment details. Those without a ticket can get their best view by standing on The Mall, along the edge of the parade, or on the edge of St James's Park by Horse Guards Parade. Arriving before 09:00 is recommended.
points_of_interest.hours: Held annually on a Saturday in June, beginning around 10AM

points_of_interest.name: Croydon Grants
points_of_interest.description: Entertainment Venue. Includes a large 11-screen Vue Cinema, The Milan Bar (a Wetherspoons chain pub), Reflex 80s Bar and Disco, Nando's and Tiger Tiger restaurant and nightclub.
points_of_interest.address: 16 High Street, Croydon, CR0 1GT, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Florence Nightingale Museum
points_of_interest.description: Tells the story of the Lady with the Lamp. Various family events, including art workshops. In the grounds of St. Thomas' Hospital.
points_of_interest.address: St Thomas' Hospital, Westminster Bridge Rd

points_of_interest.name: Menier Chocolate Factory
points_of_interest.description: Restaurant, theatre, gallery and bar.

points_of_interest.name: Namco Funscape
points_of_interest.description: Entertainment centre including an amusement arcade, bowling alleys, ping pong tables, pool tables and bumper cars.
points_of_interest.address: County Hall, Westminster Bridge Rd, SE1 7PB

points_of_interest.name: Chessington World of Adventures
points_of_interest.description: Theme park, zoo and sea-life centre.

points_of_interest.name: Cineworld Haymarket
points_of_interest.description: Slightly off the main area for cinemas and entertainment around Leicester Square and Theatreland this cinema offers projections of recent movies on three large screens.

points_of_interest.name: Vue Piccadilly
points_of_interest.description: Multi screen of the Vue network very close to Piccadilly Circus.

points_of_interest.name: AFC Wimbledon
points_of_interest.description: Founded in 2002 by former fans of Wimbledon F.C. when that club received approval to move from London to Milton Keynes, where the club is now known as Milton Keynes Dons. After a series of promotions in the following years, AFC Wimbledon are now in Football League Two, the fourth tier of England's professional club system.
points_of_interest.address: Kingsmeadow, Kingston Rd, Kingston upon Thames, KT1 3PB

points_of_interest.name: Trafalgar Studios
points_of_interest.description: Whitehall Theatre

points_of_interest.name: St John's Smith Square
points_of_interest.description: SJSS Former baroque church by Thomas Archer. From the 1960s, converted into a concert hall and featuring world class classical music performers with daily concerts from September to July.
points_of_interest.address: St John's Smith Square, London, SW1P 3HA

points_of_interest.name: London Night Tour
points_of_interest.address: Departing from Coach stop 3, Bulleid Way

points_of_interest.name: Boating on the Serpentine
points_of_interest.description: Blue Bird Boats Rowing boats and pedalos available for hire. Alternatively, you can go on a (very short) 'cruise' on the solar shuttle, a silent boat powered entirely by the rays of the mighty London sun.
points_of_interest.hours: Easter-Halloween daily 10AM-dusk, solar shuttle every 30 min noon-dusk

points_of_interest.name: Swimming in the Serpentine
points_of_interest.description: Serpentine Lido Famous swimming club in Hyde Park's lake. The winter months are members-only (hardy club members traditionally take part in a swim on Christmas Day), but during the summer months the lido is open to the general public. A concrete 'beach' area, sun loungers, a kiddies' paddling pool and café are also on-site.
points_of_interest.address: Serpentine Road, Westminster, London, W2 2UH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Hyde Park Tennis and Sports Centre
points_of_interest.description: Contains six hard tennis courts, two mini tennis courts, a six-rink lawn bowling green and a nine-hole putting green; plus support facilities such as changing rooms and a café. Bowling greens, tennis courts and nearby football pitches can be booked. Putting is mostly drop-in only (as is some tennis). Some equipment can be rented from the sports centre.
points_of_interest.hours: Times vary by month and area; generally open in daylight hours

points_of_interest.name: Gresham College
points_of_interest.description: Founded in 1597 as London's alternative higher education institution to Oxford and Cambridge, Gresham College continues to provide free public lectures every week during term time. Most lectures require no booking, with wonderful speakers delivering lectures on a wide range of interesting topics.

points_of_interest.name: Institut Français du Royaume-Uni
points_of_interest.description: The first in a worldwide network of institutes to promote and present the best of French culture. The site includes a café-restaurant, a cinema showing French films, the largest French library in the UK and a French language centre, and runs other events. Set in a Kensington block that also includes the French consulate and a French school.
points_of_interest.hours: M–F 9AM–11PM; Sa 10AM-11PM; Su depends on events

points_of_interest.name: Ciné Lumière
points_of_interest.description: Watch French-language movies in the Institute's cinema.

points_of_interest.name: Language Centre
points_of_interest.description: Learn French or take courses on French culture from France's official teaching centre in the UK. Intensive courses can be completed in just two weeks, general courses are closer to 10–15 weeks.

points_of_interest.name: La Médiathèque
points_of_interest.description: The largest French library in the UK. Read and borrow French books from the library. Non-members are free to browse; members can borrow books.

points_of_interest.name: London Cru
points_of_interest.description: Urban winery based in West London run by a team of experts that include international winemaker Gavin Monery and Master of Wine student Mark Andrew. The winery offers public tours, wine tastings, courses, and custom winemaking.

points_of_interest.name: Royal Albert Hall
points_of_interest.description: Since opening in 1871 as part of Queen Victoria's memorial to her late husband it has become one of the most famous venues in the UK, and remains one of London's main concert halls. It still mainly caters for a classical audience, but it also hosts many other varied events including the odd contemporary rock/pop acts, and its corridors are sometimes used as exhibition spaces. During July–September the Albert Hall hosts the '''BBC Proms'''. This British national institution is a series of nightly classical concerts with world-leading performers for which standing tickets can be bought on the door on the night for as little as £5.

points_of_interest.name: Royal Court Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Britain's leading national theatre company dedicated to new work by innovative writers from the UK and around the world.

points_of_interest.name: The Troubadour
points_of_interest.description: Famous bohemian cafe with a pleasing menu of hearty dishes such as fishcakes, burgers and delicious filling salads. Good wine list too and lovely leafy garden out the back. There is a great little music venue downstairs and even accommodation on the top floor. As a music venue, the Troubadour has been programming acoustic music since the 1950s when Bob Dylan et al took to the stage. It's bigger now and has gone electric but is still one of the best venues in London for up and coming talent. The musical spectrum is broad. On any night you might catch solo singer-songwriters or full bands. No heavy rock or covers bands though. Amongst the acts hosted have been, Adele, Laura Marlin, Jamie T and The Kleeks. There is a good menu too but arrive early to get a table. It can get very busy. Well worth a visit.

points_of_interest.name: Fulham Road Picturehouse
points_of_interest.description: Trendy and reasonably priced 3-screen art deco cinema which shows mainstream and independent films. Also shows a lot of classics.

points_of_interest.name: The Ronson Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Science Museum IMAX Cinema IMAX cinema screen at the Science Museum showing documentary films and blockbusters.
points_of_interest.address: Armstrong Road, Kensington and Chelsea, London, SW7 2DD, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Cutty Sark
points_of_interest.description: A preserved tea and wool clipper built in 1869 which set the record for passage from Australia under sail. The ship was damaged by fire on 21 May 2007, but much of the ship's structure and rigging had already been removed as a conservation and renovation project had been underway since 2006. The site reopened in 2012 with changes to the display of the ship including raising the entire vessel so that now visitors can walk underneath.

points_of_interest.name: Garden Museum
points_of_interest.description: The first museum in the world dedicated to the history of gardening, based in the deconsecrated Church of St Mary-at-Lambeth. The exhibits cover everything from royal gardens to allotments.

points_of_interest.name: Holland Park
points_of_interest.description: Originally the private garden of Holland House, much of which was destroyed in the London Blitz, Holland Park is a mixture of woodland, European and Japanese-style formal gardens and leisure facilities. It includes a large field dedicated to football and cricket, as well as tennis courts. As you walk around the park, you can see bits of the house dotted around the place which give you some idea of how grand it used to be. In the summer this is a great place to catch outdoor opera. An ecology centre near the police station provides information about the ecology of the park and arranges various activities for children. There is a café in the park that sells ice creams and hot food. The park is a popular way to walk from Notting Hill to Kensington High Street.
points_of_interest.address: Main entrances at Holland Park Avenue, W11 3SW (north side) and Kensington High Street, W8 6AG (south side)

points_of_interest.name: Wandsworth Park
points_of_interest.description: This 19-acre riverside park was opened by London County Council in 1903 on land which used to be allotments. The park is replete with a putting green, small cafe, cricket pitch and tennis courts. The park is home to 350 species of trees and the riverside promenade is lined with London Plane trees which provide shade and beautiful views across the river.

points_of_interest.name: Brockwell Park
points_of_interest.description: A large hilly green park; 10 min walk from the centre of Brixton. Has the following facilities: Brockwell Lido, children's play area, paddling pool, café, flower gardens, sports facilities, toilets and several ponds. Brockwell Park also has a BMX track.

points_of_interest.name: Wimbledon Lawn Tennis Museum
points_of_interest.description: The Wimbledon Lawn Tennis Museum, the largest of its kind, offers a captivating journey through tennis history. Established in 1977 during Wimbledon's centenary, it was reopened in 2006 by The Duke of Kent, enhancing its offerings. With exhibits tracing back to 1555, including interactive touchscreens, the museum showcases memorabilia from legendary players across eras. Seasonal changes bring fresh exhibits, while the Centre Court experience invites visitors to soak in its atmosphere, except during The Championships. Guided tours with Blue Badge guides and audio options enrich the visit. Open year-round, except during The Championships when access is limited to ticket holders.
points_of_interest.address: Centre Court, All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club, Church Rd
points_of_interest.hours: 10:30AM-5PM, closed 24-26 Dec, 1 Jan, middle Su and first M after the Championships

points_of_interest.name: Victoria and Albert Museum
points_of_interest.description: VA Named in honour of Queen Victoria and her consort Prince Albert, this museum has existed for over 150 years. It contains a huge collection of decorative arts from all over the world and far back in time. Trying to see everything in one day would be exhausting, so use the excellent maps the V&A provides to plan where you want to go. There are regular exhibitions concentrating on a particular theme from Chinese art to fashion designers. Frequently they put on children's activities and late DJ nights.

points_of_interest.name: The Arsenal Museum
points_of_interest.description: Founded in 1886, Arsenal has a wonderful history from the club’s time at Woolwich, Highbury and Emirates Stadium and the newly refurbished museum offers visitors the chance to take in a number of exciting exhibits.
points_of_interest.address: Emirates Stadium, Highbury House, 75 Drayton Pk, N5 1BU

points_of_interest.name: Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park
points_of_interest.description: Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park is a vibrant destination in east London, built for the 2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympics. This sprawling park is home to the London Stadium, the Olympic swimming pool, and the iconic ArcelorMittal Orbit, Britain’s largest piece of public art. Originally known as The Olympic Park during the Games, it was renamed in honor of Queen Elizabeth II’s Diamond Jubilee. Today, the park offers a mix of green spaces, sporting venues, and cultural attractions, making it a must-visit for both sports fans and families alike. Its transformation into a thriving public space continues to draw visitors from across the city.
points_of_interest.address: 2 Redman Place, Newham, London, E20 1JQ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: British Library
points_of_interest.description: The official book depository of the United Kingdom, holding a copy of every book ever printed here, and a wide variety of periodicals. No less than 150 million items catalogued and there is an unimaginable {{convert|625|km}} of shelving! Visitors may not use the library unless they have proof of identity, home address, and a genuine need to use a specific item, but there is a free "Treasures of the British Library" exhibition chronicling the history of the written and printed word and displaying some of the library's best known items, including two of the original manuscripts of the Magna Carta and Leonardo Da Vinci's notebook. Additionally there are temporary exhibitions on historical or literary subjects, which charge admission. Popular ones can be very crowded at weekends. In the central atrium stands the King's Library (the library of King George III) surrounded by a glass wall, so visitors can occasionally see librarians retrieving books for readers. Tours of the library building run M W F-Su and cost £6. Call to book. Large items of luggage are not permitted in the building and cannot be stored in the cloakroom.

points_of_interest.name: The Bathing Ponds
points_of_interest.description: There are three notable outdoor bathing ponds on the heath. The Men's Pond and Women's Pond are both part of the line of small lakes on the eastern edge of the heath known as Highgate Ponds, and the Mixed Pond is part of Hampstead Ponds on the opposite side. Swimming hours are seasonal, complicated, age-dependent and change frequently, so it is worth checking before making a special trip.
points_of_interest.address: 32 Millfield Lane, Camden, London, N6 6JB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Capel Manor Gardens
points_of_interest.description: Nestled in Enfield, Greater London, Capel Manor Gardens offers a serene escape from the city. This enchanting destination is part of Capel Manor College, a renowned environmental college. Visitors can explore vibrant plant collections, beautifully maintained gardens, and a variety of flora that showcase horticultural expertise. The gardens provide a peaceful atmosphere, perfect for nature lovers and those seeking a relaxing day out. With family-friendly activities and seasonal events, Capel Manor Gardens is a hidden gem in North London, offering something for everyone to enjoy.
points_of_interest.address: Capel Manor Gardens, Bullsmoor Lane, Enfield, Middlesex, EN1 4RQ

points_of_interest.name: Trafalgar Square
points_of_interest.description: The main, central square of London, Trafalgar Square is associated with celebration and demonstration - it is the site of London's lacklustre New Year celebrations, and in 2003 was the site of the triumphant homecoming of the British Rugby team from the World Cup, and a centre for demonstration against Britain's involvement in the Iraq War. The square has been associated with the many hundreds of pigeons that used to be found here, but in 2003 a bylaw was passed to make it illegal to feed them. Nelson's Column, surrounded by the four bronze lions can be found here, on the south side of the square. The north-west plinth in the square was intended to hold an equestrian statue of William IV, but remained bare since 1841 due to insufficient funds. Since 1999, it has been used to display controversial contemporary sculpture.
points_of_interest.address: 57 Trafalgar Square, Westminster, London, WC2N 5DU, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Charing Cross and Charing Cross Station
points_of_interest.description: Old train station with an enormous office and shopping complex in glass and pale stone. A lavish hotel is also on the site. The name comes from the Queen Eleanor (13th century) gothic pillar outside the station, which is actually a Victorian-era replica. '''Charing Cross Road''' was once famous for its vintage book shops, but these have now largely disappeared due to high rents and online competition; however, the road is still home to one of London's largest bookshops, '''Foyle's'''.
points_of_interest.address: Hungerford Lane, Westminster, London, WC2N 5PH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Alexander Fleming Laboratory Museum
points_of_interest.description: The Alexander Fleming Laboratory Museum, located in London, commemorates the discovery of penicillin by the renowned scientist. This small museum offers a glimpse into the historic laboratory where Fleming made his groundbreaking find. Visitors can explore exhibits showcasing Fleming's life, his discovery, and the profound impact of penicillin on medicine. The museum provides an intimate and educational experience, making it a fascinating stop for those interested in scientific history and medical advancements. Its central location makes it easily accessible for travelers exploring London.
points_of_interest.address: St. Mary's Hospital, Praed St, W2 1NY

points_of_interest.name: Chiswick House and Gardens
points_of_interest.description: Maintained by English Heritage, Chiswick House is a famous and fine example of the 18th century Palladian style of British architecture. The third Earl of Burlington (1694–1753), who designed this elegant Classical villa close to the Thames, drew inspiration from his ''grand tours'' of Italy, while William Kent was employed to create sumptuous interiors to contrast with the pure exterior. The Neo-Classical gardens, although much reduced from their original size, are the perfect complement to the house.
points_of_interest.hours: W-Su and bank holidays 1 Apr-31 Oct 10AM-5PM, Sa until 2PM

points_of_interest.name: Bank of England
points_of_interest.description: The Bank of England, located in the heart of London's financial district, is the central bank of the United Kingdom and one of the oldest in the world. Established in 1694, it has played a pivotal role in shaping global finance. Known as "The Old Lady of Threadneedle Street," its historic headquarters have been a fixture on Threadneedle Street since 1734. Visitors can explore its museum to learn about its rich history and see a portion of the UK's vast gold reserves, which include over 5,000 tonnes of gold stored in its vaults.
points_of_interest.address: 7 Princes Street, City of London, London, EC2R 8AQ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Bunhill Fields Burial Ground
points_of_interest.description: First used to bury bones to make space at St Paul's, it was designated as a burial ground during the Great Plague of 1665. Notable interments include Daniel Dafoe, John Bunyan and William Blake. This small graveyard is a rarity in central London, and seems oddly tranquil in comparison to the nearby bustling streets of the City. Some 120,000 bodies are believed to be buried here: as the inscription reads, it is a burial ground for 'nonconformists'. Notably, Bunhill Fields contains the graves of William Blake, Daniel Defoe and John Bunyan. The watchful eye will notice that the paved way across the field is actually made up of tombstones.

points_of_interest.name: Canary Wharf
points_of_interest.description: A vast shopping, eating, entertainment and (primarily) business complex, home to Britain's second tallest skyscraper, One Canada Square. Now increasingly lively at weekends as well, but still at its most impressive during the week. Spectacular main exit from the Jubilee line Tube station. There is a substantial amount of information about the history and the architecture of the development on the website of Canary Wharf Group, the company that owns the development.
points_of_interest.address: 45 Bank Street, Tower Hamlets, London, E14 5NY, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Bishop's Park
points_of_interest.description: The area surrounding Fulham Palace was given by the Church of England as a public recreational ground.
points_of_interest.address: Bishop's Avenue, Hammersmith and Fulham, London, SW6 6EA, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Red House
points_of_interest.description: A major building of the history of the 'Arts and Crafts style' and of 19th century British architecture. Has some interesting textile displays. William Morris lived here, the architect was Philip Webb, with wall paintings and stained glass by Edward Burne-Jones.

points_of_interest.name: Marble Arch
points_of_interest.description: This enormous arch was built in front of Buckingham Palace. In 1851 the expansion of the palace meant the arch could no longer remain where it was, so it was moved to this point on Hyde Park. It now stands rather sadly on a large traffic island, but the subway beneath the roads means you can stop off at the Marble Arch on your way from Oxford St to Hyde Park. As of March 2024, the arch is closed off and covered for conservation as outdoor exposure has slowly eroded away at the marble.
points_of_interest.address: 1-4 Marble Arch, Westminster, London, W1H 7EJ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Soho Square
points_of_interest.description: Soho Square, a charming garden square in the heart of London, offers a peaceful retreat amidst the bustling city. Originally named King Square after Charles II, it features a weathered statue of the monarch that has stood since 1661. The square hosts free open-air concerts during the summer and is surrounded by historic buildings, including a unique mock "market cross" built in 1926. Once a hub for artists and merchants, Soho Square now blends residential charm with creative industries and community-focused organizations, making it a vibrant spot to relax and soak in its rich history.

points_of_interest.name: Hackney Town Hall
points_of_interest.description: Hackney Town Hall is a stunning example of municipal architecture in Hackney, London. As the headquarters of Hackney London Borough Council, this Grade II listed building stands out for its historical and architectural charm. A notable landmark in the area, it reflects the borough's rich history and civic pride.

points_of_interest.name: British Museum
points_of_interest.description: A vast repository of the world's cultures, controversially including hundreds of items from all over the world. Entire sections are devoted to Egyptian, Greek, and Middle Eastern artifacts, as well as the piece which united them all, the Rosetta Stone. Other items on everyone's list are the largest collection of mummies outside Egypt and the Elgin Marbles. The collection also includes some of the world's finest collections of Chinese and Sub-Saharan African art; perhaps the most famous of the latter are the Benin bronzes. A definite highlight of a trip to London. Temporary exhibitions are invariably excellent and meticulously researched, but can be expensive. It has a fine store, mainly selling replicas of items in the collection.
points_of_interest.hours: Sa-W 10AM-5:30PM, Th F 10AM-8:30PM; Central Great Court remains open Sa-W until 6PM, Th F until 11PM

points_of_interest.name: Bushy Park
points_of_interest.description: The second largest of the London Royal Parks, covering an area of 450 hectares (1,099 acres). Lying north of Hampton Court Palace, the history of the park is inextricably linked to the palace, yet it has always had its own distinct rural character. There are herds of both Red Deer and Fallow Deer, they are wild but usually safe, just don't go too close or get between a hind and its calf. The D-Day linked bits are easiest found from the Teddington side. Go through SHAEF gate and there is an information board. You should be able to spot a flagpole a hundred yards into the park, this marks the spot where General Eisenhower had his office, if you have time, or children who are up for a challenge, there are bronze markers with combined British and Canadian and US flags at the corners where the main buildings of Camp Griffiss were. The partially restored early 18th-century baroque water gardens are a short walk from the Hampton Hill gate. The park is subdivided by Chestnut Avenue, Christopher Wren's grand approach to Hampton Court Palace which runs from Teddington Gate to Hampton Court Gate and with the gilded Diana fountain closer to the Palace end (you may have seen it as location for the finish line of some of the cycling events at the 2012 Olympics).
points_of_interest.address: Chestnut Avenue, Richmond upon Thames, Teddington, TW11 0EQ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Fan Museum
points_of_interest.description: The world's largest fan museum, for those who are big fans of fans. Closed in winter.

points_of_interest.name: Lambeth Palace
points_of_interest.description: The official London residence of the Archbishop of Canterbury since the 13th century and now a Grade I listed building. Tours must be booked in advance and tickets can be purchased via [http://www.ticketmaster.co.uk/Lambeth-Palace-Tours-tickets/artist/1663351 Ticketmaster].
points_of_interest.hours: Only open to pre-booked guided tours

points_of_interest.name: Design Museum
points_of_interest.description: A must for anyone with an interest in modern and contemporary design. The permanent exhibition follows the change in British homes from the early 20th century until present day, which is constantly updated to include new design classics. There are temporary exhibits which run for 3-4 months. The museum also runs ''Designer of the Year'' which awards a prize to a person or organisation that has produced an impressive piece of design. There is a small shop that has plenty of art and design books as well as designer goods to take home with you.

points_of_interest.name: Battersea Park
points_of_interest.description: A lovely park on the southern banks of the Thames known or its wildlife and some splendid examples of mature trees.
points_of_interest.address: Central Avenue, Wandsworth, London, SW11 4NJ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Charles Chaplin plaque
points_of_interest.description: Charles Chaplin lived with his mother in various addresses in and around Kennington Road in Lambeth, including 3 Pownall Terrace, Chester St and 39 Methley Street, and briefly lived with his father and his mistress, Louise, at 287 Kennington Road where a plaque now commemorates the fact. After Chaplin's mother was admitted to the Cane Hill Asylum, her son was left in the workhouse at Renfrew Road in Kennington.

points_of_interest.name: Wimbledon Common
points_of_interest.description: A large area (460 hectares) of woodlands, open grass areas and healthland with a windmill, nature trails and ponds. Also the legendary home of the Wombles.
points_of_interest.address: 10 North View, Merton, London, SW19 4UJ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Natural History Museum
points_of_interest.description: Probably the most popular of all the museums here and a must see for many visitors to London. Home to at least 70 million specimens from across all the life sciences. It's difficult to say what the most popular exhibit here is; the blue whale which towers over the entrance hall, the (now slightly tacky-looking) animatronic ''Tyrannosaurus rex'' in the dinosaur gallery, or the life-size model blue whale in the mammals gallery. Also well worth a check are the Darwin Centre (book on a free tour to see some of the most interesting, and sometimes gruesome, specimens not on public display); and the studio dedicated to BBC wildlife personality extraordinaire, David Attenborough. The NHM's "Earth Galleries" were once the adjacent Geological Museum, an independent institution until the 1980s, and still located in a separate building with a separate entrance.

points_of_interest.name: City Road Basin Plaza
points_of_interest.description: A former industrial site which fell into decline in the 1950s and 60s. The site remained undeveloped and inaccessible to the public for many years. A multi-million-pound project has created public access to the waterway (one of the largest open stretches of water in North London) complete with a newly landscaped public park facing onto the canal.
points_of_interest.address: 14 Graham Street, Islington, London, N1 8GB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: House Mill
points_of_interest.description: Situated on the River Lea in Mill Meads, the House Mill is a remarkable Grade I listed building and part of the historic Three Mills complex. Dating back to the Domesday Book of 1086, the site has been home to tidal mills for centuries. The current structure, built in 1776 by Daniel Bisson, is the largest surviving tidal mill in Britain. Its south facade features a 1776 coat of arms and cast iron wall plates. The adjacent Miller’s House, rebuilt in 1995, offers a glimpse into the site’s residential past. This historic gem is a must-visit for history enthusiasts.

points_of_interest.name: Camley Street Natural Park
points_of_interest.description: A 2-acre nature reserve amid the industrial wasteland just north of King's Cross Station. This lovely little park gives visitors interested in nature the opportunity to learn about the work of the London Wildlife Trust who administer this and 26 other reserves in London. This is the only one in the centre of the city.

points_of_interest.name: Forty Hall & Estate
points_of_interest.description: Forty Hall is a historic gem nestled in the heart of Enfield, offering a glimpse into the past. This stunning 17th-century manor house, now a museum, invites visitors to step back in time and explore its rich history. The estate also boasts the remains of the former Tudor Elsyng Palace, adding a layer of historical depth that captivates history enthusiasts. Whether strolling through the grounds or discovering the museum's treasures, Forty Hall provides a delightful experience for all who visit.
points_of_interest.address: 37 Forty Hill, Enfield, EN2 9EU, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: National Gallery
points_of_interest.description: Houses the British national collection of western European art dating from the 13th to 19th centuries. A truly awe-inspiring collection, notable works include Hans Holbein's ''The Ambassadors'', Van Gogh's ''Sunflowers'' and Constable's ''The Haywain''. The vast majority of art is free of charge to visit. Temporary exhibitions are generally fairly costly, but invariably well researched and presented. The audioguides are very comprehensive, have comments on most of the paintings in the museum, and are free though this fact is not advertised. A donation is suggested. In addition to courses, workshops, lectures and other events, the National Gallery has free talks and tours every day.

points_of_interest.name: Cleopatra's Needle
points_of_interest.description: Cleopatra's Needle originated in the ancient Egyptian city of Heliopolis, in the Temple of Atum, but the Romans moved it to Alexandria in 12 BC. In 1819, viceroy Mehemet Ali presented Cleopatra's Needle to the British, commemorating military victories in Egypt, but it remained in Alexandria until 1877 when transportation was arranged to bring it to London. On the voyage, the ship capsized in a storm, killing six crewmembers. Cleopatra's Needle was thought to be lost, but Spanish trawlers found it afloat a few days later, and after some repairs, it arrived in London on 21 Jan 1878. The obelisk is flanked by two faux-sphinxes, which show the effects of bombings of London during World War II. Today, Cleopatra's Needle shows some wear from exposure to London's damp weather.

points_of_interest.name: Abbey Road Studios
points_of_interest.description: World-renowned studios where many famous musicians and groups, most notably The Beatles, recorded music. The equally famous zebra crossing, immortalized on the cover of the Beatles' album ''Abbey Road'', is right in front. In the vicinity, in Cavendish Avenue, is a home that used to be owned by Sir Paul McCartney.
points_of_interest.address: 3 Abbey Rd, St. John's Wood, NW8 9AY

points_of_interest.name: Boston Manor House
points_of_interest.description: A Jacobean manor house (built in 1622), it is a pleasant and informative place to while away an hour or two, particularly during the summer when the extensive open parklands to the rear of the building make for a delightful stroll.

points_of_interest.name: Mansion House
points_of_interest.description: Home and office of the Lord Mayor, this unique building provides a spectacular setting for business meetings, civic and livery activity, and conferences. Not normally open to the public, Mansion House offers guided tours to small, organised groups. To Hold an event at Mansion House contact the Events Team.
points_of_interest.address: 8-10 Mansion House Place, City of London, London, EC4N 8BJ, United Kingdom
points_of_interest.hours: Tuesday 2PM only, groups may book at other times

points_of_interest.name: The Honourable Society of Gray's Inn
points_of_interest.description: Gray's Inn One of the four Inns of Court in London who hold the exclusive right to call qualified legal professionals to the bar, i.e. to become barristers at law. The grand buildings housing the inns are arranged around lovely green gardens. There are records of Gray's Inns operating from this location since the 14th century.

points_of_interest.name: Christ Church
points_of_interest.description: The restoration of the nave was completed in September 2004, and this church is still a striking building designed by Sir Nicholas Hawksmoor with a particularly tall, pointed spire. Hawksmoor's design was significantly altered in the 19th century, and present continuing restoration is intended to restore it to Hawksmoor's original vision. Christ Church was built as part of the 50 Churches for London project.

points_of_interest.name: Hurlingham Park
points_of_interest.description: A large open park which is mainly sports pitches. It does though have some lovely frontage right onto the Thames and makes for a lovely walk for that reason.
points_of_interest.address: 56 Hurlingham Road, Hammersmith and Fulham, London, SW6 3RQ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Danson Park
points_of_interest.description: A truly stunning yet under-visited park, next to Welling, that features a mansion house (Danson House) and boating lake.
points_of_interest.address: Danson Park, Bexleyheath, DA6 8HL, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Regent's Park
points_of_interest.description: Large open space very popular with Londoners and less visited by tourists than the other great city parks. A number of lovely lakes, an open air theatre, regular puppet shows, various sporting activities and some splendid ancient trees. There is also a cafe and play area next to the boating pond.
points_of_interest.address: Inner Circle, Westminster, London, NW1 4NX, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Photographers' Gallery
points_of_interest.description: The exhibitions are wide and varied, from documentary photographers to fine artists, some long gone, and some on their way up. With the crowds and chaos of Leicester Square on one side and Covent Garden on the other, this is a welcome retreat.

points_of_interest.name: Sutton House
points_of_interest.description: Sutton House is a charming Grade II* listed Tudor manor house located on Homerton High Street in the vibrant London Borough of Hackney. Owned by the National Trust, this historic property offers a unique glimpse into London's past. Step back in time and explore the well-preserved architecture and interiors, which reflect its rich history. A rare example of a Tudor house in London, Sutton House is a must-visit for history enthusiasts and anyone looking to uncover the borough's hidden gems.

points_of_interest.name: Cartoon Museum
points_of_interest.description: The Cartoon Museum is a London museum for British cartoons, caricatures and comic strips, owned and operated by the Cartoon Art Trust . It has a library of over 5,000 books and 4,000 comics. The museum issues catalogues and features a changing display of over 250 exhibits from its collection of over 4,000 original cartoons and prints. The museum is "dedicated to preserving the best of British cartoons, caricatures, comics and animation, and to establishing a museum with a gallery, archives and innovative exhibitions to make the creativity of cartoon art past and present, accessible to all for the purposes of education, research and enjoyment.".

points_of_interest.name: Hampton Court Palace
points_of_interest.description: Historic home to English kings such as Henry VIII, now open to the public. There are many attractions which can occupy a whole day visit, including 60 acres of gardens with the famous maze, the Tudor kitchens, the Chapel Royal, the Great Hall, Mantegna's Triumphs of Caesar paintings, and various exhibitions about Henry VIII.

points_of_interest.name: Greenwich Park
points_of_interest.description: Situated on a hill rising up from Greenwich town centre, the park offers impressive views from the hilltop across the River Thames to Docklands and the City of London. The park also provides a setting for several historic buildings, including the Royal Observatory, the '''old Royal Naval College''', the National Maritime Museum and the '''Queen's House'''.
points_of_interest.address: Blackheath Avenue, Greenwich, London, SE10 8QY, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Archbishop's Park
points_of_interest.description: This park used to be the grounds of Lambeth Palace but has been a public park since 1901. In addition to the green space it provides, it contains a range of sports facilities (booking required, except for the cricket nets) and a playground.
points_of_interest.address: 2 Carlisle Lane, Lambeth, London, SE1 7LF, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Leighton House
points_of_interest.description: The former Victorian home of an artist Frederic (Lord) Leighton. While regarded as one of the finest examples of Victorian residential architecture, it's not the usual Neo-Gothic venue. The entrance rooms, especially the so-called Arabic Hall, look like an eclectic cross-breed between the Alhambra and Topkapı Palace. This may sound quite terrible, but surprisingly it works. While the rest of the building is less vividly decorated it's still designed rather well and displays some works by Lord Leighton himself and his fellow Pre-Raphaelites, but also a handful of works by Delacroix and Corot as well as a collection of some colourful pottery. Regular small exhibitions are held in the house's extension.

points_of_interest.name: Battersea Power Station
points_of_interest.description: One of the great icons of the old smog-filled London of the mid-20th century and regarded as a fine example of industrial design of the Art Deco era. This coal-fired power station generated its last electricity in 1983 and sat empty for many years before being redeveloped with flats, shops, and offices in the 2010s. In many ways best viewed from a distance on the north side of the Thames at Chelsea.
points_of_interest.address: 13 Pump House Lane, Wandsworth, London, SW11 8DE, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Wimbledon Society Museum of Local History
points_of_interest.description: Showing local history in Wimbledon from the Stone Age to the present day.
points_of_interest.hours: Sa Su 2:30PM-5PM, by appointment at other times

points_of_interest.name: Science Museum
points_of_interest.description: Dedicated to scientific exhibitions and collections bar those related to the life sciences. A number of famous historical machines and inventions are housed here, from steam locomotives to the Apollo 10 command module. The space exhibits are especially popular. Exhibitions tend to concentrate on explaining scientific principles with working models and there is a strong emphasis on education and attracting children. The Science Museum opened a "Children's Gallery" in the 1930s and it continues to lead the way in this area; now, there are three separate galleries aimed at all ages of younger visitor, from 5 to 16. The museum also runs "Science Nights" whereby children spend an evening learning principles and participating in experiments before spending the night sleeping in the museum with the exhibits. Also houses a vast library of scientific and medical books and journals.

points_of_interest.name: Crafts Council
points_of_interest.description: This gallery promotes contemporary craftspeople working materials such as metal, glass, pottery and textiles but with a unique take on each medium. The work frequently strays into contemporary art and blurs the border between art and craft. The small shop inside provides individually crafted pieces, that are as expensive as you would expect.

points_of_interest.name: Walthamstow Wetlands
points_of_interest.description: Nature reserve set around reservoirs, one of the largest urban wetlands in Europe and a nice place for birdwatching. Opened to the public in October 2017. There is a cycle and running route through the wetlands. Dogs aren't allowed, except for assistance dogs.

points_of_interest.name: Jewish Museum
points_of_interest.description: A Jewish museum is a cultural institution dedicated to preserving and showcasing the history, traditions, and contributions of Jewish communities. These museums often feature exhibits on art, artifacts, and personal stories that highlight the Jewish experience. Visitors can explore the rich heritage of Jewish culture through interactive displays, historical collections, and educational programs. Whether you're interested in history, art, or cultural traditions, a Jewish museum offers a fascinating glimpse into the diverse and vibrant Jewish heritage. It’s a great destination for both locals and travelers seeking to deepen their understanding of Jewish history and identity.

points_of_interest.name: The Hill Garden and Pergola
points_of_interest.description: A quite beautiful hidden garden on West Heath, which is little known even to many Londoners. It was originally part of the gardens of 19th-century Inverforth House built by Viscount Leverhulme (the then owner of Lever Brothers, now Unilever). The gardens are now common land and part of Hampstead Heath, and the most impressive feature is a restored timber pergola, covered with various climbing plants including roses, honeysuckle, clematis, wisteria and various vines. The pergola offers two stunning views from its north-western point. You can look straight out and over the heath's canopy and see nothing but mature trees. Alternatively, you can look down and see the beautifully manicured herb garden and the length of the pergola stretching out before you. The adjacent Hill Garden offers a complete contrast to the wildness of the pergola. The garden is beautifully manicured and is a favourite haunt for artists. The bench by the ornamental fish pond here gives a stunning view of Hampstead Heath with the towers of urban London as the backdrop.

points_of_interest.name: Harrow School
points_of_interest.description: Harrow is famous for its school, Winston Churchill attended it as did 7 other British prime ministers. The school is at the top of the hill, the buildings and surrounding area are a step back in time. Public tours take place four times a year in the holidays, while private tours for groups of up to 10 can be arranged any time of the year. Try to go in term time on a Sunday as the pupils in long coats and straw boaters, and the masters in mortar boards are a sight rarely seen anywhere outside of Hollywood films of ''Olde England''!.

points_of_interest.name: National Portrait Gallery
points_of_interest.description: The National Portrait Gallery is just around the corner from the National Gallery and is an entertaining way to learn about British history since the Tudors. Visitors walk around the gallery chronologically, viewing portraits of notable figures from British history - from Henry VII, painted by Hans Holbein, to Blur, painted by Julian Opie.

points_of_interest.name: Covent Garden Piazza and Central Market
points_of_interest.description: Once an important working market, and the backdrop for the musical ''My Fair Lady'', Covent Garden today is a covered shopping mall with shops predominantly selling clothing, but also gifts and cosmetics, as well as stalls selling handicrafts (Tu-Su) or antiques (M), and restaurants. It's well worth a visit just for the attractive ambience, with classical musicians busking in the lower part of the market and a famous location for street entertainers. There is a popular pub, The '''Punch and Judy Tavern''' at the western end, with a large balcony overlooking a square where street entertainers perform. At the eastern end, the corresponding balcony is occupied by Chez Gerard, a restaurant selling relatively-expensive but good continental cuisine. Most shops are open daily 10AM-7PM, but may close earlier on Sundays.
points_of_interest.address: 17 The Piazza, Westminster, London, WC2E 8RB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Little Venice
points_of_interest.description: A canal basin where the Regent's Canal meets the Grand Union, just a few minutes walk from Paddington Station.
points_of_interest.address: 36 Blomfield Road, Westminster, London, W9 2PF, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Monument
points_of_interest.description: Designed by Sir Christopher Wren, this tall column (which can be ascended to get a great view) marks the alleged site where the Great Fire of London broke out in September 1666.
points_of_interest.address: 16-18 Monument Street, City of London, London, EC3R 8AJ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Honourable Society of Lincoln's Inn
points_of_interest.description: Lincoln's Inn Like Gray's Inn, one of the four societies of the bar. The wonderful old buildings here are arranged around the open spaces of Lincoln's Inn Fields and a walk around this area will give any visitor a real sense of the history and grand traditions of the legal profession in London.

points_of_interest.name: Dennis Severs' House
points_of_interest.description: Built as a townhouse belonging to a wealthy Huguenot merchant family in the 18th century, the late artist Dennis Severs has returned its interior to how it might have looked in those early days. But this is no mere museum; there are no exhibits or glass cases. Instead, Dennis Severs' House offers a completely immersive journey into the past with each room appearing, feeling and smelling as if its occupant had just left. A must for history lovers.
points_of_interest.hours: M "lunchtime" noon–2PM, M W "silent nights" 5–9PM, Su "daytime" noon–4PM

points_of_interest.name: Ravenscourt Park
points_of_interest.description: An eight-hectare park in Hammersmith with a long history. It is home to a lake, tea house, tennis courts, an all-weather football pitch, a bowling green, areas in which to just sit or play, a garden centre and some truly ancient trees, particularly cedars.

points_of_interest.name: ZSL London Zoo
points_of_interest.description: London Zoo London's main zoo located in the northern reaches of Regent's Park. Takes a very conservation-driven approach these days and always has great exhibits aimed at children. Opened in 1828 for scientific study, then to the public in 1847.

points_of_interest.name: St John-at-Hackney Community Space Centre
points_of_interest.description: This tower of St John-at-Hackney Church is the oldest building in Hackney and a famous landmark of the borough.

points_of_interest.name: Charles Dickens Museum
points_of_interest.description: Step into the former London home of one of literature's greatest figures at the Charles Dickens Museum. Located at 48 Doughty Street in King's Cross, this charming Georgian townhouse was Dickens's residence from 1837 to 1839. Now a museum, it offers a glimpse into the life and works of the celebrated author. Explore the restored interiors, which reflect the Victorian era, and discover personal items, rare manuscripts, and memorabilia that bring Dickens's world to life. This intimate museum is a must-visit for fans of Dickens and anyone curious about the history of one of London's most iconic writers.
points_of_interest.hours: M W-Sa 10AM-5PM (last admission 4:30PM), Tu 10AM-7PM, Su 11AM-5PM (last admission 4:30PM)

points_of_interest.name: Ham House & Garden
points_of_interest.description: The Duke and Duchess of Lauderdale's elegant 17th-century manor house, a mile or so upriver from Richmond riverside.

points_of_interest.name: Deer Park
points_of_interest.description: Deer Park, a historic landscape feature, served as an enclosed area for deer in medieval and Early Modern England, Wales, and Ireland. Typically bounded by a ditch, bank, and wooden pale or stone wall, these parks were designed to contain deer while offering a controlled environment for hunting. The landscape was carefully crafted to provide both habitat for the deer and open spaces for hunting, featuring tree-dotted lawns, wooded areas, and clumps of trees. Intended to be both functional and visually appealing, Deer Park reflects a blend of natural beauty and practical design.
points_of_interest.address: 145 Maze Hill, Greenwich, London, SE3 7UB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The South Bank Lion
points_of_interest.description: The Red Lion This statue was once the mascot of the Red Lion Brewery and stood on its roof until the brewery was demolished to make way for the Royal Festival Hall. It was moved to Waterloo and then to its present position on the bridge. Keen students of biology may notice that the statue is missing certain male body parts. It used to be anatomically correct but was deemed too lewd and scandalous when placed closer to pedestrians' eye-level and was castrated so as not to cause offence.

points_of_interest.name: 18 Stafford Terrace
points_of_interest.description: The Victorian residence of satirical cartoonist Edward Linley Sambourne and his household, which is now open as a museum. The "aesthetic" interior design, preserved close to how the Sambournes would have kept it in 1899, features much Chinese and Middle Eastern-style furniture, art, and decorative schemes, along with a selection of Edward's cartoons, which typically ribbed the British establishment and its colonial-driven international relations.
points_of_interest.hours: W Sa Su 2PM-5:30PM; guided tours: W Su 11AM-12:15PM, costumed tours Sa 11AM-12:15PM

points_of_interest.name: Clapham Common
points_of_interest.description: This large open space in densely built Wandsworth has been a source of comfort to Londoners for time immemorial. The common is roughly triangular shape with an area of {{ha|88}}. It is mostly open grassy parkland with scattered mature trees. There are three ponds here which are notably popular with local fisherman. The Grade II listed bandstand was fully restored in 2006.
points_of_interest.address: 26 Windmill Drive, Wandsworth, London, SW4 9DE, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Wimbledon Windmill Museum
points_of_interest.description: The Wimbledon Windmill Museum is a historic windmill turned museum located on Wimbledon Common in South London. This charming attraction offers a glimpse into the area's industrial past, showcasing the windmill's history and significance. Visitors can explore the preserved interior and learn about its role in the community. A great spot for history enthusiasts and families alike, Wimbledon Windmill Museum provides a unique and educational experience in a picturesque setting.
points_of_interest.address: 2 Windmill Road, Merton, London, SW19 5NQ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Geological Museum
points_of_interest.description: The Red Zone of the Natural History Museum This venerable old institution was absorbed by the neighbouring Natural History Museum in 1985 but still has something of a separate identity. Unsurprisingly, devoted to all things geological with especially popular exhibits on vulcanology and earthquakes and fossils of all types. Very popular with kids and often underrated.

points_of_interest.name: Gillespie Park Ecology Centre
points_of_interest.description: Gillespie Park Ecology Centre is a unique urban oasis in the heart of Islington, London. This community-focused center offers a peaceful retreat from the city, with lush green spaces and a variety of plant and animal life. Visitors can explore the center's gardens, attend workshops, or join guided nature walks. It’s a great spot for families and nature enthusiasts alike, providing insight into local biodiversity and sustainable living practices. The surrounding park also features a nature reserve, making it a must-visit for anyone looking to connect with nature in the city.
points_of_interest.hours: Daily except on Arsenal FC home match days

points_of_interest.name: Vestry House Museum
points_of_interest.description: Presents the history of Waltham Forest. The building was constructed to be a workhouse and has since been used as a police station and a private home. Its collection includes the Bremer car, built by the engineer Frederick Bremer in 1892 and has a claim to being the first petrol-driven car made in Britain.

points_of_interest.name: Regent's Canal
points_of_interest.description: You can walk or cycle along the canal through east London all the way to the Thames (3 hr). The St. Pancras lock is directly north of St Pancras station. Regent's Canal was once a lifeline for trade and industry in London with narrowboats and barges ferrying goods to and from North London. The canal winds its way from the Grand Union Canal near Paddington in West London, past Regent's Park, Camden, Islington and Mile End to Limehouse, where it meets the Thames. From Camden Lock you can walk upstream along the canal to Regent's Park and on to London Zoo. It is a great way to approach the Zoo and a good way to avoid the traffic. Downstream of Camden is less pretty but still an interesting walk, taking you through the Islington Tunnel (one of the longest tunnels in the British canal system) and out in to East London. Whichever way you go along the path, watch out for cyclists!
points_of_interest.address: 2 Water Lane, Camden, London, NW1 8HY, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Kenwood House
points_of_interest.description: A splendid Regency house with enormous gardens and woodlands. The gardens alone are worth the visit and are a superb example of 18th-century landscaping. On show at the house is art by masters such as Rembrandt, Turner, Reynolds and Vermeer, and the gardens have a very notable sculpture by Henry Moore. A regular program of outdoor opera takes place here every summer. Movie buffs will recognise Kenwood from Mansfield Park among other famous films. Administered by English Heritage, separately from the rest of Hampstead Heath.

points_of_interest.name: Harrow on the Hill
points_of_interest.description: Harrow on the Hill grew around the millennium-old St. Mary's Church, and was the centre of power for an area encompassed by what is the current borough. The hill is a place where you can see a chunk of English history in the urban landscape.
points_of_interest.address: 38 Sudbury Hill, Harrow, HA1 3YP, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: St. Paul's Church
points_of_interest.description: St. Paul's Church, located on Pulteney Street in Adelaide, is a historic Anglican church that stands at the northeast corner of Pulteney and Flinders streets. Originally built alongside the Pulteney Street School, which has since evolved into Pulteney Grammar School, the church is a testament to the city's rich history. While it no longer serves as a place of worship, the building has been repurposed as a vibrant entertainment venue, blending its heritage with modern-day culture. Visitors can appreciate its enduring presence and role in Adelaide's evolving landscape.

points_of_interest.name: Ealing Town Hall
points_of_interest.description: Ealing Town Hall is a historic municipal building located in the heart of Ealing, London. This charming structure, with its rich architectural details, serves as a civic landmark and a point of interest for visitors. As a Grade II listed building, it reflects the area's heritage and offers a glimpse into its storied past.

points_of_interest.name: St Giles-without-Cripplegate
points_of_interest.description: Medieval Grade I listed church. This church played a key role in the English Revolution and was the parish church of some of the most decisive Puritans: Oliver Cromwell was married and this is where John Milton was buried. It was the home of the Morning Exercises. The tower remains from the original building; the rest was destroyed in the Blitz but rebuilt based on the original plans.

points_of_interest.name: Myddelton Square Park
points_of_interest.description: Myddelton Square Park is a hidden gem nestled in the heart of London, offering a serene retreat from the city's hustle and bustle. Designed in the 19th century, this charming park features beautifully maintained gardens, meandering walking paths, and a central fountain that adds to its tranquil ambiance. The park is steeped in history, with a statue of Sir Hugh Myddelton, a notable figure in London's water supply development. Visitors can enjoy picnics on the lush greenery, relax in a peaceful setting, or participate in community events that bring the neighborhood together. It's an ideal spot to unwind and soak in the local culture.

points_of_interest.name: Museum of London Docklands
points_of_interest.description: The Museum of London Docklands, located in West India Quay, offers a fascinating look at the history of the River Thames, the growth of the Port of London, and the docks' connection to the Atlantic slave trade. Housed in a stunning Grade I listed Georgian warehouse built in 1802, the museum provides a unique glimpse into the city's maritime past. Situated near Canary Wharf, it's an easily accessible and engaging destination for anyone interested in London's rich history.

points_of_interest.name: Wormwood Scrubs
points_of_interest.description: The Scrubs One of the largest areas of common land in London. Its sporting facilities include several football pitches (Queens Park Rangers F.C. used to play here in the Victorian age).
points_of_interest.address: Artillery Lane, Hammersmith and Fulham, London, W12 0AP, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: London Central Mosque
points_of_interest.description: Regent's Park Mosque Islamic Cultural Centre and the main mosque in London. Visitors are welcome but must be suitably attired. The Mosque runs classes, prayers, talks and events.

points_of_interest.name: St Augustine's Tower
points_of_interest.description: St Augustine's Tower is a historic landmark that offers a glimpse into centuries past. This medieval tower, one of the oldest structures in the area, features stunning architecture and rich history. Visitors can explore its intricate design and learn about its significance through interactive exhibits. The tower also provides panoramic views of the surrounding landscape, making it a must-visit for history enthusiasts and those seeking a unique perspective on the region.
points_of_interest.address: 354 Mare Street, Hackney, London, E8 1HR, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Foundling Museum
points_of_interest.description: A museum and a gallery telling the story of the Foundling Hospital, an orphanage for abandoned children founded in the 18th century. Massive art donations by British artists and the involvement of George Friederic Handel as a patron made this childcare organisation an early centre of art and music.

points_of_interest.name: Richmond Palace
points_of_interest.description: The remains of the once-magnificent palace, home to English kings since Edward I, adjoin Richmond Green, a pleasant open green space and historic cricket ground. Only the Gate House and Wardrobe, now converted into flats, remain.
points_of_interest.address: 3 Old Palace Yard, Richmond upon Thames, Richmond, TW9 1PA, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Royal Observatory
points_of_interest.description: The home of Greenwich Mean Time and the Prime Meridian line, this is one of the most important historic scientific sites in the world. It was founded by Charles II in 1675 and is, by international decree, the official starting point for each new day, year and millennium (at the stroke of midnight GMT as measured from the Prime Meridian). Now a detached part of the National Maritime Museum, it houses an impressive display and a planetarium built in 2007. There are several different star shows per day that are well worth the money, especially as it's now the only celestial performance of its kind around, after the London Planetarium completely converted to Madame Tussauds.

points_of_interest.name: County Hall
points_of_interest.description: The former seat of regional London government, now home to attractions such as the London Aquarium, the London Dungeon, and Namco Funscape.

points_of_interest.name: The Tower House
points_of_interest.description: A private residence which can only be seen from the street. Designed and built in a French neo-Gothic style by William Burges, it features a handsome cone-roofed tower. Legendary guitarist Jimmy Page has been the house's proud owner since he bought it from actor Richard Harris in 1972.

points_of_interest.name: London Wetland Centre
points_of_interest.description: Substantial nature reserve on the old disused Barn Elms Reservoirs. A major wetland habitat for wintering wildfowl and an excellent choice for any keen birders visiting London, and an entertaining place for kids to learn about nature

points_of_interest.name: Kennington Park
points_of_interest.description: Kennington Park, located in south London, is a historic green space that offers a blend of natural beauty and rich history. Once Kennington Common, the site was a hub for public gatherings, including the famous Chartist rally of 1848. Converted into a park in 1854 with royal support, it has since become a peaceful retreat for both relaxation and recreation. The park is known for its cricket heritage, with ties to The Oval, and hosts casual games of cricket and football. Today, it also features a restored Flower Garden and is a popular spot for community and cultural events.

points_of_interest.name: Buddhapadipa Temple
points_of_interest.description: Nestled in Wimbledon, London, Buddhapadipa Temple is a serene Thai Buddhist temple under Thai royal patronage. This peaceful retreat offers a glimpse into traditional Thai culture, blending intricate architecture with a calming atmosphere. Visitors can explore the temple grounds, attend meditation sessions, or join cultural festivals, making it a unique destination for both spiritual seekers and curious travelers.
points_of_interest.hours: Temple ground: M-F 9AM-6PM, main temple: weekends

points_of_interest.name: National Army Museum
points_of_interest.description: This large museum traces the history of the British Army, and includes interesting and thought-provoking exhibits that go well beyond a collection of military equipment (though the museum does, of course, boast a large collection of it).

points_of_interest.name: London Canal Museum
points_of_interest.description: Exhibits explaining the history of London's canals, in the former Gatti's Ice House: it stored huge blocks of ice brought from Norway. There's additional material on the early history of ice cream in London.

points_of_interest.name: Walthamstow Village
points_of_interest.description: The ancient nucleus of present-day Walthamstow centred around the 12th-century St. Mary's Church.
points_of_interest.address: 117 Church Hill, Waltham Forest, London, E17 3BD, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: St. Pancras Old Church and cemetery
points_of_interest.description: Hidden away behind St. Pancras railway station is what is believed to be one of the oldest sites of Christian worship in England. There has been a church on the site since at least around the year 314. The current church is mostly a 19th-century structure, but it contains some traces of an older Norman structure. Surrounding the church is a cemetery, today transformed into a public park that contains a memorial to philosopher and "mother of feminism" Mary Wollstonecraft, who was originally buried there before her remains were moved to Bournemouth. This is where her daughter Mary, the author of ''Frankenstein'', first declared her love for her future husband, Romantic poet Percy Bysshe Shelley.

points_of_interest.name: Bentley Priory Nature Reserve
points_of_interest.description: The place is a beautifully preserved nature reserve but it also contains Bentley Priory, this place was the RAF Fighter Command HQ in the Second World War. When London was burning, this place was never bombed, some people say that German Air Command did not destroy it because they wanted to make it their own HQ, this place was inside the RAF Stanmore Air Base but now its been opened to the public. It also has a deer park and a beautiful pond; named Boot Pond.
points_of_interest.address: 6 Glenthorpe Gardens, Stanmore, HA7 3GG, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Piccadilly Circus
points_of_interest.description: At the junction of five major roads, Piccadilly Circus is the home of the famous aluminum statue of Eros, which sits atop a fountain. The monument is officially known as Shaftesbury Memorial Fountain and initially wasn't supposed to depict Eros, but different god Anteros. The north side of Piccadilly Circus holds an enormous display board of electric advertisements, including Britain's biggest illuminated display (the widest in the world), advertising Coca-Cola.
points_of_interest.address: 1 Piccadilly Circus, Westminster, London, W1J 0DA, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Seven Dials
points_of_interest.description: An intersection of seven streets in the northern part of the Covent Garden district. Lots of mid-range designer clothing and shoe stores
points_of_interest.address: Seven Dials, Camden, London, WC2H 8JB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Ealing Common
points_of_interest.description: Ealing Common is a peaceful retreat in West London, offering a spacious green area perfect for relaxation. Visitors can enjoy leisurely strolls along well-maintained paths, surrounded by lush greenery. It’s an ideal spot for picnics or simply unwinding. The common also serves as a vibrant community hub, hosting various events throughout the year. Its charm and accessibility make it a must-visit for both locals and travelers seeking a serene escape within the city.

points_of_interest.name: St Sepulchre-without-Newgate
points_of_interest.description: Church of the Holy Sepulchre (Holborn) Grade I listed Saxon church founded before the 12th century. The exterior was mostly constructed in the 15th century, and the interior in the 19th. The north side of the church houses a musician's chapel opened in 1955. In addition to the services, there are often evening (chargeable) concerts.
points_of_interest.hours: Open W noon-3PM, services Su 10:30AM, Tu 1PM & 6:30PM

points_of_interest.name: Royal Courts of Justice
points_of_interest.description: The building holds the High Court and the Court of Appeal, two of the highest courts in the United Kingdom, though only civil cases are heard here. Trials are open to the public, but tourists would probably be more interested in seeing the impressive entrance hall, and admiring the stunning Victorian Gothic exterior.

points_of_interest.name: The Brick Lane Gallery
points_of_interest.description: Exhibits an eclectic variety of contemporary art and street art by British and International artists, focusing mainly on exhibiting emerging and mid-career artists. They present an integrated programme of exhibitions, including solo-shows as well as group exhibitions, introducing innovative developments in painting, sculpture, photography, performance, video and works on paper.

points_of_interest.name: Chelsea Harbour Design Centre
points_of_interest.description: The cutting edge of British design from Furniture to Fabrics and Lighting. Some showrooms actually sell their designs (at impossible prices). There is also a nice café here.

points_of_interest.name: Lesnes Abbey Woods
points_of_interest.description: Lesnes Abbey Woods offers a peaceful retreat from the city, combining lush greenery with a touch of history. The site features the ruins of Lesnes Abbey, adding a layer of intrigue to its natural beauty. It’s also part of the Green Chain Walk, making it a convenient stop for hikers exploring South London. Visitors can enjoy a serene escape, immersed in nature and history.
points_of_interest.address: 393 Abbey Road, Belvedere, DA17 5DH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Victoria Park
points_of_interest.description: Commonly called the People's Park, it's huge and hosts summer festivals. On an island in the park is a Chinese pagoda, a reconstruction of a pagoda built in 1842. On Sundays the park hosts a popular street food market.
points_of_interest.address: 15 Iveagh Close, Tower Hamlets, London, E9 7BW, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Fitzroy House
points_of_interest.description: L. Ron Hubbard House A historic house that was inhabited by playwright George Bernard Shaw, it is where writer L. Ron Hubbard, founder of Scientology, worked in the 1950s. The building is reminiscent of the time, complete with Adler typewriters, Grundig tape recorders, and Western Union telefax. Tours by appointment.

points_of_interest.name: Richmond Park
points_of_interest.description: The largest open space in London, covering almost 1,000 hectares (2,500 acres) and home to a huge array of wildlife, including 400 wild deer. Also contains the lush Isabella Plantation, which is full of trees and flowers, and the Royal Ballet School, seen in the film ''Billy Elliot''. Popular with cyclists, both for the on-road perimeter circuit and the off-road trails. There are several car parks for walkers and picnickers.
points_of_interest.address: Sawyer's Hill, Richmond upon Thames, Richmond, TW10 5HR, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The National Maritime Museum
points_of_interest.description: Museum devoted to the maritime role in Britain's history. Contains the UK's national collection of Maritime artefacts (although do not expect much in the way of whole ships). One of the buildings housing the museum is the Queens House, built by Inigo Jones as the first Palladian building in England.

points_of_interest.name: Sea Life London Aquarium
points_of_interest.description: The Sea Life London Aquarium is centrally located on the South Bank of the River Thames, near the iconic London Eye. Since opening in 1997, this popular attraction has welcomed millions of visitors. Home to a stunning array of marine life, the aquarium offers an engaging and educational experience for all ages. With its interactive exhibits and diverse aquatic displays, it’s a must-visit for families and anyone fascinated by the underwater world.

points_of_interest.name: Maharajah Duleep Singh's House
points_of_interest.description: A blue plaque marks the house in which the last Maharajah of the Sikh Empire lived in the 1880s.

points_of_interest.name: St Mary's Church
points_of_interest.description: One of the oldest churches in Battersea, this church is where Christians have worshiped at the same site since 800 AD. It is protected as a Grade I listed building with its combination of heritage and architectural merit.

points_of_interest.name: Museum of Garden History
points_of_interest.description: In an old church, which also has the tomb of Captain Bligh of The Bounty mutiny fame. The museum charts the history of garden design and gardening.

points_of_interest.name: Cannizaro Park
points_of_interest.description: Cannizaro Park is a beautiful public park in Wimbledon, located near the southwest edge of Wimbledon Common. Known for its stunning ornamental landscaped gardens, the park features serene ponds and an array of sculptures, making it a peaceful retreat for visitors. Boasting a Grade II* listing on the Register of Historic Parks and Gardens, Cannizaro Park is a charming destination that offers a perfect blend of natural beauty and historical significance.
points_of_interest.address: 19 Hanford Row, Merton, London, SW19 4UT, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Memorial Scrolls Trust Museum
points_of_interest.description: Czech Scrolls Museum Following the mass murder perpetrated by the Nazis, the Jewish population of postwar Czechoslovakia was a tiny fraction of its former size, and religious persecution continued under the communist regime.
