This tiny museum tells the fascinating story of how, in 1964, 1,500 Torah scrolls were rescued from rotting in Prague and brought to London, where they were painstakingly restored by hand. 130 scrolls remain in situ, but the rest have been distributed among synagogues across the UK and around the world.
points_of_interest.address: 3rd floor, Kent House, Rutland Gardens, SW7 1BX
points_of_interest.hours: By appointment only; scheduled guided tours of 60 min for up to 20 people once a week, see details [https://memorialscrollstrust.org/index.php/czech-scrolls-museum here]

points_of_interest.name: Victoria Miro Gallery
points_of_interest.description: An excellent contemporary art gallery in a converted Victorian furniture factory. Press the buzzer to unlock the door, it is not a typical Tate-tourist magnet.

points_of_interest.name: William Morris Gallery
points_of_interest.description: Dedicated to William Morris, the Victorian arts & crafts designer and writer. Located in his old Georgian family home, Water House, which is now a Grade II* listed building.

points_of_interest.name: St. Pancras International railway station
points_of_interest.description: St. Pancras International is a stunning central London railway station, renowned for its iconic architecture and rich history. As the terminus for Eurostar services to mainland Europe, it connects London to cities like Paris and Brussels. The station also offers domestic routes across the UK. Designed by William Henry Barlow, its grand Victorian design features a single-span roof and Gothic Revival details. Once threatened with demolition, it was saved by a passionate campaign and restored to its former glory. Today, it stands as a Grade I listed building, blending historic charm with modern amenities, making it a must-visit destination in London.
points_of_interest.address: 7 Pancras Road, Camden, London, N1C 4AG, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: 2 Willow Road
points_of_interest.description: A house designed by Erno Goldfinger in 1939 and regarded as an icon of modernist architecture. The contents are just as impressive as the house and include original works by Henry Moore and Max Ernst. Local lore has it that Hampstead resident of the time Ian Fleming objected so strongly to Goldfinger's modernist design that he named his famous Bond villain after him.

points_of_interest.name: Headstone Manor and Museum
points_of_interest.description: Local history museum for the London Borough of Harrow. Headstone Manor House was built in about 1310 and is the earliest timber framed building in the area. Over the centuries, it has been modified and expanded repeatedly and makes for an interesting study in the history of English houses. Nowadays it displays artifacts from the history of Harrow, ranging from prehistory through the 20th century. Cafe and Visitor Centre.

points_of_interest.name: Leicester Square Garden
points_of_interest.description: Relax and unwind in the garden, and gaze at the activity going on all around, while listening to the buskers, street entertainers and preachers performing in the area. At the centre of the square is a fountain with a statue honouring William Shakespeare, and the benches that surround the fountain are dotted with other fun statues—you can take your picture sitting next to Mr. Bean, or standing with Charlie Chaplin.
points_of_interest.address: 48 Leicester Square, Westminster, London, WC2H 7LU, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: St Martins in the Fields
points_of_interest.description: A neoclassical church that stands opposite the National Gallery. Since World War I, the homeless have sought shelter at this church, a tradition that continues to this day.

points_of_interest.name: Ealing Green
points_of_interest.description: Ealing Green is a charming green space in the heart of the London Borough of Ealing, offering a peaceful retreat from the city's hustle. Surrounded by beautiful trees and vibrant flower beds, the green is perfect for picnics, relaxation, or a quick break while exploring the area. Visitors can enjoy the nearby cafes, shops, and historic buildings, making it a great spot to unwind and soak in the local atmosphere. Whether you're looking to people-watch or simply enjoy nature, Ealing Green provides a welcoming and picturesque setting for all.

points_of_interest.name: Old Bailey
points_of_interest.description: Central Criminal Court This is probably the most famous criminal court in the world, and has been London's principal criminal court for centuries. It hears cases remitted to it from all over England and Wales as well as the Greater London area. The present building dates largely from 1907 (a new block was added from 1970 for more modern facilities) and stands on the site of the infamous medieval Newgate Gaol. The Central Criminal Court is of course best known today for its association with John Mortimer's ''Rumpole of the Bailey'' character, novels and television series. Daily case listings are available at [http://www.thelawpages.com/court-hearings-lists/Central-Criminal-Court.php The law pages]. No bags, cameras, drinks, food or mobile phones—no facilities for safekeeping. Children under 14 are not admitted.
points_of_interest.address: 20 Old Bailey, City of London, London, EC4M 7BF, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Staple Inn
points_of_interest.description: See the rare range of Tudor half-timbered buildings. Staple Inn was built in 1585 and served as an inn Inn of Chancery (law school). Most of it escaped both the Great Fire and the German air raids, unlike other buildings in the area. The western end is actually from a different, adjoining building—which was incorporated into the Inn with a unified facade during restoration work in 1936, although the difference can still be seen in the roofing and slightly different style. One of Charles Dickens's homes was on the site and it was featured in his ''Mystery of Edwin Drood''.

points_of_interest.name: Young V&A
points_of_interest.description: Museum of Childhood The Victoria and Albert Museum's East London branch has a focus on childhood and is particularly known for its large collection of toys throughout the ages. Great for children of all ages.

points_of_interest.name: Fulham Palace
points_of_interest.description: The former retreat of the Bishops of London until 1973 now incorporates Bishop's Park and is a lovely green area in a heavily built part of London as well as home to some important historic buildings. Also a museum which charts the history of the palace back to the 11th century (and the area itself back to prehistoric times). Of note in the museum includes an entire room dedicated to Bishop Henry Compton's botanical exploits where he would gather all kinds of plants from the North American colony and grow them in the palace garden. Sadly the garden itself was destroyed when "Capability" Brown's landscaping became fashionable and Compton's codex of plants is missing with exception of a few preserved copies of its pages. There is a small cafe.

points_of_interest.name: Crossness Engines
points_of_interest.description: Four vast elaborately decorated beam engines that pumped Victorian London's poop; they were too heavy to remove when decommissioned. One of them is occasionally set in motion. check website for open days.

points_of_interest.name: Grosvenor Square
points_of_interest.description: Grosvenor Square is a historic garden square in the heart of Mayfair, Westminster. Once a hub for 18th-century fashionable residences, it later became known for its strong American and Canadian diplomatic ties in the 20th century. Today, the square blends its rich history with modern commercial use, offering a serene escape amidst the bustling city. Visitors can enjoy its landscaped gardens and historic charm, making it a pleasant spot to relax and take in the area's storied past.
points_of_interest.address: 15 Grosvenor Square, Westminster, London, W1K 6LD, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Clissold Park
points_of_interest.description: Park with a rich history. It is a former country house and estate and was first opened to the public in 1889.

points_of_interest.name: Petrie Museum of Egyptian Archaeology
points_of_interest.description: Formerly the teaching collection of Sir Flinders Petrie, one of Britain's greatest archaeologists, now preserved by University College London. Exhibits include beaded dresses, sculpture and wall reliefs, items of everyday use, papyri, cartonnage and pottery. Fascinating!

points_of_interest.name: Richmond Hill
points_of_interest.description: The view from the top of the hill (between Friar Stile Road and Nightingale Lane) is protected by an act of parliament and takes in the river, the meadows at the bottom of the hill. Much painted by JMW Turner. Well worth the short walk up the hill and it is on the way to Richmond Park if you are walking from the town.
points_of_interest.address: 116 Richmond Hill, Richmond upon Thames, Richmond, TW10 6RJ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Royal Naval College
points_of_interest.description: Built by Christopher Wren in 1694 as the Greenwich Hospital for the relief and support of seamen and their dependents and for the improvement of navigation. It became the Royal Naval College in 1869. In 1999 the University of Greenwich moved in, and was joined by Trinity College of Music in 2001. Best known for its Painted Hall, with elaborate ceiling and wall paintings executed by Sir James Thornhill between 1707 and 1726.
points_of_interest.address: Old Royal Naval College, 2 Cutty Sark Gdns, SE10 9NN
points_of_interest.hours: Painted Hall and Chapel daily 10AM-5PM, closed 24-26 Dec

points_of_interest.name: London Dungeon
points_of_interest.description: As with any Merlin attraction, it is arguably overpriced for what it is. Brings to life the gorier elements of London's past both real life and fictional. Including the execution of Charles I after the English Civil War, the bubonic plague, Jack the Ripper, Mrs. Lovett's pie shop and Sweeney Todd's barber shop with faithful recreations of disaster, disease, and torture using live actors. Younger children may be scared.
points_of_interest.address: County Hall, Westminster Bridge Rd, SE1 7PB
points_of_interest.hours: M–W 10AM–5PM, Th 11AM–5PM, F 10AM–5PM, Sa Su 10AM–6PM (open until 6PM during school holidays)

points_of_interest.name: Museum of Brands
points_of_interest.description: A history of British consumer culture told through over 12,000 food packages, toys, advertisements, and consumer products. The centrepiece of the museum is the "time tunnel" that takes you through the decades from the Victorian era to the present day. Other exhibits cover innovations in packaging, personalised labels, the future of eco-friendly packaging, and how individual brands have changed over time, among other topics. The time tunnel takes about an hour or two, depending on how much time you spend looking at the details of all the items on display, and the other exhibits are much smaller. The gift shop has a mix of nostalgia-themed products and reusable items to reduce your use of plastic (which may be very welcome after seeing so much packaging!).

points_of_interest.name: Wandsworth Museum
points_of_interest.description: A modest museum covering local history which relocated in 2010; has an excellent cafe.

points_of_interest.name: SIS/MI6 Building
points_of_interest.description: Imposing building on the waterfront with a huge number of CCTV cameras and looks more fortified than a prison. Quite a sight to behold and you're able to walk around the outskirts of the building but can guarantee that you're being watched when you do.

points_of_interest.name: Chelsea Physic Garden
points_of_interest.description: Garden founded by apothecaries in the 17th century to the medicinal properties of plants. It was only opened to the public in the 1980s, when it became a charity. The heat-sink caused by its thick walls, combined with the general waste heat of London itself, keeps the garden much warmer than it would otherwise be at this latitude. Due to this, the garden contains the world's most northerly example of a grapefruit outside of a greenhouse, and the largest fruiting olive tree in the country. The collection contains thousands of different plant species.
points_of_interest.hours: Nov-Mar: M-F 11AM–3PM; Apr–Oct: M 11AM–5PM, Tu–F Su 11AM–6PM (Late Openings Jul-Aug T W 11AM-10PM, last entry 8:30PM)

points_of_interest.name: God's Own Junkyard
points_of_interest.description: A museum of sorts in a converted warehouse displaying hundreds of illuminated signs (neon and bulb signs) including signs of businesses, decorative signs, movie props and artworks.
points_of_interest.address: Unit 12, Ravenswood Industrial Estate, Shernhall Street, E17 9HQ

points_of_interest.name: The Jewel Tower
points_of_interest.description: This small tower across the road from the Houses of Parliament is the only part of the original Palace of Westminster still standing. While it is overshadowed in splendour by the surrounding buildings, it's well worth a visit, and has good displays about the early history of Westminster.
points_of_interest.hours: daily in summer, Sa, Su only in winter.

points_of_interest.name: Burgh House and Hampstead Museum
points_of_interest.description: This beautiful grade I listed Georgian building houses the Hampstead Museum, which has an interesting collection of exhibits on the history of the local area.

points_of_interest.name: Heath Robinson Museum
points_of_interest.description: Small museum devoted to the life & work of British Artist William Heath Robinson who is renowned for his pictures of impossible contraptions. Café on site. Set in attractive park.
points_of_interest.address: Pinner Memorial Park, West End Lane, Pinner HA5 1AE

points_of_interest.name: Chinatown
points_of_interest.description: The main sights to see in London's Chinatown are the expressions of Chinese culture and Eastern ambience in Chinatown, and for a good Chinese meal. There are few souvenir shops for tourists and no museums or temples.
points_of_interest.address: 37-38 Gerrard Street, Westminster, London, W1D 5QB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Fassnidge Park
points_of_interest.description: Fassnidge Park, located in the London Borough of Hillingdon, is a charming green space nestled within the Green Belt. This scenic park offers a mix of open fields and woodlands, providing a peaceful retreat for visitors. With picnic areas, walking trails, and plenty of natural beauty, it’s an ideal spot for families and nature lovers alike. Its accessible location, close to both urban amenities and countryside landscapes, makes it a popular destination for those seeking a relaxing day outdoors.

points_of_interest.name: St Paul's Cathedral
points_of_interest.description: The great domed cathedral of St Paul's, designed by Sir Christopher Wren to replace the Gothic medieval cathedral destroyed in 1666 in the Great Fire of London, was built between 1675–1710. Of the most famous London sights, St Paul's is the one most conveniently located for the Barbican. It's a significant building in British history, having been the site of the funerals of several British military leaders (Nelson, Wellington, Churchill), and significantly held peace services marking the end of the two world wars. The cathedral is also famous for its ''Whispering Wall'', as well as its stunning view over the city. The crypt is also open to the public, holding the tombs of Nelson, Wellington and Christopher Wren. It is possible to sidestep the admission charge by entering for one of the midday services, even if you don't take part, or for the daily [https://www.stpauls.co.uk/choral-evensong-at-st-pauls choral evensong] in the late afternoon. However, you'd still need a ticket to get to the top. 17px Photography is not allowed.

points_of_interest.name: Wesley's Chapel and Leysian Mission
points_of_interest.description: John Wesley, founder of the Methodist church, laid the foundation stone, preached here and is buried behind the chapel. The site also contains the Museum of Methodism.

points_of_interest.name: Victoria Park
points_of_interest.description:
Victoria Park (known colloquially as Vicky Park or the People's Park) is a park in the London Borough of Tower Hamlets in East London, England.

It is the largest park in Tower Hamlets and one of London's most visited green spaces with approximately 9 million visitors every year. The park spans 86.18 hectares of open space and opened to the public in 1845.
points_of_interest.address: 9 Gunmakers Lane, Tower Hamlets, London, E3 5PE, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Gandhi's Student Accommodation
points_of_interest.description: Step back in time and explore the humble surroundings where Mahatma Gandhi once resided during his student years. This historic site offers a unique glimpse into the simple life of one of the world's most influential leaders. Visitors can see the modest quarters, which reflect Gandhi's austere lifestyle and commitment to simplicity. The accommodation provides a quiet, contemplative atmosphere, allowing guests to connect with the ideals that shaped Gandhi's philosophy. It’s a must-visit for history enthusiasts and those seeking inspiration from the life of a global icon.

points_of_interest.name: Chislehurst Caves
points_of_interest.description: A seriously underlooked attraction, the caves are not in fact caves but a twenty-mile long network of passageways, carved from the chalk deep under Chislehurst . Used as a massive air-raid shelter during World War II, the Caves are now a local tourist attraction. Tours often last for an hour, where you'll learn the fascinating history as well as hear ghost and horror stories.
points_of_interest.hours: W-Su 10AM-4PM, seven days during school holidays

points_of_interest.name: Apsley House
points_of_interest.description: The Wellington Museum The London residence of the Dukes of Wellington, which now acts as a museum for the inaugural and most famous holder of the title. It boasts an impressive collection of paintings, sculptures, medals and swords. Perhaps the most bizarre item in Wellington's collection is a nude statue of Napoleon Bonaparte, commissioned by the emperor himself and bought by the British government following his defeat at the Battle of Waterloo as a gift for the duke.
points_of_interest.address: 149 Piccadilly, Hyde Park Corner, London, W1J 7NT

points_of_interest.name: Hackney Downs
points_of_interest.description: Near Clapton Ponds, has free tennis courts and is nice for cycle, though a bit plain and squarish.
points_of_interest.address: 61 Downs Road, Hackney, London, E5 8QP, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Pollock's Toy Museum
points_of_interest.description: A treasure trove of antique toys exhibited in a warren of 6 rooms above the toy shop of the same name. A very charming place indeed, though the doll rooms are a bit gruesome.

points_of_interest.name: Old Vicarage School
points_of_interest.description: The Old Vicarage School is a charming and historic destination that offers a glimpse into the past. This beautifully preserved building showcases architectural details and a sense of nostalgia, making it a fascinating spot for history enthusiasts. Visitors can explore the grounds, learn about its significance, and enjoy the peaceful atmosphere. It’s a great place to step back in time and appreciate the stories it holds.

points_of_interest.name: Trinity Hospital
points_of_interest.description: Tucked away near the River Thames, Trinity Hospital is a historic group of almshouses in Greenwich, London. Originally built in 1613-14 by Henry Howard, Earl of Northampton, it was established to provide housing for 12 local residents and eight from his birthplace in Norfolk. Rebuilt in 1812 in Gothic style, this Grade II* listed building offers a glimpse into the area's rich history. Its charming architecture and riverside location make it a worthwhile stop for those exploring Greenwich.

points_of_interest.name: London Eye
points_of_interest.description: An enormous, 135-metre-high observation wheel with 32 exterior glass-walled capsules. It offers incomparable views over central London and up to 40 km (25 mi) away on a good day. Tickets are sold for specific times, so if visitors wish to go on the London Eye at a specific time, they are strongly advised to book in advance, particularly in the summer. On a busy day, you can easily spend 1-3 hr queuing just to buy a ticket. However, you can also purchase tickets in advance online. Then you can collect your tickets at the London Eye in a separate queue, which takes a few minutes or less.
points_of_interest.hours: Jun-Sep 10AM-9PM daily, Oct-May 10AM-8PM daily (except 25 Dec and 3-8 Jan)

points_of_interest.name: St Mary Abbots
points_of_interest.description: Although there has been a parish church on the site since the 13th century, the present building dates only from 1872. It was designed by Sir George Gilbert Scott (perhaps most famous for St Pancras station and hotel), who was a parishioner, and it has the tallest church spire in London. Imposing and formidable, without necessarily being beautiful, it is nonetheless Grade II* listed.

points_of_interest.name: Imperial War Museum
points_of_interest.description: Fronted by two immense guns from Royal Navy battleships, the IWM focuses on British military history since 1914. The central atrium display of objects bearing "witness to war" (everything from a Harrier Jump Jet to a battle-scarred press Land Rover) branches into immersive and sensitive exhibitions on the First and Second World Wars, modern warfare, the Holocaust, and more. The same institution owns the ''HMS Belfast'' (South Bank), ''Cabinet War Rooms'' (Westminster), and ''Duxford Air Museum'' (Cambridgeshire - a day trip from London).

points_of_interest.name: Redbridge Central Library & Museum
points_of_interest.description: Interesting structure from an architectural point of view. Unfortunately it is also the locale of choice for the native ''rude-boys'' to hang out, alas this is not due to the educational value of the institution.

points_of_interest.name: Palace of Westminster
points_of_interest.description: more widely known as the '''Houses of Parliament''' On the UNESCO World Heritage List, the Palace of Westminster is the seat of Parliament in the United Kingdom. It's often termed the "Mother of All Parliaments" - an exaggeration, but perhaps only a slight one. The present building largely dates from the 19th century when it was rebuilt following a fire in a splendid example of Victorian neo-Gothic architecture. The House of Commons (elected Members of Parliament or MPs) is located to the north of the building and is decorated with green leather upholstery, and the House of Lords (unelected Lords) is located to the south and decorated with red leather upholstery.

points_of_interest.name: Camden Arts Centre
points_of_interest.description: A contemporary arts centre with exhibitions focused on exposing new talent. Housed in a lovely Victorian mansion.
points_of_interest.hours: Tu-Su 10AM-6PM, W 10AM-9PM, closed M and national holidays

points_of_interest.name: RAF Museum
points_of_interest.description: The Royal Air Force Museum is a must-visit destination for aviation enthusiasts, offering a fascinating glimpse into the history of the Royal Air Force. With two public sites in London and Cosford, the museum showcases a vast collection of historic aircraft, interactive exhibits, and stories of bravery and innovation. The London site, located at the former Hendon Aerodrome, was opened by Queen Elizabeth II in 1972 and features iconic planes and immersive displays. The Cosford site, merged with the museum in 1998, adds even more depth to the RAF's storied past. A perfect day out for families and history buffs alike.
points_of_interest.address: Grahame Park Way, London, NW7 2LA, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Benjamin Franklin House
points_of_interest.description: The only remaining home of Benjamin Franklin in the world. The founding father of the United States lived here from 1757 to 1775. Many exhibits charting his life and achievements as well as artefacts. A special Historical Experience Show runs W-Su at noon, 1PM, 2PM, 3:15PM, and 4:15PM all year round.

points_of_interest.name: Lammas Park
points_of_interest.description: The name derives from 'Lammas lands', which were used for grazing cattle in medieval times. Bowling green, croquet pitch, tennis courts, children's playground and playcentre. The park nearly adjoins Walpole park mentioned below.

points_of_interest.name: Tower Bridge
points_of_interest.description: Magnificent 19th-century bridge, decorated with high towers and featuring a drawbridge. The bridge opens several times each day to permit ships to pass through – timings are dependent on demand, and are not regularly scheduled. When Tower Bridge was built, the area to the west of it was a bustling port – necessitating a bridge that could permit tall boats to pass. Now the South Bank area sits to its west, and the regenerated Butler's Wharf area of shops and riverside restaurants lie to its east. You can get the lift to the top level of the bridge and admire the view. Glass floors provide an interesting perspective for the brave. The museum highlights the bridge's history and engineering, and there are photographic exhibitions along the walkways between the towers.
points_of_interest.address: Tower Bridge, London, EC3N 4AB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Two Temple Place
points_of_interest.description: Astor House A former home for William Waldorf Astor, a wealthy American moved to London at the end of 19th century. This Victorian house, built between 1892-1895 by John Loughborough Pearson. is in an eclectic Neo-Gothic style. It's richly decorated from outside, but even more rich and heavily eclectic inside. The building is owned by the ''[http://bulldogtrust.org/ Bulldog Trust]'' and it's open to the public during exhibitions. For exact dates/time check with the [http://www.twotempleplace.org/exhibitions/ exhibitions schedule]. A café, a shop and a cloakroom are open for visitors during these days.
points_of_interest.hours: Only during exhibitions Jan-Apr: M Th-Sa 10AM-4:30PM; W 10AM-9PM; Su 11AM-4:30PM

points_of_interest.name: Whitechapel Art Gallery
points_of_interest.description: Whitechapel has been a champion of Modern Art since 1901, and has held exhibitions of greats such as Picasso, Pollock and Frida Kahlo and supported British Artists such as Gilbert & George and Lucian Freud. The space continues to hold regular new exhibitions with additional linked events on Thursday evenings. There is a cafe and a small art bookshop. Free entry. There are excellent facilities for disabled people (visual, hearing and physical).

points_of_interest.name: Kensal Green Cemetery
points_of_interest.description: One of the "Magnificent Seven" Georgian-Victorian cemeteries in London.

points_of_interest.name: Crofton Roman Villa
points_of_interest.description: The only villa open to the public in Greater London. It was inhabited from about AD 140-400 and was the centre of a large farming estate. Today you can see the remains of 10 rooms protected inside a public viewing building. Remains include tiled (tessellated) floors and the under-floor heating system (hypocaust).
points_of_interest.address: Crofton Roman Villa, Crofton Rd, Orpington
points_of_interest.hours: Apr-Oct, Bank Holidays, W F 10AM-1PM and 2PM-5PM, Su 2PM-5PM

points_of_interest.name: Handel & Hendrix in London
points_of_interest.description: Handel House Museum Home to the baroque composer George Frideric Handel from 1723 until his death in 1759. Some of the greatest classical music ever composed was done so at this address. The museum charts Handel's life and works and offers recitals of music in the magnificent setting of the period rooms. By contrast, next door was home to Jimi Hendrix when he lived in London in 1969, and entry to this top-floor flat is included.

points_of_interest.name: London Fields
points_of_interest.description: There are records of a public park at this site going back to the 16th century. Every Saturday, there is a farmers' market selling here, complemented by many others selling hand-made jewellery, gifts, childrenswear and vintage clothing.

points_of_interest.name: Wellcome Collection
points_of_interest.description: Sir Henry Solomon Wellcome's vast collection of medical artefacts and art work that together explore what it means to be human. Special health related exhibitions.

points_of_interest.name: Terrace Gardens
points_of_interest.description: Terrace Gardens is a picturesque destination offering stunning views and a serene atmosphere. Visitors can explore well-manicured pathways, vibrant floral displays, and cozy seating areas perfect for relaxation. The gardens often host cultural events and seasonal activities, making them a charming spot for both locals and travelers. With its natural beauty and tranquil ambiance, Terrace Gardens is an ideal place to unwind and enjoy the outdoors.
points_of_interest.address: 90 Richmond Hill, Richmond upon Thames, Richmond, TW10 6RJ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Ranger's House
points_of_interest.description: Ranger's House is a charming Georgian mansion located near Greenwich Park in Blackheath, southeast London. Once the official residence of the Ranger of Greenwich Park, this historic Grade I listed building offers a glimpse into the past. Its elegant design and tranquil rose garden provide a peaceful retreat from the city. Since 2002, it has been home to the Wernher Collection, showcasing an impressive array of art. Perfect for history enthusiasts and those seeking a serene escape, Ranger's House is a hidden gem worth exploring.

points_of_interest.name: Southbank Centre
points_of_interest.description: Large 1960s development on the South Bank. Built largely of concrete, views on its architectural merits vary considerably. Presents a varied programme of music, literature, dance, performances and exhibitions on contemporary art and culture at its venues the Royal Festival Hall, Queen Elizabeth Hall and The Hayward. A host of new eateries and shops have now opened along the riverside and terrace. The Royal Festival Hall hosts almost daily classical music concerts throughout the year, tickets often available on the day. The Royal Festival Hall opened in 1951 and was substantially altered in 1964. Its 2007 renovation held true to its 1960s design. Free events are held daily, ranging from free music to festivals, interactive art installations to the popular slow food market.

points_of_interest.name: 575 Wandsworth Road
points_of_interest.description: 575 Wandsworth Road, London, was the home of Kenyan poet and civil servant Khadambi Asalache until his death in 2006. Following his death he left it to the National Trust, which opened the house as a museum for pre-booked guided tours.

points_of_interest.name: Diana Memorial Fountain
points_of_interest.description: More of an artificial stream than a fountain, flowing in an oval through an open grassy area which, in normal summers, is a popular paddling spot for children and grown-ups alike.
points_of_interest.address: West Carriage Drive, Westminster, London, W2 2UH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Valentines Park
points_of_interest.description: A pleasant green area, Essex County Cricket team used to play on the pitch in the western side of the park.
points_of_interest.address: 30 Holcombe Road, Redbridge, Ilford, IG1 4XE, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Buckingham Palace
points_of_interest.description: The main residence of His Majesty King Charles III, Her Royal Highness Queen Camilla, and latterly of HM Queen Elizabeth II. In the summer, 19 State Rooms are open to the public. Places are strictly limited, and it might not be possible to just turn up and get a ticket for a specific entry time, visitors should book in advance to ensure admission.
points_of_interest.address: Ambassador's Court, Westminster, London, SW1A 1AA, United Kingdom
points_of_interest.hours: Summer opening: 31 Jul-29 Sep 9:45AM-3:45PM (closed rest of year)

points_of_interest.name: Fenton House
points_of_interest.description: A magnificent old house dating from 1667 that is administered by the National Trust. It is most famous for its globally important collection of early keyboard instruments, and there is also a fine collection of art and porcelain. Frequently hosts recitals.

points_of_interest.name: London Transport Museum
points_of_interest.description: In many cities a local transport museum would be of very narrow interest - not London, however! London's public transport is iconic, and the story of how it developed from horse and cart through early buses, Tube trains and trolleybuses to the present day is well worth coming to find out about. There is plenty of opportunity to clamber aboard the historic buses and Tube trains on display. Also, because London's transport is so well known, the museum shop contains plenty of items that make interesting and original gifts and souvenirs.

points_of_interest.name: Osterley Park and House
points_of_interest.description: A Tudor manor house with a neoclassical facade and interior design resembling an Italian palazzo. It was owned by the Child family who were bankers to the royal family. Osterley Park is a popular filming location, the music room while small was used for ''Batman: The Dark Knight Rises'' and exterior shots of the house were used for an ITV production of ''Vanity Fair''.
points_of_interest.hours: House 4 Mar-1 Nov W-Su 1PM-4:30PM, gardens 3 Mar-1 Nov W-Su 11AM-5PM, park 29 Mar-24 Oct 8AM-7:30PM, 25 Oct-28 Mar 8AM-6PM

points_of_interest.name: Tower of London
points_of_interest.description: Founded by William the Conqueror in 1066, enlarged and modified by successive sovereigns, the Tower is today one of the world's most famous and spectacular fortresses and a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Discover its 900-year history as a royal palace and fortress, prison and place of execution, mint, arsenal, menagerie and jewel house. In the winter you can skate on the dry moat. The Tower contains enough buildings and exhibits to keep a family busy for a full day, with plenty of both warlike and domestic contents. Some areas, such as the St John's Chapel in the White Tower, do not allow photography, but these are clearly signposted. Beefeaters, who are all retired sergeant majors from the British Army, provide guided tours for free as well as ceremonial security. See history come alive – go to the '''Ceremony of the Keys''' at the Tower of London. This ceremony, the locking up of the Tower, has been performed every night at 10PM for 800 years. Tickets for the ceremony are free but MUST be prearranged.
points_of_interest.address: Inner Ward, Tower Hamlets, London, EC3N 4AB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: International Petroleum Exchange
points_of_interest.description: One of the world's largest energy futures and options exchanges. The Brent Crude marker which represents an important benchmark for global oil prices is traded here. It also houses the European Climate Exchange, where emissions trading takes place.

points_of_interest.name: Wilton's Music Hall
points_of_interest.description: Wilton's Wilton's Music Hall is the oldest Grand Music Hall in the world. Built in 1858 it has had a long and colourful history. Wilton's has been the haunt of Victorian sailors (and their ladies), become a Mission, survived two world wars, being a rag warehouse, being forgotten, becoming derelict and has ended up as a theatre once more. It is now a performance space offering entertainment of as wide a variety as puppetry to poetry and has launched a capital appeal to save it from crumbling.

points_of_interest.name: Queens Club
points_of_interest.description: Queen's Club is a historic venue famous for hosting the men's tennis warm-up event before Wimbledon. This elegant Victorian building boasts facilities for badminton and squash, showcasing its rich sporting heritage. Nearby, the National Tennis Centre in Roehampton aims to foster future champions, enhancing the area's reputation as a tennis hub.

points_of_interest.name: Down House
points_of_interest.description: It was at Down House that Charles Darwin worked on his scientific theories, and wrote ''On the Origin of Species by Means of Natural Selection'', the book which both scandalised and revolutionised the Victorian world when it was published in 1859. Built in the early 18th century, the house remains much as it was when Darwin lived here. The rooms on the ground floor have been furnished to reflect the domestic life of the family and the first floor offers an interactive exhibition on his life, his research and his discoveries. English Heritage has restored the gardens to their appearance in Darwin's time.

points_of_interest.name: Madame Tussauds
points_of_interest.description: Madame Tussauds is a world-famous waxwork museum, best known for its Grand Hall, with a collection of international royalty, statesmen and world leaders. Visitors generally report that the entrance fee does not warrant the selection of waxworks on show, which rarely resemble celebrities. Also, there is usually a long queue stretching down the road.

points_of_interest.name: Woodberry Wetlands
points_of_interest.description: Stoke Newington Reservoirs Two former Thames Water reservoirs which are now managed as a nature reserve in urban Hackney by the London Wildlife Trust. Has a small visitor centre.

points_of_interest.name: Camera Museum
points_of_interest.description: A downstairs museum dedicated to cameras from the 1800s to present day, including a camera rifle like the one used in ''Licence to Kill''. The museum is a quick visit and worth the stop even for someone with a moderate interest in photography.

points_of_interest.name: Museum of Richmond
points_of_interest.description: The Museum of Richmond, located in the Old Town Hall near Richmond Bridge, offers a fascinating glimpse into the history of Richmond, Kew, Petersham, and Ham. With free admission and open from Tuesday to Saturday, the museum features permanent displays that span from medieval times to the present day. Highlights include 16th-century glass from Richmond Palace, a model of the palace, and a notable painting by Leonard Knyff. Temporary exhibitions and a variety of events further explore the area's rich heritage, making it a must-visit for anyone interested in local history and culture.
points_of_interest.address: Old Town Hall, Whittaker Ave, TW9 1TP

points_of_interest.name: Greenwich Peninsula Ecology Park
points_of_interest.description: A hidden-away green space and wildlife haven in the middle of urban Greenwich. Comes alive in the summer with brightly coloured insects and birds.
points_of_interest.address: The Ecology Park Gatehouse, Thames Path, John Harrison Way, SE10 0QZ

points_of_interest.name: Queen Elizabeth Hall
points_of_interest.description: QEH Music venue hosting daily performances.
points_of_interest.address: Waterloo Bridge, Lambeth, London, SE1 8XT, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Cinema Museum
points_of_interest.description: A somewhat idiosyncratic but interesting museum with limited opening. It can only be visited on guided tours or screenings that can be booked by email or phone. The building is a former workhouse where Charlie Chaplin once lived.

points_of_interest.name: Rose Garden
points_of_interest.description: The roses are mixed with herbaceous plants and bedding flowers so there's always some horticultural interest no matter the time of year, though the roses' peak is in June. Two interesting fountains depict Diana the huntress and a boy seemingly wrestling a dolphin.
points_of_interest.address: South Carriage Drive, Westminster, London, SW1X 7BF, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Eastbury Manor House
points_of_interest.description: Eastbury Manor House is a Grade I listed building situated in the London Borough of Barking and Dagenham in Greater London, England. It dates to the Elizabethan period, although the land on which it was built was formerly part of the demesne of Barking Abbey. The house is owned by the National Trust but has been managed since the 1930s by the London Borough of Barking and Dagenham and its predecessors. It is open to the public for 10 months of every year.

points_of_interest.name: St James's Palace
points_of_interest.description: St James's Palace, the most senior royal palace in London, holds significant historical and ceremonial importance. Built by King Henry VIII in the 1530s, it served as a hunting lodge and retreat, later gaining prominence after the Palace of Whitehall burned down. Although Buckingham Palace became the main royal residence in 1837, St James's Palace remains a key ceremonial site, hosting events like the Accession Council. Its Tudor architecture, with red brick and the Chapel Royal, adds to its charm. Today, it houses various royal offices and is still used for official receptions and family functions.
points_of_interest.address: Stable Yard Road, Westminster, London, SW1A 1BN, United Kingdom
points_of_interest.hours: Not open to the public, but can be seen from the street

points_of_interest.name: Freud Museum
points_of_interest.description: The former home of Sigmund Freud. A wide range of exhibits, most famously including the psycho-analytic couch that all of his patients used. Freud was an avid collector of antiquities and there is a fine collection of Greek, Roman and Oriental pieces on show.

points_of_interest.name: Highgate Wood
points_of_interest.description: A 28-hectare remnant of the great Middlesex Wood which once spread across north London. There is a supervised children's playground, a café and an information centre.
points_of_interest.address: 460 Archway Road, Haringey, London, N6 4NA, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Aldwych station
points_of_interest.description: The TfL-backed Hidden London offers tours around the disused Aldwych tube station which had its own branch on the Piccadilly line. The tour explains the station's unusual history including its use for protection (for both people and historical artefacts held by the British Museum) from the Blitz during WWII. More recently, it was used as a filming location and for testing station equipment and decor. Of note, it was used for filming ''James Bond: Die Another Day'', ''V for Vendetta'' and the Prodigy music video for ''Firestarter''. Tours are roughly an 1 hour and 15 minutes long, wear sturdy shoes (not sandals).

points_of_interest.name: Ruislip Lido
points_of_interest.description: An artificial lake surrounded by woodland, the Waters Edge Pub/Restaurant, a sandy beach (No swimming allowed), narrow gauge railway rides around the lake.

points_of_interest.name: All Hallows by the Tower
points_of_interest.description: All Hallows by the Tower, an historic Anglican church in the City of London, stands near the Tower of London. Dating back to AD 675, it is often called the oldest church in the City, though its exact founding date is debated. The church survived the Great Fire of London in 1666 but suffered damage during World War II. After reconstruction, it was rededicated in 1957. From 1922 to 1962, it was led by Tubby Clayton, founder of the Christian organization Toc H, of which it remains the guild church. This resilient landmark blends rich history with active community life.

points_of_interest.name: Hunterian Museum
points_of_interest.description: Inside the Royal College of Surgeons. Exhibitions on the history of surgery, including medicine, natural history and art. The museum was established by John Hunter (1728-1793), the founder of scientific surgery.

points_of_interest.name: Jack The Ripper Museum
points_of_interest.description: A small museum is set in a Victorian house near the infamous Battle of Cable Street. There are 5 floors including the basement, each dedicated to several aspects of famous murders starting with a recreation of Mitre Square on the first floor, Jack the Ripper's sitting room on the second floor, the police station on the third, a victim's bedroom on the fourth and the mortuary in the basement. There is also a walking tour. Book tickets online to save money, there is also a Halloween special deal.
points_of_interest.address: 12 Cable St, Tower Hill, Whitechapel, E1 8JG

points_of_interest.name: Royal Waterman's Alms Houses
points_of_interest.description: Royal Waterman's Alms Houses, designed by George Porter, is a charming example of 19th-century architecture. Built in 1840–1841 by the Company of Watermen and Lightermen of the City of London, this historic landmark reflects the city's rich maritime heritage. Once home to local watermen, the residents moved out in 1973, and the buildings now serve as private residences. The elegant design and historical significance make it a notable attraction for those exploring the area.

points_of_interest.name: The Royal Academy of Arts
points_of_interest.description: The Royal Academy no longer has a permanent exhibition space, instead hosting art exhibitions. Notable exhibitions have included the paintings of Monet, contemporary art associated with the theme of apocalypse, and Aztec art. Each Summer, the Royal Academy plays host to a Summer Exhibition, displaying 1,200 new works by established and new artists selected by the academy, most of which are available for visitors to buy. Each member has to donate a work of art, so over the years, the academy has built a sizable collection. Exhibitions are invariably excellent, and it is worth paying for audio guides, if they are not included. Visitors should book tickets in advance, as exhibitions are often very popular – particularly shortly after opening.

points_of_interest.name: Abney Park Cemetery
points_of_interest.description: One of the ‘Magnificent Seven’ garden cemeteries of London, which has become a woodland memorial park, popular with local dog owners. There are free guided walks that you can book tickets for online
points_of_interest.address: 52 Bouverie Road, Hackney, London, N16 0AJ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Brunei Gallery, SOAS University of London
points_of_interest.description: An exhibition space that hosts a programme of changing contemporary and historical exhibitions from Asia, Africa and the Middle East, aiming to present and promote cultures from these regions and to be a student resource and public facility. There are live music performances every last Wednesday of every month except December and July.

points_of_interest.name: Royal Botanic Gardens
points_of_interest.description: A UNESCO World Heritage Site, these extensive, historic and beautiful gardens feature elements illustrating significant periods of garden and landscape art from the 18th to the 20th centuries, and a plant collection second to none in the world. Since their creation as a royal estate in 1759, Kew Gardens (as they are commonly known) have made a significant and uninterrupted contribution to the study of plant diversity and economic botany. The gardens cover 120 hectares (300 acres) and are over 1.5 km (0.9mi) long. They contain glasshouses, a conservatory, and numerous installations of buildings, art and of course exotic plant species. The Temperate House, which reopened in May 2018, is the largest surviving Victorian glass structure in the world.
points_of_interest.hours: Open from 10AM everyday, closing times vary

points_of_interest.name: Eltham Palace
points_of_interest.description: Eltham Palace is a historic gem in southeast London, blending medieval grandeur with Art Deco elegance. Once a royal residence, the palace features a stunning great hall with a hammerbeam roof, one of the largest in England. In the 1930s, an Art Deco extension was added, creating a "masterpiece of modern design." Managed by English Heritage, the site offers a fascinating glimpse into history and architecture. Perfect for those who appreciate the intersection of past and present, Eltham Palace is a must-visit for history enthusiasts and design lovers alike.

points_of_interest.name: Undercroft
points_of_interest.description: London's most famous and popular skateboarding area, situated partly underneath Queen Elizabeth Hall along Queen's Walk and the Thames. Also popular with graffiti artists, BMXers and so forth.

points_of_interest.name: Holocaust Memorial
points_of_interest.description: A quiet birch wood surrounds an understated memorial stone inscribed with a quotation from the Book of Lamentation: "For these I weep. Streams of tears flow from my eyes because of the destruction of my people.".
points_of_interest.address: Serpentine Road, Westminster, London, SW1X 7BF, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Epping Forest
points_of_interest.description: Large expanse of green space stretching 12 miles (19 km) from Forest Gate into Essex. Despite the name it is not completely wooded: in medieval times "forest" meant a royal hunting ground.
points_of_interest.address: 22 Baldwin's Hill, Loughton, IG10 1SD, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Guards Museum
points_of_interest.description: The Guards Museum is a fascinating military museum located in the heart of Central London. Situated within Wellington Barracks on Birdcage Walk, it is just a short stroll from Buckingham Palace. This unique museum showcases the rich history of the five regiments of Foot Guards, offering visitors a glimpse into their storied past through engaging exhibits and displays. Whether you're a history enthusiast or simply curious about London's military heritage, The Guards Museum provides an insightful and memorable experience.

points_of_interest.name: Hampstead Parish Church
points_of_interest.description: Parish Church of St John-at-Hampstead The church building is rather lovely but it is the graveyard that will most interest visitors. Notable personalities buried here include Sir John Constable (artist), Hugh Gaitskell (Labour Party leader and Chancellor of the Exchequer), Kay Kendall (actress) and several members of the du Maurier family. Tomb trails are available at the church. Visiting should be OK in daylight hours, but check ahead if you are making a special trip.

points_of_interest.name: St Augustine's
points_of_interest.description: An ornate Anglican church, sometimes incorrectly called the "Cathedral of North London". The church was built in the 1870s, and has altar screens designed by Sir Giles Gilbert Scott in 1930.

points_of_interest.name: Syon Park
points_of_interest.description: The stately home of the Dukes of Northumberland for 400 years, Syon House and its 200-acre estate are located between Brentford and Isleworth. The main house was built to a design by the English architect Robert Adams, the grounds laid out by Capability Brown. The Great Conservatory, commissioned to be built in 1826, was featured in the Peter Cook and Dudley Moore film ''Bedazzled'', and is a popular local wedding venue; Syon House itself has appeared in a vast number of period dramas. Well worth a visit.
points_of_interest.hours: House: 24 Mar-31 Oct W Th Su, bank holiday Mondays, Good Friday, Easter Saturday 11AM-5PM (last entry 4:15PM), gardens 10:30AM-5PM daily or dusk if earlier except 25-26 Dec

points_of_interest.name: St Bartholomew-the-Great
points_of_interest.description: Founded in 1123, by jester-turned-monk Rahere, this Norman church is one of the oldest in London. It was damaged in the Dissolution but managed to escape both the Great Fire and the Blitz. This is a Grade I listed building. Tourists are welcome when services are not in progress and are charged an admission fee (which does not apply to those coming to pray or use the café).

points_of_interest.name: Islington Museum
points_of_interest.description: Islington Museum is a public museum dedicated to the history of the London Borough of Islington. It opened in 2008 and covers various themes on local and social history.

points_of_interest.name: William Morris Society
points_of_interest.description: Kelmscott House A small museum dedicated to William Morris and the works of the Arts and Crafts movement. Not to be confused with much larger Kelmscott Manor near Lechlade-on-Thames in Gloucestershire.

points_of_interest.name: The Whitgift Almshouses
points_of_interest.description: The Whitgift Almshouses, also known as the Hospital of the Holy Trinity, stands as a historic gem in Croydon’s town center. Founded in the 16th century by Archbishop John Whitgift, it was established to support the local community. Today, it serves as a charming retirement community, offering residents a blend of independence and support. Nestled around a picturesque private quadrangle, the almshouses provide a serene environment for self-catered living, honoring its legacy while embracing modern needs. This tranquil oasis in the heart of Croydon is a testament to enduring heritage and community care.

points_of_interest.name: Sherlock Holmes Museum
points_of_interest.description: Also known as 221B Baker St Discover mementoes of the famous fictional detective. In reality, this was a lodging house used in the late 1800s and has three floors. The first floor contains Sherlock Holmes' study with Watson's desk, and has bullet holes spelling the initials VR (for ''Victoria Regina'', Latin for Queen Victoria) much to the chagrin of the landlady Mrs. Hudson. Next to that is Holmes' bedroom with a rogues' gallery containing photographs of several notable Victorian-era murderers including Lizzy Bourdain. The remaining rooms upstairs have waxwork figures and artefacts referencing the novels, as well as their adaptations to stage and screen.20px Photography allowed, though filming requires permission. Prebooking is recommended to circumvent long queues.

points_of_interest.name: The Clowns Archive
points_of_interest.description: Museum of clowning, unique collection of faces on eggs. Open only first Friday of every month from noon-5PM.
points_of_interest.address: Holy Trinity Church, Beechwood Rd, E8 3DY

points_of_interest.name: Bedford Square
points_of_interest.description: This wonderful square was built between 1775 and 1783 as an upper middle class residential area takes its name from the Dukes of Bedford, who were the main landlords in Bloomsbury. Distinguished residents have included Lord Eldon, one of Britain's longest serving and most celebrated Lord Chancellors. This is one of the best preserved set pieces of Georgian architecture in London and the majority of the buildings are grade I listed. The gardens are private and always remain locked.

points_of_interest.name: The National Archives
points_of_interest.description: All non-classified government documents can be read and photographed here, with a (free) reader's card having been obtained. There is also a small museum, which does not require the card to access.
points_of_interest.hours: Tu Th 9AM-7PM, W F Sa 9AM-5PM, Su M closed

points_of_interest.name: Charlton House
points_of_interest.description: Charlton House is a charming Jacobean building located in Charlton, within the Royal Borough of Greenwich in south-east London. This historic site began as a grand residence for a nobleman with ties to the Stuart royal family. Over the centuries, it has served various roles, including a wartime hospital, a museum, and a library. Today, Charlton House is managed by the Royal Greenwich Heritage Trust, offering a glimpse into its rich history and architectural elegance. It remains a fascinating destination for those exploring London’s hidden gems.

points_of_interest.name: BFI Southbank
points_of_interest.description: Tucked under Waterloo Bridge, BFI Southbank, formerly known as the National Film Theatre, pitches itself as the home of film and has three screens showing classic (including silent), foreign language and less mainstream films. It has a new entrance on Theatre Alley, a shop dedicated to film, an interactive exhibition space and an excellent bar/restaurant at the back. Visitors can also access the Mediatheque - wind your way through the BFI's extensive film and TV archive for free. Cool bar and restaurant. Tickets are generally available on the spur of the moment.

points_of_interest.name: The Serpentine
points_of_interest.description: The ''Serpentine'' is a long, thin artificial lake within Hyde Park which contains a range of waterfowl and fish. It was first made by damming the River Westbourne but it is now fed by three boreholes. The western end of the lake is actually in Kensington Gardens, in which it is called '''The Long Water'''. Swimming and boating are popular activities on the Serpentine; see 'Do' section.
points_of_interest.address: Serpentine Road, Westminster, London, W2 2UH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Queen Elizabeth's Hunting Lodge
points_of_interest.description: Excellently preserved and unusual example of a Tudor-era timber-framed "hunting stand". Built for King Henry VIII, contrary to the popular name of the building. The building houses exhibitions on Tudor culture and the top floor still provides a fine view of Epping Forest.

points_of_interest.name: Henry VII Lady Chapel
points_of_interest.description: Described as "the wonder of the entire world", this chapel at the eastern end of Westminster Abbey is a breathtakingly beautiful masterpiece of medieval architecture.
points_of_interest.address: 7 Old Palace Yard, Westminster, London, SW1P 3JY, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Highgate Cemetery
points_of_interest.description: Take a guided tour of the overgrown Western Cemetery which gives it a special beauty and charm, or visit the East Cemetery unaccompanied where you will find the grave of Karl Marx. There are at least 850 notable people buried at Highgate, from authors Douglas Adams and George Eliot, to Jean Simmons and Michael Faraday; high society Victorians wouldn't be seen dead anywhere else. It has been said that Highgate has the finest collection of Victorian funerary architecture in the country, and the cemetery certainly has more than its fair share of ghosts. There's even a resident vampire!
points_of_interest.hours: East Cemetery: M-F 10AM-dusk, West Cemetery: only via guided tours 1 Mar-30 Nov M-F 2PM, 1 Nov-28 Feb Sa Su hourly 11AM-3PM, 1 Mar-31 Oct Sa Su hourly 11AM-4PM

points_of_interest.name: BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandi
points_of_interest.description: BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandir is a stunning Hindu temple that showcases intricate architecture and serene surroundings. Known for its beautiful carvings and peaceful ambiance, it is a spiritual and cultural gem. Visitors can explore the temple, learn about its significance, and enjoy the tranquil gardens. The mandir is a place of worship and reflection, offering a glimpse into Hindu heritage and traditions. It’s a must-visit for those interested in history, architecture, and spirituality.

points_of_interest.name: St Botolph's Aldersgate
points_of_interest.description: A medieval church that was rebuilt in the late 18th century, noted for its well-preserved interior. The former churchyard was converted into a public space in 1880, called Postman's Park as it was frequented by workers from the nearby Post Office headquarters.

points_of_interest.name: Museum of the Order of St John
points_of_interest.description: Museum in the former English headquarters of the Knights Hospitaller, covering the history of the order from crusading knights to modern first aid organisation.
points_of_interest.address: St John’s Gate, St John’s Lane, EC1M 4DA

points_of_interest.name: Emery Walker Trust
points_of_interest.description: The Emery Walker Trust is a historic house museum located in London, showcasing the former home of Emery Walker, a prominent figure in the Arts and Crafts movement. The property offers a unique glimpse into Walker's life and work, with its well-preserved architecture and interiors reflecting the style of the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Visitors can explore the house, which features original furnishings and decorative elements, providing insight into the cultural and artistic influences of the time. It’s a must-visit for those interested in history, design, and the Arts and Crafts movement.

points_of_interest.name: Clock Tower Museum
points_of_interest.description: A museum highlighting Croydon in the past and present includes the Riesco Gallery. Also exhibitions on the gifted black composer Samuel Coleridge-Taylor (1875-1912) who lived most of his life in Croydon. His works include The Song of Hiawatha, a great favourite (before World War II) at the Royal Albert Hall conducted by Sir Malcolm Sargent. The impressive Town Hall is adjacent.
points_of_interest.address: 39-41 Katharine Street, Croydon, CR0 1NX, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Wallace Collection
points_of_interest.description: The Wallace Collection is one of the world's finest private art collections, the best known of which is Frans Hals's work ''The Laughing Cavalier''. Other artists on display include Rembrandt, Titian, Poussin, and Reynolds. This is well worth escaping to after the hustle and bustle of Oxford Street.

points_of_interest.name: Museum of the Home
points_of_interest.description: The Museum of the Home, housed in a beautifully restored 18th-century building in Hoxton, offers a fascinating exploration of home life from 1600 to the present. Through thought-provoking exhibits and period room displays, the museum invites visitors to reflect on the concept of "home" and its emotional significance. Following a major refurbishment, the museum reopened in 2021 with expanded exhibition spaces, a café, learning pavilion, and landscaped gardens. This vibrant cultural destination is a must-visit for anyone interested in design, history, and the evolving idea of home. Admission is free, making it accessible to all.

points_of_interest.name: British Telecom Tower
points_of_interest.description: The BT Tower, also known as the GPO Tower, Post Office Tower, and Telecom Tower, is a historic communications tower in Fitzrovia, London. Standing at 581 feet tall, with an additional 39 feet from its aerial rigging, it was the city’s tallest structure from 1964 to 1980. Once home to a revolving restaurant operated by Butlins from 1966 to 1971, the tower now features a 360° LED screen displaying news across central London. In 2024, it was announced that the tower would be sold to MCR Hotels, marking a new chapter for this iconic landmark.

points_of_interest.name: Kew Bridge
points_of_interest.description: Kew Bridge is an elegant crossing over the Tideway, connecting the London Boroughs of Richmond upon Thames and Hounslow. Opened in 1903 by King Edward VII and Queen Alexandra, the bridge offers a blend of historic charm and modern functionality. Designed by John Wolfe-Barry and Cuthbert A. Brereton, it was listed as a Grade II historic structure by Historic England in 1983, recognizing its architectural and cultural significance. Today, Kew Bridge remains a vital transport link and a striking feature of London's riverscape, appealing to both locals and visitors alike.
points_of_interest.address: 8 Kew Bridge, Richmond, TW9 3AW, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Severndroog Castle
points_of_interest.description: An 18th-century folly built as a memorial to Sir William James by his widow. Today you can climb the 86 steps to the top of the castle for amazing views over London and seven different counties.

points_of_interest.name: National Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Three large auditoriums, the Olivier, the Lyttelton and the Cottesloe. The Olivier theatre is the largest with an open stage and a fan shaped auditorium around it. This ensures that all seats provide a good view. Most of the more 'popular' productions are put on here as the space provided is much larger than most theatres. The Lyttelton theatre is more traditional with a proscenium arc with good views from most seats. The Cottesloe is a small studio theatre, seating around 400. Some tickets will be available on the day, either day seats (arrive before 9:30AM and queue) or standby (arrive before 6PM and queue), or you can buy online. Popular shows, especially those around Christmas in the Olivier sell out months in advance. Tickets to The National Theatre are generally better value than most other theatres. There is also the '£15 Travelex' season in the summer (as of 2019) that provides a large number (over 100,000 seats a year) at £10. Booking in advance is required for these. There is also an exhibition space in the Lyttelton theatre foyer that frequently holds popular photographic exhibitions. Free jazz is often played in the evening in the ground floor foyer. During summer there is a free daily outdoor festival of performance, music, comedy and cabaret known as Watch This Space. Deckchairs (and artificial grass) are provided to watch on. Free exhibitions. Backstage tours £5.

points_of_interest.name: Speakers Corner
points_of_interest.description: By custom, in this far northeastern corner of the park (by the Marble Arch Tube stop near Mayfair), people are free to say whatever they like about who and whatever they like (subject to British law, though enforcement is laxer here). Traditionally, Speaker's corner is most active on Sundays when it is not raining and has been recognized for featuring previously unpopular (in the distant past), now mainstream positions on policy and society such as women's rights and Green politics. For some, it is worth checking out to see the lunatics and exhibitionists spouting off but do not feel compelled to stay. Most discussions (if they can be called that) are now recorded and posted onto YouTube, so you would be wise to avoid engaging unless you're confident in what you're arguing and a competent orator, lest you be mocked later. Contrary to its historical reputation for social discourse, the majority of Speaker's corner discussions are now overwhelmingly religious in nature, with many debates/yelling matches over Abrahamic scripture.
points_of_interest.address: Cumberland Gate, Westminster, London, W2 2UH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Wanstead Park / The Temple
points_of_interest.description: Remaining grounds of the 18th century mansion Wanstead House, with woods and ornamental lakes. The Temple (opening hours vary, check website) is the visitor centre covering the history of the park.
points_of_interest.address: 60 Northumberland Avenue, Redbridge, London, E12 5EZ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: St. Margaret's Church
points_of_interest.description: St. Margaret's is the church of the British Parliament, more specifically, the ''parish church of the House of Commons''.

points_of_interest.name: Keats House
points_of_interest.description: The poet John Keats lived here from 1818 to 1820 until he travelled to Rome where he died of tuberculosis, aged just 25. The house was restored in 2009 as a museum with period decor, furnishings and a collection of Keatsiana. Some events take place in the building next door within the grounds (Ten Keats Grove); the building also houses a volunteer-run public library, with a collection of books and periodicals, and free internet access.

points_of_interest.name: Bruce Castle & Museum
points_of_interest.description: Bruce Castle is a manor house, one of the oldest brick houses in England, that is now a public park and museum. The museum mostly concerns the local history of Haringey, and there are regular talks and workshops. Bruce Castle Park has a tree trail and children's playground.

points_of_interest.name: Gunnersbury Park Museum
points_of_interest.description: Local history museum for Ealing and Hounslow, housed in the former home of the Rothschild family.

points_of_interest.name: Postman's Park
points_of_interest.description: Postman's Park is three parks combined, bringing together the gardens of St Botolph's Aldersgate, Christ Church Greyfriars and St Leonard, Foster Lane. One of the largest parks in the City of London, Postman's Park contains the Memorial to Heroic Self Sacrifice; a memorial to ordinary people who died saving the lives of others and might otherwise have been forgotten.
points_of_interest.hours: 8AM–7PM or dusk (whichever is earlier). Closed Christmas Day, Boxing Day and New Year's Day

points_of_interest.name: Sir John Soane's Museum
points_of_interest.description: The former home of architect Sir John Soane, the building has been converted into a museum, displaying some of the objects he collected during his lifetime, including the alabaster sarcophagus of Seti I, and paintings by artists including William Hogarth. There is a display of some of Soane's architectural plans on the upper floor. Be sure to wait in the picture room until the guides open the walls up to reveal further paintings behind. The museum is a little-known tourist attraction, but well worth a visit. Admission free (but you're encouraged to leave a donation), you can walk in on the day.

points_of_interest.name: Hammersmith Bridge
points_of_interest.description: A charming green iron and steel suspension bridge designed by Joseph Bazalgette and built in the 1880s. It marks the halfway point on the famous Oxford/Cambridge university boat race. Ordinarily connecting Hammersmith to Barnes on the south bank of the River Thames, the bridge has been declared unsafe due to structural issues which stem partly from the volume of road traffic it carried, far exceeding what Bazalgette could ever have imagined or designed for, and partly due to three separate attempts by the IRA (in 1939, 1996, and 2000) to blow it up which caused damage to the structure without destroying it.
points_of_interest.hours: Closed to all traffic since August 2020

points_of_interest.name: Hackney Museum
points_of_interest.description: Hackney Museum offers a fascinating glimpse into the rich history of the London Borough of Hackney. Located in the heart of the borough, this engaging museum explores the area's diverse heritage, with a particular focus on its vibrant history of immigration. Through a variety of exhibits, visitors can uncover the stories that have shaped the community over the years. Whether you're a local resident or a curious visitor, the museum provides an insightful and enjoyable experience, highlighting the cultural and social dynamics that make Hackney such a unique and captivating place.
points_of_interest.address: Technology & Learning Centre, 1 Reading Ln, E8 1GQ

points_of_interest.name: Bloomsbury Square
points_of_interest.description: This garden square was established by Lord Southampton in 1665 and is the oldest square in London. It was opened to the public in the 1950s. The square is surrounded by a number of beautiful 18th- and 19th-century buildings and terraces.

points_of_interest.name: Kew Green
points_of_interest.description: Large lawn, split in two by Kew Rd, with St. Mary's Church, Kew Cricket Club and pubs set on or near it.
points_of_interest.address: 77 Kew Green, Richmond upon Thames, Richmond, TW9 3AH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: BFI IMAX Cinema
points_of_interest.description: Set back from the riverside is the BFI IMAX, the largest cinema screen in the UK at 26 m wide, 20 m high. Shows family-friendly 3D IMAX films as well as action films which work well on the huge screen. Also hosts special all-nighters such as the Lord of the Rings Trilogy.

points_of_interest.name: 7 July Memorial
points_of_interest.description: A memorial made out of 52 stainless steel columns representing each of the 52 victims who died in a series of terrorist attacks in the London bombings on July 7th, 2005.
points_of_interest.address: 35 Park Lane, Westminster, London, W1K 1RB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Westminster Abbey
points_of_interest.description: The Abbey charges tourists for entry, but not for worshippers. Attend a church service for free and enjoy some of the finest choral music in London from the choir. Choral Evensong at 3pm (Sa Su) or 5pm (weekdays), depending on time of year, is an especially good bet. The Abbey is the traditional scene for the coronation of British monarchs and the burial place of many past kings and queens. The Abbey contains a good gift shop and the Cellarium Café, which traces its history to the 14th century, is a good place to buy a noontime meal. Westminster Abbey is usually open to visitors from Monday to Saturday throughout the year. On Sundays and religious holidays such as Easter and Christmas, the Abbey is open for worship only. All are welcome and it is free to attend services. Visitor access to the Abbey is via the West Gate of the North Green.
points_of_interest.address: 1 Little Cloisters, Westminster, London, SW1P 3PL, United Kingdom
points_of_interest.hours: Abbey admission: M Tu Th F 9:30AM-3:45PM, W 9:30AM-7PM, Sa 9:30AM-1:45PM (extended in summer to 3:45PM), Su open for worship only, the Abbey closes 1 hr after last admission; Chapter House admission: 10:30AM-4PM daily; Westminster Abbey Museum: 10:30AM-4PM daily; Pyx Chamber: 10:30AM-4PM daily; Cloisters: 8AM-6PM daily

points_of_interest.name: Primrose Hill
points_of_interest.description: A large open grassed hill just to the north of Regent's Park. Offers a free panorama of Central London. The views are probably only bettered by those from Parliament Hill on Hampstead Heath.

points_of_interest.name: Tottenham Marsh
points_of_interest.description: Part of the Lea Valley Park, a natural habitat for many resident plants and animals.
points_of_interest.address: Carbuncle Passage, Haringey, London, N17 9QU, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: London Museum of Water and Steam
points_of_interest.description: formerly known as 'Kew Bridge Steam Museum' This museum of London's water supply is well worth a visit for anyone with an interest in the industrial revolution. Housed in the former Kew Bridge Pumping Station (a fascinating building in its own right), the Steam Museum possesses the finest collection of steam-pumping engines in the world. Different engines are to be seen working on different days, so it is worth checking the website before visiting if a particular engine is of interest. Themed days are a feature of the Steam Museum's calendar, and the purchase of an entry ticket permits limitless further visits throughout the following year.

points_of_interest.name: St Magnus the Martyr
points_of_interest.description: Su Catholic Church of England with bells and smells (incense). There is an impressive model of the old London Bridge.

points_of_interest.name: Somerset House
points_of_interest.description: Somerset House is home to three art galleries: The exceptional '''Courtauld Institute''' displays a collection of 19th- and 20th-century art, including well-known works by Degas, Matisse and Kandinsky; The Gilbert Collection presents a collection of decorative art; and the Hermitage Rooms, the most recent addition to Somerset House, hosts temporary exhibitions of works on loan from the Hermitage Museum in Saint Petersburg. The central courtyard is filled with fountains in the Summer, but in the Winter, an ice rink is installed, it is very popular, so visitors should book in advance, or expect to wait a long time to skate.

points_of_interest.name: Viktor Wynd Museum of Curiosities
points_of_interest.description: A macabre museum modelled on a 17th-century cabinet of curiosities. The museum has no particular theme connecting its exhibits, which are seemingly the most unusual and unnerving objects the owner could find: taxidermy, skulls (human or otherwise), bizarre photographs, strange sex manuals, idols from faraway lands, and similarly eccentric oddities. Upstairs is a bar (free entry) with an emphasis on cocktails and absinthe, and the museum itself is down a gilded spiral staircase beside the counter. The owner has an excellent collection of Leonora Carrington paintings. The space is small, so try to come when it's not too busy (avoid Saturdays). Children are only allowed before 7PM.

points_of_interest.name: Coram's Fields
points_of_interest.description: A park which is run as children's play area. Facilities include a pet's corner, lawns, sports pitches and a nursery. No adults are allowed to enter the park unless they are accompanying children. All visitors are welcome to join the local kids.

points_of_interest.name: Marble Hill House
points_of_interest.description: Marble Hill House is a charming Neo-Palladian villa in Twickenham, built between 1724 and 1729 for Henrietta Howard. Its design influenced Georgian villas and American plantation houses. Acquired by the London County Council in 1903, it was the first 18th-century house preserved by a public body. Restored by the GLC starting in 1965, it is now managed by English Heritage, offering a glimpse into its rich history and architectural significance.

points_of_interest.name: OXO Tower
points_of_interest.description: Home to designer-marker boutiques, selling everything from hats and homeware to wedding dresses and jewellery. Modern gallery on the ground floor which is free and open every day, various cafes, a florists and hairdressers here to. Upstairs there's the Tamesa Brasserie and Bincho Yakitori (Japanese tapas). Also contains a restaurant and bar on the top floor, giving you a great view over the Thames. You pay for the privilege through the food bill, though you can go up the tower and have access to a separate balcony for free. Interesting views of the surrounding South London area and great views of the Embankment.
points_of_interest.address: Barge House Street, Southwark, London, SE1 9PH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Kensington Gardens
points_of_interest.description: The western half of the twin parks and the half that is often forgotten in public consciousness. It tends to be more formal than its neighbouring park.
points_of_interest.address: The Broad Walk, Westminster, London, W2 4RH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Tate Britain
points_of_interest.description: This gallery houses the Tate collection of British art from 1500 through to contemporary art. A side wing collects together the gallery's collection of paintings by Turner, including some stunning seascapes. Temporary exhibitions are exceedingly varied: examples include exhibitions of Turner's paintings of Venice and the work of photographer Wolfgang Tillmans. The best known exhibition is the Turner Prize, consists of works by four artists shortlisted for the annual contemporary art prize, which runs from late October to January each year.

points_of_interest.name: Alexandra Palace
points_of_interest.description: Ally Pally Wood Green's landmark, on a hill overlooking the City of London and the West End. The grand Victorian building was the first place from which the BBC broadcast regular television, but has been gutted by fire on two separate occasions. It now serves as an exhibition and event venue, and is popular for the surrounding Alexandra Park, its boating lake and ice-rink, and its panoramic views over London.
points_of_interest.address: 1 The Avenue, Haringey, London, N10 2QE, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Musical Museum
points_of_interest.description: Something of an undiscovered gem. It houses a vast collection of working automatic musical instruments, from barrel organs to player pianos and beyond.
