Tours with knowledgeable and highly enthusiastic guides are highly recommended, as is the opportunity to listen to the Mighty Wurlitzer (which rises from the floor in the main auditorium). In addition to its function as a museum, the venue also hosts occasional cinema screenings of classic films (preceded by music from the Mighty Wurlitzer, or - in the case of silent film - accompanied by it) and houses a popular cafe with Thames views. Among the unusual (and hard-to-find) items usually available in the gift shop are clocks made from 78 rpm shellac discs, and original player piano rolls.

points_of_interest.name: St Margaret Pattens
points_of_interest.description: St Margaret Pattens, a charming Church of England church in the City of London, is nestled on Eastcheap, near the Monument. This historic site, dedicated to Saint Margaret of Antioch, offers a serene retreat from the city's vibrancy. Its rich history and tranquil atmosphere make it a must-visit for history enthusiasts and those seeking calm. Perfectly situated near key landmarks, it's an ideal stop for explorers of the area.

points_of_interest.name: Novelty Automation
points_of_interest.description: Novelty Automation in Holborn, London, is a one-of-a-kind amusement arcade featuring satirical game machines designed by cartoonist and engineer Tim Hunkin. Each machine is meticulously handcrafted, offering a quirky and humorous take on modern life. Highlights include an expressive photo booth, an interactive "divorce" experience, and a whimsical "small hadron collider." The arcade also showcases three of Hunkin's classic creations previously displayed at Cabaret Mechanical Theatre: The Frisker, Test Your Nerve, and The Chiropodist. This offbeat attraction is a must-visit for those seeking a fun and thought-provoking experience in the heart of London.

points_of_interest.name: The Residence Gallery
points_of_interest.description: The Residence Gallery is a charming destination for art enthusiasts and history buffs alike. Nestled in a beautifully restored 19th-century townhouse, the gallery showcases a diverse collection of contemporary art and historical exhibits. Visitors can explore rotating installations, each offering unique insights into local and international creativity. The building itself is a work of art, blending original architectural details with modern touches. Whether you're here to admire the art or simply soak in the ambiance, The Residence Gallery is a must-visit for anyone seeking a cultural gem in the heart of the city.

points_of_interest.name: Russell Square
points_of_interest.description: The largest square in London. It was established in 1806 by the 5th Duke of Bedford and his statue can still be seen in the square. There is also a café.

points_of_interest.name: Strawberry Hill House
points_of_interest.description: Eccentric Gothic home of 18th-century poet and author, Horace Walpole, son of England's first prime minister.

points_of_interest.name: Former City Hall
points_of_interest.description: Former offices of the Greater London Authority. A radically-designed glass fronted and rounded building, previously headquarters for London's Mayor and Assembly. City Hall has now be relocated to The Crystal, a building in Greenwich, near to the cable car. The old building is disused and not open to the public, but can be viewed from the outside.

points_of_interest.name: Albert Memorial
points_of_interest.description: Highly detailed, Gothic-style monument to commemorate Prince Albert, husband of Queen Victoria. Opposite the '''Royal Albert Hall'''.
points_of_interest.address: South Carriage Drive, Westminster, London, SW7 2AJ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Green Park
points_of_interest.description: In contrast to the other Royal Parks in the area, Green Park can seem a little plain. It has no lakes or buildings and few monuments. It is still a pleasant green, lightly wooded, area in the centre of London, neighbouring two other parks and Buckingham Palace.
points_of_interest.address: 100 Piccadilly, Westminster, London, W1J 9HU, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Wembley Stadium
points_of_interest.description: The large arch, the answer to the old stadium's twin towers, is an impressive structure and is often lit up to celebrate special occasions (such as London winning the 2012 Olympic Games bid).

points_of_interest.name: St Mary-at-Hill
points_of_interest.description:
St Mary-at-Hill, a historic Church of England parish church, is nestled in the heart of the City of London on Lovat Lane, a charming cobbled street near Eastcheap. Founded in the 12th century, this medieval gem has endured the test of time, surviving the Great Fire of London in 1666 and subsequent transformations. Today, it stands as a blend of old and new, with some of its original fabric still intact. The church is surrounded by ancient lanes, including one featuring a striking double-faced clock that offers a great view of its elegant exterior.

St Mary-at-Hill is not only a historic landmark but also a vibrant community hub. It shares its space with the congregation of St Anne's Lutheran Church, reflecting the diverse and inclusive spirit of the area. Visitors can appreciate its rich history, architectural charm, and peaceful atmosphere amidst the bustling city.

points_of_interest.name: Postal Museum
points_of_interest.description: Mail Rail Besides exhibits about the history of the postal service, the museum also has Mail Rail, an operating segment of a former underground railway that used to carry mail to various post offices within London. Visitors can ride a miniature train through the original tunnels. The ride is not for visitors who are large or have mobility problems. The Postal Museum and Mail Rail are in two separate buildings across the street from each other.

points_of_interest.name: Addington Palace
points_of_interest.description: Addington Palace, an 18th-century mansion in the London Borough of Croydon, offers a glimpse into history as the former summer residence of the Archbishops of Canterbury from 1807 to 1897. Today, the estate is home to the Addington Palace Golf Club, while the mansion itself has been transformed into a popular venue for weddings and events. Its rich heritage and picturesque setting make it a charming destination for both history enthusiasts and those seeking a scenic escape.
points_of_interest.address: 2 Gravel Hill, Croydon, CR0 5BB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Senate House Building
points_of_interest.description: The Senate House Building is a striking example of neoclassical architecture, serving as a prominent landmark in its surroundings. Known for its grand design and historical significance, it has played a key role in the region's political and cultural landscape. Visitors can admire its imposing structure, which features a blend of traditional and modern elements. The building is often surrounded by vibrant public spaces, making it a popular spot for both locals and travelers to explore and photograph. Whether you're interested in history, architecture, or simply soaking in the atmosphere, the Senate House Building is a must-see destination.

points_of_interest.name: Twickenham
points_of_interest.description: Twickenham, which seats over 80,000, is the home of the England national rugby team, and is used mostly for major internationals and cup finals. Tour the stadium and visit the Museum of Rugby. Check their website to avoid being turned away on match days.

points_of_interest.name: HMS Belfast
points_of_interest.description: HMS Belfast, now a museum ship on London’s River Thames, offers a fascinating glimpse into naval history. This former Royal Navy cruiser played a significant role in World War II, including the Battle of North Cape and support for the D-Day landings. After the war, she served during the Korean War before being preserved as a museum in the 1970s. Today, she is part of the Imperial War Museum, featuring interactive exhibits that showcase her wartime service and life on board. Visitors can explore her decks and learn about her storied past in the heart of London.

points_of_interest.name: Diana Memorial Playground
points_of_interest.description: The Diana Memorial Playground, nestled in Kensington Gardens near Kensington Palace, offers a whimsical escape inspired by Peter Pan. This enchanting spot, dedicated to Princess Diana, features a pirate ship and sensory garden, catering to children of all ages. Its magical theme invites families to explore and play, while the surrounding greenery provides a serene backdrop for adults to unwind. A perfect destination for those seeking a delightful and relaxed family experience in London.
points_of_interest.address: The Broad Walk, Kensington and Chelsea, London, W2 4RU, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: St. James's Park
points_of_interest.description: St. James's Park, a picturesque Royal Park in central London, offers a serene escape amidst the city's bustle. Located near Buckingham Palace, it's part of a chain of parks including Green Park and Hyde Park. Once a deer park for Henry VIII, it now invites visitors to enjoy leisurely strolls and picnics. The park is easily accessible via nearby Underground stations, making it a must-visit for both history enthusiasts and those seeking relaxation. Its rich history and beautiful landscapes create a welcoming atmosphere for all.
points_of_interest.address: The Mall, Westminster, London, SW1H 9AB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: London Transport Museum Depot
points_of_interest.description: This is the main storage facility of the London Transport Museum, holding items that cannot be fit into the main building at Covent Garden in central London. The building holds a wide range of railway carriages, buses, trams and trolleybuses, mostly restored, and many other exhibits, including signalling equipment, track items, tunnel segments, signs, models, and hundreds of small items. On open days preserved buses operate on tours of the surrounding area.
points_of_interest.hours: Open to general public two or three weekends per year, guided tours more frequently. See [https://www.ltmuseum.co.uk/whats-on/museum-depot/open-weekends website] for details

points_of_interest.name: St Mary le Bow
points_of_interest.description: St Mary-le-Bow, a historic Church of England parish church on Cheapside, is a notable landmark in the City of London. Founded in 1080 by Lanfranc, Archbishop of Canterbury, the church was rebuilt by Sir Christopher Wren after the Great Fire of London. Its striking spire makes it one of Wren’s tallest churches. The church is famous for its bells, which inspired the nursery rhyme "Oranges and Lemons" and the legend of Dick Whittington. Damaged during the Blitz, it was meticulously restored and holds Grade I listed status. Today, it stands as a testament to London’s rich history and resilience.

points_of_interest.name: The Perimeter
points_of_interest.description: Contemporary art gallery tucked away in a quiet cobbled mews. Hosts a couple of exhibitions a year, entry needs to be booked in advance.

points_of_interest.name: Custard Apple, Breadfruit and Soursop by Veronica Ryan
points_of_interest.description: The first permanent artworks to honour the Windrush generation in the UK.
points_of_interest.address: 354 Mare Street, Hackney, London, E8 1HR, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: St George's Gardens
points_of_interest.description: Peaceful gardens and interesting monuments including the daughter of Richard Cromwell, son of Oliver Cromwell.

points_of_interest.name: Twickenham Stoop
points_of_interest.description: Across the road from the main Twickenham Stadium is this smaller stadium (capacity about 15,000) known as "The Stoop". It's home to two teams both playing rugby union (15-a-side) in the Premiership, the top tier of the game in England. These are '''Harlequin FC''', usually called "Harlequins" or simply "Quins", and '''London Irish'''. They both often qualify for European competitions.
points_of_interest.address: Twickenham Stoop Stadium, Langhorn Dr, Twickenham

points_of_interest.name: Clink Prison Museum
points_of_interest.description: A museum that tries to recreate the conditions of the original prison that used to be on this site from the 12th century until 1780, which was notorious the name of it has since become slang as a generic term for prison.

points_of_interest.name: Elfin Oak
points_of_interest.description: The Elfin Oak, a 900-year-old tree stump in Kensington Gardens, is a whimsical attraction featuring intricate carvings of elves, gnomes, and fairies. Originally from Richmond Park, it was moved here in 1928 as part of a public improvement project. Over two years, illustrator Ivor Innes crafted its enchanting details, bringing mythical creatures to life.
points_of_interest.address: The Broad Walk, Kensington and Chelsea, London, W2 4RU, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Wellington Arch
points_of_interest.description: The Arch was designed in the 1820s by Decimus Burton as a Roman-style triumphal arch to commemorate victory in the Napoleonic Wars; although money ran out before it was completed. Adrian Jones' chariot statue on the top, "Peace descending on the Quadriga of War", was added in 1912. The original equestrian statue, added in 1846, was widely disliked and now stands in Aldershot. The arch is now owned by English Heritage and is open to the public: it contains exhibits about the arch and English history, while the view from the top is quite impressive.
points_of_interest.address: Apsley Way, Hyde Park Corner, W1J 7JZ
points_of_interest.hours: Interior access daily: Apr–Sep 10AM–6PM; Oct 10AM–5PM; Nov–Mar 10AM–4PM

points_of_interest.name: Battle of Britain Bunker
points_of_interest.description: The remains of RAF Uxbridge are a museum with the Battle of Britain bunker used to coordinate pilots of the No. 11 Group Fighter Command during World War II. The bunker can only be visited by a tour guide which can be booked via the website.

points_of_interest.name: St Stephen Walbrook
points_of_interest.description: Constructed 1672-9 to a design by Sir Christopher Wren and regarded as one of the finest Wren churches. The 63 feet (19 m) high dome is based on Wren's original design for St Paul's Cathedral. The circular altar is by the British sculptor Henry Moore, and the kneelers are designed by Patrick Heron. Free lunchtime concerts at 1PM on Tuesdays (except August). Free Organ recitals at 12:30PM on Fridays. Occasional art exhibitions on Christian themes and other events.

points_of_interest.name: Warm Shores by Thomas J Price
points_of_interest.description: Nine-foot-high bronze sculptures celebrating the Windrush Generation.
points_of_interest.address: 117 Wilton Way, Hackney, London, E8 1BH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Goodenough College
points_of_interest.description: Goodenough College offers accommodation for international postgraduate students. The college's student community of approx 650 represents over 90 countries, offering a unique experience through stimulating intellectual debate, fostering cross-cultural activity and providing an exceptional social environment. Tours around the college are offered every Friday at 1PM and every first Saturday of the month at 11AM.

points_of_interest.name: Winchester Palace
points_of_interest.description: Ruins of the 12th-century palace which was the London residence of the Bishops of Winchester.
points_of_interest.address: Corner of Clink St and Storey St

points_of_interest.name: Italian Gardens
points_of_interest.description: The Italian Garden is a timeless style inspired by the grand Renaissance gardens of Italy. These gardens blend formal design with a relaxed elegance, extending the symmetry of the house into nature. Characterized by their use of Mediterranean plants and classic elements, Italian Gardens have influenced garden design across Europe and beyond. Over time, many have evolved, incorporating elements from other styles, such as the English landscape garden. Today, Italy boasts a diverse range of gardens, reflecting its varied climates and rich horticultural history. A visit offers a glimpse into this enduring and evolving gardening tradition.
points_of_interest.address: 62 Bayswater Road, Westminster, London, W2 3PS, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: For Arts Sake
points_of_interest.description: For Arts Sake is a unique cultural destination that blends gallery, studio, and shop into one inspiring space. Housed in a beautifully restored 1930s Art Deco building in Chiswick, London, this vibrant spot celebrates contemporary art with a distinctly British flavor. Visitors can explore an eclectic collection of paintings, sculptures, and prints by both local and international artists. It’s also a great place to discover exclusive pieces or simply enjoy the creative atmosphere. Family-friendly and full of character, For Arts Sake is a must-visit for art lovers and curious travelers alike.

points_of_interest.name: Temple Church
points_of_interest.description: A small realm of serenity in the midst of the typical turmoil. It used to be the court of the Knights Templar. You can still visit the beautiful Romanesque church, which is one of the oldest ones in London (opened in 1185) and has connections to the order of Templars. The chancel of the church was built by Henry III. The church still serves the members of Gray's Inn and Lincoln's Inn and has frequent services open to the public. Fans of Dan Brown's ''The Da Vinci Code'' will recognise the church from both the novel and the film.
points_of_interest.hours: Varies, but approx.: M–Tu: 11AM–4PM; W: 2PM–4PM; Th–F: 11AM–4PM

points_of_interest.name: University College London
points_of_interest.description: UCL Includes a small but beautiful quad and an interesting Neo-Classical facade. The core buildings of UCL were built after the university's foundation in 1826.

points_of_interest.name: The Golden Hind
points_of_interest.description: The Golden Hind, captained by Francis Drake during his historic circumnavigation of the world from 1577 to 1580, is a celebrated piece of maritime history. Originally named Pelican, the ship was renamed in 1578 to honor Drake's patron, Sir Christopher Hatton, whose crest featured a golden hind. Today, a full-sized, seaworthy replica of The Golden Hind stands on the south bank of the Thames in London, offering a fascinating glimpse into the era of exploration and adventure. This iconic attraction is a must-visit for history enthusiasts and travelers alike.
points_of_interest.address: 6 Clink Street, Southwark, London, SE1 9FE, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Kensington Palace
points_of_interest.description: A royal residence which is still used by Prince William, Kate and their young family. Much of it is however open to the public and it is a very popular tourist attraction perhaps due as much to its association with Princess Diana as anything else. The King's Gallery here is a magnificent Regency period court drawing room and contains some impressive paintings including a Van Dyke. Also a nice restaurant on site called The Orangery.

points_of_interest.name: Hounslow Urban Farm
points_of_interest.description: Hounslow Urban Farm offers a peaceful retreat from the hustle and bustle of city life. Located near Feltham, this charming farm is home to a variety of animals, including cows, pigs, goats, and birds. Visitors can get up close and personal with the animals, making it a great destination for families and nature lovers alike. The farm also features educational programs and activities, providing insight into rural life and sustainable farming practices. Its serene setting and interactive experiences make it a delightful day-trip destination for those looking to connect with the countryside without leaving London.
points_of_interest.address: Faggs Road, Feltham, Middlesex TW14 OLZ

points_of_interest.name: St Dunstan in the East
points_of_interest.description: The ruins of a church dating back to Saxon times, rebuilt by St Dunstan in 950, destroyed in the Great Fire of London, and then rebuilt by Sir Christopher Wren in 1697. Most of the church was destroyed during the blitz, leaving only the tower (dating from Wren's time) and hollowed-out walls (from an 1817 reconstruction). The ruins are now overgrown with picturesque vines and trees, and were converted into a public garden in 1967, complete with benches.

points_of_interest.name: BBC Broadcasting House
points_of_interest.description: New Broadcasting House aka NBH The complex incorporates the Old Broad House built in 1930s. The façades of which feature the famous sculpture of ''Prospero and Ariel'' and the ''Ariel friezes'' by Eric Gill and Gilbert Bayes. BBC's ''The One Show'' is transmitted from the studio at the ground floor every weeknight starting from 7PM. The studio is quite visible from the plaza outside and some parts of the show are performed from outside of the studio – in the plaza.
points_of_interest.hours: Due to security reasons the Broadcasting House is not open to visitors

points_of_interest.name: Southwark Cathedral
points_of_interest.description: Not as popular with tourists as St Paul's north of the river, Southwark Cathedral has been the site of worship since the year 852. Literally in the shadow of London Bridge, the Cathedral is a shelter from the noise of the city. Next to the Cathedral is the '''Borough Market''' open Th-Sa with a wide range of speciality food to buy, a good area for lunch.

points_of_interest.name: The Round Pond
points_of_interest.description: Full of swans, geese, gulls, and other birds. Deckchairs can be hired for £1.50. The park benches and grassy areas are free.
points_of_interest.address: The Broad Walk, Westminster, London, W2 4RH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Brentford Dock
points_of_interest.description: Fans of British TV may be interested to know that the riverside area to the south of Brentford High Street is frequently used for outdoor filming by popular series such as ITV's ''The Bill''. The backdrop of the estate (sited on the former Brentford Dock, the terminus for GWR trains transferring goods to the Thames) appears frequently in shows requiring a 'gritty', urban atmosphere. The northern aspect of the Brentford Dock estate belies its extremely picturesque marina (filled with a variety of narrowboats, Dutch barges and pleasure craft) and waterside views, however. Indeed, for connoisseurs of post-war architecture, Brentford Dock is often cited as an example of a successful and aesthetically-pleasing social housing development from a period most commonly characterised by its failures.
points_of_interest.address: 3 Justin Close, Brentford, TW8 8QR, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Museum of London
points_of_interest.description: Now permanently closed, will be replaced by new museum at the former Smithfield market site in 2026. The Museum of London Docklands remains open.
points_of_interest.address: London Wall (NB: this is a street!)

points_of_interest.name: The Shard
points_of_interest.description: The View from the Shard Go up the tallest building in Western Europe to see the furthest panoramic view of London ever to have a price tag stuck on it. Entry is to a timeslot, but once you're up there you may spend as much time (and extra money on tea, cake or cocktails) as you want.
points_of_interest.hours: Hours vary, but most commonly 11AM-7PM. Often closed M and Tu. Check [https://www.theviewfromtheshard.com/plan-your-visit/opening-times/ website]

points_of_interest.name: The Serpentine Gallery
points_of_interest.description: A nice modern art gallery, near to the Serpentine. Too small to host a permanent collection, instead hosts temporary exhibitions which can last anything from a few weeks to over a year. Each summer a pavilion next to the gallery is designed by a different architect, which then houses various cultural events.

points_of_interest.name: Guildhall Art Gallery and Roman Amphitheatre
points_of_interest.description: The Guildhall Art Gallery houses the City Corporation's art collection, and also runs special exhibitions throughout the year. During construction of the modern gallery, workers discovered the ruins of London's Roman amphitheatre. The gallery was redesigned, and now the Amphitheatre is open to the public within the Guildhall Art Gallery itself and also free of charge.

points_of_interest.name: Millennium Bridge
points_of_interest.description: This steel pedestrian bridge connecting Bankside with the City of London has all the lovely views of the Thames that you'd expect, but most of those who cross Millennium Bridge never notice its most distinctive feature. The bridge is dotted with hundreds of tiny paintings, so small that you'll probably miss them under your feet if you're not looking for them.
points_of_interest.address: 1 Paul's Walk, London, EC4V 3QH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Roper's Garden
points_of_interest.description: Small green area, with benches, by the Thames. Created in the crater of a World War II bomb site, it contains an ancient cherry tree to commemorate the visit of Gunji Koizumi, the man who introduced judo to the country. Named after Margaret Roper née More, to whom the area was a gift from her father, Sir Thomas More, on her marriage to William Roper.

points_of_interest.name: New Zealand Memorial
points_of_interest.description: Sixteen cruciform bronze pillars designed by Paul Dibble and John Hardwick-Smith.
points_of_interest.address: 140 Piccadilly, Westminster, London, W1J 7NS, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Dr Johnson's House
points_of_interest.description: Dr Samuel Johnson was the highly distinguished 18th-century "man of letters", best known for his comprehensive English Dictionary of 1755, but also for his prolific output of poems, essays and novels. Something of a "hidden gem", this small, independent museum is dedicated to him—and, with its historic interiors, paintings and prints, personal effects and other exhibits—gives an impression of what it might have been like during his occupancy from 1748 to 1759. Built in 1700, this impressive period building—a rare example of its kind in the area—survived the brutal onslaught of the Blitz during World War II and is now maintained in excellent condition.
points_of_interest.hours: October-April: M-Sa 11AM-5PM; May-September: M-Sa 11AM-5:30PM; closed Sundays, Bank Holidays

points_of_interest.name: Tate Modern
points_of_interest.description: An enormous art gallery converted from the former Bankside Power Station, a visit to Tate Modern could easily take half a day. The gallery collects together contemporary and modern art from around the world, arranged thematically. The most stunning aspect of the building, is the enormous Turbine Hall, which plays host to a single piece of work commissioned for the space each year. An extension of the gallery has opened in a ten-storey building behind the existing power station.

points_of_interest.name: Alfred Hitchcock's House
points_of_interest.description: A plaque erected in 1999 marks the house where the famous director lived from 1926 to 1939.

points_of_interest.name: Bank of England Museum
points_of_interest.description: Charts the history of the bank from 1694 to the present day. A highlight is the opportunity to handle a genuine bar of gold. Photography allowed, but no flash.

points_of_interest.name: The Thames
points_of_interest.description: Kingston borough redeveloped the riverfront, and it is an extremely pleasant way to spend a summer day. It can get very busy, and to avoid the crowds you can cross over Kingston Bridge and walk along the quieter Richmond side.
points_of_interest.address: Kingston Bridge, Richmond upon Thames, Kingston upon Thames, KT1 4AA, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: London Fire Brigade Museum
points_of_interest.description: Admission by guided tour only, which must be booked in advance. The museum is housed in part of a Victorian fire station and its collections include fire engines and historical equipment.

points_of_interest.name: Bram Stoker's House
points_of_interest.description: This charming house is a must-visit for literature enthusiasts, as it was once the home of Bram Stoker, the celebrated author of *Dracula*. A notable feature of the property is the plaque unveiled by the London Dracula Society, paying tribute to Stoker's enduring legacy. Visitors can explore the historic residence and immerse themselves in the surroundings that may have inspired the iconic novel. It’s a unique opportunity to connect with the life and work of one of literature’s most influential figures.

points_of_interest.name: Simón Bolívar
points_of_interest.description: Simón Bolívar, known as El Libertador, was a pivotal figure in Latin America's struggle for independence. Born in Caracas into a wealthy family, he lost his parents early and was educated abroad, where Enlightenment ideas shaped his vision. In Rome, he vowed to free Spanish America from colonial rule. Bolívar led successful campaigns across Colombia, Venezuela, Ecuador, Peru, Panama, and Bolivia, founding the Republic of Colombia. His legacy is profound; Bolivia and Venezuela are named after him, and his impact endures in culture and monuments, making him a celebrated hero across Latin America.

points_of_interest.name: Barbican Centre
points_of_interest.description: The Barbican Centre is a world-leading arts venue in the City of London, offering a diverse range of performances and exhibitions. Home to the London Symphony Orchestra and BBC Symphony Orchestra, it showcases classical music, theatre, and film. Its striking brutalist design and vibrant atmosphere make it a must-visit cultural destination. Opened by Queen Elizabeth II in 1982, the Barbican Centre is a gift to the nation, reflecting the City of London's commitment to the arts.
points_of_interest.hours: Art Gallery: M-F 11AM–7PM 10AM–6PM, Sa–Su 10AM–7PM; The Curve: M-F noon–7PM, Sa Su 11AM–7PM

points_of_interest.name: Out of Order
points_of_interest.description: For a good photo opportunity seek out ''the phone boxes'', a sculpture by artist David Mach in Old London Road featuring a number of disused red telephone boxes leaning against each other like dominoes.
points_of_interest.address: 2 Old London Road, Kingston upon Thames, KT2 6SN, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Topolski Century
points_of_interest.description: Painted between 1975 and 1989, Topolski Century is a unique, monumental work of a Polish artist Feliks Topolski (1907-1989) that presents a remarkable record of the key events and the iconic figures of the 20th century such as Winston Churchill, Mahatma Gandhi, Martin Luther King, Pablo Picasso and Coco Chanel. 600 feet long and 20 feet high, Topolski Century is the artist’s eye witness testimony to the era that shaped our lives. It is global in its scope and is Topolski’s legacy to future generations.

points_of_interest.name: Mark Twain's House
points_of_interest.description: The American writer lived at this address from 1896 to 1897.

points_of_interest.name: Thomas Cubitt
points_of_interest.description: Renowned British master builder Thomas Cubitt played a pivotal role in shaping London's architectural landscape. He is best known for his work in developing iconic streets and squares across Belgravia, Pimlico, and Bloomsbury. His contributions left a lasting legacy in the city's historic neighborhoods.
points_of_interest.address: Corner of Denbigh St and St George's Drive

points_of_interest.name: London Mithraeum
points_of_interest.description: Temple of Mithras The London Mithraeum is a 3rd century Roman mithraeum that was discovered in Walbrook during construction work in 1954. The entire site was relocated several times before being returned to its original site as part of the new Bloomberg building. This temple of the mystery god Mithras became perhaps the most famous 20th-century Roman discovery in London. In addition to the temple structure, there is a display of Roman artefacts found on the site and a contemporary art exhibit responding to the site. Visitor numbers are limited and timed slots are often fully booked up several weeks into the future so plan well ahead.
points_of_interest.hours: Tu-Sa 10AM-6PM, Su and bank holidays noon-5PM

points_of_interest.name: All Saints Church
points_of_interest.description: Kingston's old parish church near the marketplace goes back to the sixteenth century on earlier foundations. Inside, for those interested in military history, is a chapel dedicated to a former local regiment, the East Surreys.

points_of_interest.name: Hayward Gallery
points_of_interest.description: The largest public art space in the UK and the exhibitions showcase masters and young British and international artists, usually accompanied by outdoor installations that bring the area to life. The gallery often holds free exhibitions which can be enjoyed by all. Particularly strong on contemporary art exhibitions. Hosts a single temporary exhibition at any time.
points_of_interest.hours: Sa-M Th 10AM-6PM, Tu 10AM-8PM, W 10AM-8PM, F 10AM-9PM (except 24-27 Dec and 1-2 Jan)

points_of_interest.name: Oscar Wilde's House
points_of_interest.description: The famous Victorian writer lived at this house.

points_of_interest.name: Westminster Cathedral
points_of_interest.description: Worth a quick visit if you are passing. The brick and stone neo-Byzantine Catholic Cathedral (not to be confused with the much more famous Westminster Abbey) is near Victoria Station, just off Victoria Street. Construction started in 1895, and some of the interior is still unfinished. The Treasures of Westminster Cathedral exhibition is inexpensive and worthwhile for learning the history of the cathedral, there are interesting exhibits including a 1:28 wooden scale model uses by the architects. Has a café and gift shop.

points_of_interest.name: Barts Pathology Museum
points_of_interest.description: Bart's Pathology Museum is a unique and fascinating destination for those interested in medical history. Located in London, the museum showcases a wide range of pathological specimens and historical medical equipment, offering a glimpse into the evolution of medicine. The museum's atmospheric setting, with its Victorian-era architecture, adds to its charm. Visitors can explore the exhibits through guided tours, which provide insightful context about the specimens and their historical significance. This museum is a must-visit for anyone with an interest in science, history, or the medical field, though it may not be suitable for the faint of heart.

points_of_interest.name: All Saints Carshalton
points_of_interest.description: Historic Anglican church with a very ancient history. The church's website states that the church's tower in all likelihood dates from before the Norman conquest, and the first nave was probably built around 1150, though most of the present-day church was built in the 19th and early 20th centuries.
points_of_interest.address: West end of Carshalton High Street, opposite Carshalton Ponds

points_of_interest.name: The London Bridge Experience
points_of_interest.description: The London Bridge Experience and London Tombs are two scare attractions for one price. They were voted the UK's Best Year Round Scare Attraction for three years running.

points_of_interest.name: Rosalind Franklin's House
points_of_interest.description: One of the discoverers of the DNA molecule lived here in the 1950s until her death in 1958.

points_of_interest.name: Banqueting House
points_of_interest.description: Designed and built in 1619-1622 by the Neo-Classical architect Inigo Jones, The Banqueting House is now all that remains of Whitehall Palace, the sovereign's principal residence from 1530-1698 when most of it was destroyed by fire. Renowned for its architecture and paintings (by Rubens, among others), the building is also famous for being the scene of Charles I's execution in 1649 at the end of the English Civil War.
points_of_interest.hours: M-Sa 10AM-5PM, closed Su, Bank Holidays and 24 Dec-1 Jan (inclusive); The Banqueting House is liable to close at short notice for government functions, telephone to check before you travel

points_of_interest.name: Barbican Conservatory
points_of_interest.description: The Barbican Conservatory is the second largest conservatory in London, after the Princess of Wales Conservatory at Kew Gardens. Located at the Barbican Centre, it houses more than 2,000 species of plants and trees, as well as terrapins and koi carp. The conservatory covers 23,000 square feet , and is located on top of the theatre's fly tower.

points_of_interest.name: The Old Operating Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Britain's oldest operating theatre is an unusual tourist attraction, located in the roof space of St. Thomas's Church along with the herb store originally used by St. Thomas's Hospital's apothecary.
points_of_interest.address: 9 St. Thomas Street, Southwark, London, SE1 9RY, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: T.S. Eliot's House
points_of_interest.description: The poet lived and died in this house.

points_of_interest.name: Cabinet War Rooms and Churchill Museum
points_of_interest.description: A branch of the Imperial War Museum, the Cabinet War Rooms preserves the underground corridors and rooms from which Churchill and the cabinet directed the war against Hitler and the Nazis, maintained almost exactly as they were left in 1945. In 1984, IWM opened the rooms to the public for the first time. In 2005, the attached Churchill Museum was opened as the world's first permanent museum dedicated to the life and wartime achievements of Sir Winston Churchill. Audio guides are included in your admission. No cloakroom, no rucksacks, no suitcases. Café is open daily from 10am to 5pm. Hot food is served until 3pm.
points_of_interest.address: Clive Steps, King Charles St, SW1A 2AQ

points_of_interest.name: Blitz Plaque
points_of_interest.description: The first of tens of thousands of bombs to hit London in World War II fell here in 1940.

points_of_interest.name: Fashion & Textile Museum
points_of_interest.description: The Fashion & Textile Museum offers a fascinating look at the evolution of fashion and its cultural significance. Explore exhibits that highlight iconic designs, textiles, and accessories, showcasing how fashion reflects social status, self-expression, and identity. Discover the origins of the term "fashion," tracing its roots to the Latin word "Facere," meaning "to make," and learn how it has grown into a global industry. The museum also addresses timely issues like sustainability, emphasizing the importance of reducing fashion's environmental impact. A must-visit for anyone interested in style, history, and the future of fashion.
points_of_interest.hours: Tuesdays – Saturdays, 11.00 – 18.00 with last entry 45 minutes before closing

points_of_interest.name: Sir William Gilbert's House
points_of_interest.description: One half of the comic opera writing team Gilbert & Sullivan lived here.

points_of_interest.name: Downing Street
points_of_interest.description: Downing Street, located in Westminster, London, is a historic street known for housing the official residences of the Prime Minister and the Chancellor of the Exchequer. Situated off Whitehall, it’s a short walk from the Houses of Parliament. Built in the 1680s by Sir George Downing, the street has been the heart of British government for over three centuries. Number 10 is famously the Prime Minister’s residence, while Number 11 is home to the Chancellor. The term "Downing Street" also symbolizes the British government itself. Today, the street balances its rich history with modern governance, offering a glimpse into the nation’s political heritage.
points_of_interest.address: 11 Downing Street, Westminster, London, SW1A 2AB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Baltic Exchange
points_of_interest.description: The Baltic Exchange is a historic landmark in London, serving as a key hub for the maritime industry. Originally located at 24-28 St Mary Axe since Edwardian times, the building was tragically destroyed by a bomb in 1992. The organization later relocated to 38 St Mary Axe in 1995, before establishing its current headquarters at 77 Leadenhall Street. Today, the Baltic Exchange operates globally, with offices across Europe, Asia, and the United States, continuing its vital role in maritime trade and freight market information.

points_of_interest.name: Sir Winston Churchill's House
points_of_interest.description: Sir Winston Churchill's former home is a historic site that offers a glimpse into the life of one of Britain's most revered leaders. Located near Bladon, the house reflects Churchill's personal style and contributions to history. Visitors can explore the rooms where he lived and worked, gaining insight into his life beyond politics. The surrounding countryside, which inspired his writing and painting, adds to the charm. This intimate setting provides a unique perspective on Churchill's legacy, making it a must-visit for history enthusiasts and those interested in British heritage.

points_of_interest.name: Household Cavalry Museum
points_of_interest.description: The Household Cavalry Museum offers a glimpse into the rich history of the Household Cavalry, one of the most prestigious corps of the British Army. Comprising the Life Guards and the Blues and Royals, this elite unit has played a significant role in every major conflict since 1660. Today, the Household Cavalry serves both as the King's official bodyguard and as a modern armed reconnaissance force. Visitors can explore the museum to learn about the regiments' dual role in ceremonial duties and armored operations, showcasing their enduring legacy as a symbol of British military tradition and pageantry.

points_of_interest.name: London Wall
points_of_interest.description: Remains of the wall that surrounded the City of London for almost two thousand years. The parts around the Barbican are mostly Tudor due to maintenance (Roman remains can be seen in and around the Tower of London). Other local remains are the {{marker|name=Noble St wall fragment|type=see|lat=51.5169|long=-0.0958|image=Roman Wall, Noble Street, London EC1 - geograph.org.uk - 1087379.jpg}} and the {{marker|name=St Alphage Gdns wall fragment|type=see|lat=51.5177|long=-0.0922|image=}}.
points_of_interest.address: 1 Bastion Highwalk, City of London, London, EC2Y 5AP, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Billionaires' Row
points_of_interest.description: Kensington Palace Gardens One of the most expensive residential streets on the planet! Most of the buildings here are embassies or ambassadorial residences but the rest of the mansions belong to some of the richest people in the country (or elsewhere). For added historical value, during World War II, the current Norwegian embassy was where King Haakon VII led the Norwegian government-in-exile (commemorated by a blue plaque) and MI19's "London Cage" prisoner-of-war facility was located here. There is no public right of way but the Crown Estate allow pedestrians and cyclists to use the street; photography is not permitted.
points_of_interest.address: 15 Kensington Palace Gardens, Kensington and Chelsea, London, W8 4QG, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Whitehall
points_of_interest.description: This street runs between Parliament Square and Trafalgar Square, and is the site of several British government buildings. Horseguards Parade, and the heavily guarded entrance to ''Downing Street'' (see above) are on the west side. Banqueting House is on the east side. In the centre of the street sits the Cenotaph, a war memorial erected following World War I, which is the centre of the annual Remembrance Day ceremony on 11 November.
points_of_interest.address: 70 Whitehall, Westminster, London, SW1A 2AS, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Lloyds of London
points_of_interest.description: The headquarters of world's most famous insurance market, housed in a revolutionary (at the time) bizarre, Matrix-like glass-and-steel building designed by Richard Rogers, with all support services (lifts, ventilation, etc.) suspended outside. Recognised as a masterpiece of exoskeleton architecture.

points_of_interest.name: Brompton Oratory
points_of_interest.description: Church of the Immaculate Heart of Mary Beautiful Italianate church created during the Catholic revival of the 19th century.

points_of_interest.name: London Stock Exchange
points_of_interest.description: After leaving its brutalist skyscraper on Old Broad St, the London Stock Exchange now resides on Paternoster Sq. Dating back to 1698, it is one of the world's oldest and largest stock markets.

points_of_interest.name: Carlyle's House
points_of_interest.description: Now preserved by the National Trust, this 18th-century house was the home of the historian Thomas Carlyle from 1834 and now houses a museum dedicated to his life and work.

points_of_interest.name: London Bullion Market Association
points_of_interest.description: The London Bullion Market Association, established in 1987, is a leading international trade association representing the global Over The Counter bullion market. As "the global authority on precious metals," it plays a pivotal role in setting standards and promoting integrity in the industry. The LBMA serves a diverse membership, including miners, refiners, and storage providers, and is instrumental in organizing conferences and events that shape the precious metals market. Its influence extends worldwide, making it a cornerstone of London's financial district and a key player in the global economy.

points_of_interest.name: Chelsea Old Church
points_of_interest.description: This church on the bank of the Thames was built in 1157. It is the only church in London with chained books. A statue of Thomas More sits in front of the church.

points_of_interest.name: London Metal Exchange
points_of_interest.description: The LME is the leading centre for non-ferrous metals trading. It is also the last financial market in London which still retains open outcry trading.

points_of_interest.name: Crosby Hall
points_of_interest.description: All that remains of a Tudor mansion built in the City of London. In 1910, to avoid demolition to make way for a bank, it was moved brick by brick and reassembled at Cheyne Walk. It is now a Grade II* listed building and possibly the largest private home in the capital.

points_of_interest.name: London Stone
points_of_interest.description: London Stone is a historic landmark housed in a public display case at 111 Cannon Street in the City of London. It is an irregular block of oolitic limestone measuring 53 × 43 × 30 cm (21″ × 17″ × 12″), the remnant of a once much larger object that had stood for many centuries on the south side of the street.

points_of_interest.name: Holy Trinity Church
points_of_interest.description: From their website: "In common with the aims of the Arts & Crafts Movement, the architect of Holy Trinity Church, John Dando Sedding, believed that a church should be 'wrought and painted over with everything that has life and beauty—in frank and fearless naturalism.'" Naturalism or not, the church is known as an ornate building.

points_of_interest.name: St Bride Printing Library
points_of_interest.description: This specialist small library houses an impressive range of books on graphic design, typography, bookbinding and papermaking. The books cannot be borrowed but can be photocopied or photographed (with permission). An essential visit for any graphic design student.

points_of_interest.name: Royal Hospital
points_of_interest.description: A retirement home for soldiers created by King Charles II. Tours around the listed building and grounds are regular and include the museum (which can be visited separately) whose exhibits contain military memorabilia donated by Chelsea Pensioners over the years.

points_of_interest.name: The Gherkin
points_of_interest.description: The Gherkin, also known as 30 St Mary Axe, is a striking landmark in London's financial district. Completed in 2003, this 41-story skyscraper stands at 180 meters tall and was designed by Foster + Partners and the Arup Group. Its sleek, contemporary design has made it one of London's most recognizable buildings. The Gherkin won the prestigious 2003 Emporis Skyscraper Award, celebrating its innovative architecture. A standout feature of the city skyline, it has become a symbol of modern London, blending seamlessly into the historic surroundings of the City of London.

points_of_interest.name: Russian Orthodox Cathedral
points_of_interest.description: Cathedral of the Dormition and All Saints Constructed in the Lombard style as an Anglican church in the 19th century, and passed to the Moscow Patriarchate in 1956. Rather beautiful and unique in London.

points_of_interest.name: Willis Building
points_of_interest.description: The Willis Building is a striking commercial skyscraper in London's financial district, named after its primary tenant, the Willis Group. Located on Lime Street in the City of London, it was designed by renowned architect Norman Foster and developed by British Land. Standing 125 meters tall with 26 floors, the building features a distinctive "stepped" design with setbacks at 97 meters and 68 meters. Its sleek, modern architecture makes it a notable landmark in the area, opposite the iconic Lloyd's building. The Willis Building offers 475,000 square feet of office space, with much of it occupied by the insurance broker Willis.

points_of_interest.name: Brompton Cemetery
points_of_interest.description: One of the "Magnificent Seven" old cemeteries in London. Graves range from plain to ornate and the site can be a tranquil place to walk amid the bustle of the city. It was opened in 1840 and is still a working cemetery, although it was closed for some time in the late 20th century. Can be nice, if morbid, for an afternoon stroll, especially as a route (and cycle route) between Old Brompton Road and Fulham Road.
points_of_interest.address: entrances on Old Brompton Road and Fulham Rd

points_of_interest.name: Leadenhall Building
points_of_interest.description: Another Richard Rogers creation, nicknamed the Cheesegrater. Completed in 2014. Also opposite Lloyd's.

points_of_interest.name: Penfold Post Box
points_of_interest.description: One of the few Victorian hexagonal Penfold post boxes still in use. Although there are others in this district, this one in notable for a narrow escape during World War II: minor bomb damage can still be seen in the base of the pillar.

points_of_interest.name: 20 Fenchurch Street
points_of_interest.description: The Sky Garden The unusual "walkie scorchie" profile of this skyscraper by Rafael Vinoly has seen it grab the headlines, as did the "death rays" caused by the sun's heat reflecting off the building onto the street below when it was first completed; car tyres melted and burst, and at least one man fried an egg using only the heat from the walkie talkie. Visitors can access the '''sky garden''' to see a magnificent view over the City and beyond; it's the only place you can't see the tower from! Online booking to visit during the day is essential. Alternatively, you can eat at one of the restaurants in the evening.

points_of_interest.name: Police Box
points_of_interest.description: This police box was intended as part of a 1990s high-tech revival of the 1920s-60s police box system. The experiment failed and this is now the only police box left in London. It remains as street furniture and is quite popular with fans of the TV series ''Doctor Who''.
points_of_interest.address: Earls Court Road, outside Earl's Court station

points_of_interest.name: Fishmongers' Hall
points_of_interest.description: The main headquarters of the Worshipful Company of Fishmongers and a Grade II* listed building.

points_of_interest.name: Royal College of Art
points_of_interest.description: A Victorian school, now a university with a mission to advance knowledge of the fine arts. Exhibitions are common. Times and admission charges vary but can often be free, although visitors may need to book tickets to certain events.

points_of_interest.name: Horizon 22
points_of_interest.description: London's highest viewing platform that is free to the public. Sitting at the 58th floor of an office building, and the tallest building in City of London proper, it gives visitors a 300-degree view of London.

points_of_interest.name: Royal College of Music
points_of_interest.description: Victorian school of music created on a suggestion by Prince Albert. It is still an active school but visitors may be more interested in its museum and performances. The free museum houses instruments dating back to the 15th century with several unusual pieces. Performances—by students, professors or visitors—are often free as well.

points_of_interest.name: Royal Geographical Society
points_of_interest.description: The UK learned society of geographers, founded in 1830. Hosts weekly lectures and other gatherings, many of which are free to attend to any member of the public. The RGS has funded many British expeditions over the years and displays at its northeastern corner statues of two of its best-known explorers: Dr David Livingstone, who hoped to end the East African slave trade by finding the source of the Nile; Sir Ernest Shackleton, who led the "worst journey in the world" across the Southern Ocean to rescue his stricken crew trapped in the Antarctic sea ice. Both men died on the expedition.

points_of_interest.name: Saatchi Gallery
points_of_interest.description: Prestigious contemporary art gallery worth a visit.
points_of_interest.address: Duke Of York's HQ, King's Road, SW3 4RY

points_of_interest.name: The Lock Market
points_of_interest.description: Many stores mainly focused around music and clothing. This is the market most people mean when they talk about the "Camden Market".
points_of_interest.address: 18 Camden Lock Place, Camden, London, NW1 8AL, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Stables Market
points_of_interest.description: This is the largest of Camden's market areas, featuring hundreds of stalls selling everything from African art to beds to fetish clothing to antiques. This is probably the best place in London for interesting clothes, including vintage, goth, cyber and general club-wear. Cyberdog is an experience just to look at, and the extreme basement contains some distinctly adult items. Burleska and Sai Sai are among a number of corest stockists.
points_of_interest.address: 752-753 Chalk Farm Road, Camden, London, NW1 8AH, United Kingdom
points_of_interest.hours: Some shops open all week, but most stalls only Sa Su 9AM-6PM

points_of_interest.name: Paddington Store
points_of_interest.description: Paddington Bear Store The official store of Michael Bond's famous ''Paddington Bear'' with merchandise including books, DVDs, souvenirs and of course, marmalade.
points_of_interest.address: The Lawn at Paddington Station, W2 1RH

points_of_interest.name: Camden Lock Village
points_of_interest.description: The three-storey market that stood here burned down in 2008. It has reopened since, but the area just contains a number of small stalls. The owners are trying to get planning permission for re-development.
points_of_interest.address: 2 Water Lane, Camden, London, NW1 8HY, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Portobello Road Market
points_of_interest.description: During the week this is the place to go to buy your fruit and veg but on Fridays and Saturdays there are hundreds of stalls selling clothes, [http://www.portobelloroad.co.uk/ antiques], jewellery and [http://shopportobello.co.uk/ lots more].
points_of_interest.address: 166 Portobello Road, Kensington and Chelsea, London, W11 2EB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Centre Court Shopping
points_of_interest.description: Shopping mall with two floors of shops. Includes shops such as Body Shop, Boots, Gap, H&M, Kew, La Senza, Monsoon, River Island, Sony and Warehouse. There are food outlets on the third floor and a cafe on the ground floor.

points_of_interest.name: Inverness Street Market
points_of_interest.description: This is a small market selling a range of common goods such as fruit and vegetables, cheap clothes and other bits and bobs. The Inverness Street Market is the smallest market in Camden, but it's the original local market in Camden predating the others by decades.
points_of_interest.address: 16 Inverness Street, Camden, London, NW1 7HJ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Westbourne Grove
points_of_interest.description: Smart boutiques, food shops and outdoor cafes.
points_of_interest.address: 1-3 Chepstow Road, Westminster, London, W2 5BL, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Buck Street Market
points_of_interest.description: This is the first market you see turning right out of the tube station and it has a big sign declaring it "The Camden Market". However, it only sells only the typical funny t-shirts, knock-off designer boots, keyrings, etc., that you can find in practically every city in the world.
points_of_interest.address: 3 Buck Street, Camden, London, NW1 8NJ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Ben Sherman
points_of_interest.description: The flagship retail outlet of this iconic British fashion brand. Men's and women's clothing, accessories and shoes.

points_of_interest.name: The Travel Bookshop
points_of_interest.description: Great place to browse. Its other point of interest is that it was the inspiration for Hugh Grant's shop in the movie ''Notting Hill''.

points_of_interest.name: Elys of Wimbledon
points_of_interest.description: A department store just off the High Street and a few minutes' walk from the Tube & Rail station.

points_of_interest.name: Camden Passage Antiques Centre
points_of_interest.description: One of London's leading antique and collectible centres for the past 40 years. The complex is home to dealers in a wide variety of fields and is a must for any visitor to London interested in antiques. Controversially, the main arcade has now become another branch of Jack Wills, but many dealers remain in the area.

points_of_interest.name: Amsterdam London Shop
points_of_interest.description: Probably the finest purveyor of curious things in London. They also sell weed and hash-smoking paraphernalia.

points_of_interest.name: The Great Frog
points_of_interest.description: Rock and heavy metal jewellery specialist. Been in business here for more than 40 years. The iconic skull ring worn by so many famous rockers was originally designed and produced by Great Frog.

points_of_interest.name: Get Stuffed
points_of_interest.description: Taxidermy shop offering a stock of stuffed animals and bones, for an unusual purchase, and service for preparing your own specimens.

points_of_interest.name: Official Doc Martens Boot Co.
points_of_interest.description: The British Boot Company Selling Doc Martens since the 1960s. The proprietor is always happy to talk and has some fun tales about the strange requests he has had from famous people.

points_of_interest.name: Reckless Records
points_of_interest.description: Second-hand record (vinyl) store.

points_of_interest.name: Map
points_of_interest.description: Trendy gift shop with cool products. Much too nice to be in Archway!

points_of_interest.name: Rokit
points_of_interest.description: A proud upshoot that took its roots from Camden market and now has four high street stores across London.

points_of_interest.name: Putney High Street
points_of_interest.description: Shopping, also international and British dining experience.
points_of_interest.address: 95 Putney High Street, Wandsworth, London, SW15 1SS, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: New Beacon Books
points_of_interest.description: A bookshop and publisher founded in 1966, specialising in black literature, including African, Caribbean, African-American, and Black British books.

points_of_interest.name: The Harry Potter Shop at Platform 9¾
points_of_interest.description: One-stop emporium for all your wizarding needs, this is the official souvenir shop of the ''Harry Potter'' franchise in London. Adjacent is the eponymous platform, where you can have your picture taken pushing a luggage trolley through a solid wall. It's probably the only other Harry Potter-themed store in London outside of the WB Studio Tour in Watford.

points_of_interest.name: Selfridges
points_of_interest.description: Worth a visit to its food hall; it also has a great selection of bottled beers.

points_of_interest.name: Tooting and Broadway Markets
points_of_interest.description: Provide a varied and interesting selection, including fruit and vegetables, clothes, furniture and household items.

points_of_interest.name: Chapel Market
points_of_interest.address: 32 Baron Street, Islington, London, N1 9ES, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: John Lewis
points_of_interest.description: Good for fabrics, knitting supplies, haberdashery, other crafts, furniture, and homewares in general.

points_of_interest.name: Clonezone
points_of_interest.description: The world's largest gay retail company. Merchandise includes underwear and adult toys.
points_of_interest.hours: M Tu 11AM–8PM, W–F 11AM–9PM, Sa noon–10PM, Su noon–6PM

points_of_interest.name: Daunt Books
points_of_interest.description: A wonderful, old-style independent book shop which has a second branch up the hill at 51 South End Rd.

points_of_interest.name: Burlington Arcade
points_of_interest.description: Regency-era shopping arcade home to luxury fashion and jewellery boutiques.

points_of_interest.name: Berwick Street Market
points_of_interest.description: An absolute gem and a relic of Soho's past. This is an old fashioned London fruit and vegetable market complete with shouting ''Barrow Boys'' and a whole array of colourful characters. There has been a market at this site since the early 1800s. Best early in the mornings. The street food vendors make this a good lunch option.

points_of_interest.name: Brixton Market
points_of_interest.description: Brixton Market consists of several different parts. The main section is Electric Avenue, selling mainly fruit, vegetables and meat, which also has a very good Chinese supermarket. On Pope's Road, you will find clothes and bric-a-brac. You will find more indoor markets around the area, such as Brixton Village (between Pope's Road and Coldharbour Lane), Reliance Arcade (between Brixton Road and Electric Lane) and Granville Arcade (running between Electric Lane and Atlantic Road). These sell everything from wigs, clothes, pets, exotic foods and coffee.
points_of_interest.address: 9 Electric Avenue, Lambeth, London, SW9 8JY, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Westfield Stratford City
points_of_interest.description: Vast shopping mall between the station and the Olympic Park. Also has many restaurants, a cinema, a baseball batting cage and a bowling alley.
points_of_interest.address: 5 Celebration Avenue, Newham, London, E20 1DB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Farmer's Market
points_of_interest.description: A regular farmer's market selling fresh organic produce every Saturday

points_of_interest.name: Cordings Ltd
points_of_interest.description: Outfitter for the upmarket country set, including colourful corduroy trousers for men.

points_of_interest.name: Foyles
points_of_interest.description: London's best known bookshop is a mazy warren containing a seemingly impossible number of books! It is not always easy to find your way around and although greatly improved since the renovation in 1999, the service is notably surly. Nonetheless, this place is a must for all book lovers.

points_of_interest.name: Walthamstow Market
points_of_interest.description: The longest outdoor street market in Europe, stretching for roughly a kilometre. All manner of items may be purchased here.

points_of_interest.name: Hampstead Antiques Emporium
points_of_interest.description: More than 30 antique dealers permanently occupy this small arcade and adjacent courtyard. Several genres represented including furniture, paintings, toys and textiles.

points_of_interest.name: Petticoat Lane Market
points_of_interest.description: Traditionally the East End market where nearly anything could be found (legal or not) now mostly cheaper mainstream clothes. Main market Sunday, smaller market M-F in Wentworth St.

points_of_interest.name: Fortnum and Mason
points_of_interest.description: World famous as grocers to the British Royal Family, Fortnum's original store has been here in Piccadilly since 1707.

points_of_interest.name: MinaLima
points_of_interest.description: A shop and gallery showcasing the work of the designers who create the letters, signs, newspapers, and many other props and graphics in the ''Harry Potter'' movies. Lots of prints and souvenirs available for purchase. Worth a visit for Harry Potter fans.

points_of_interest.name: The Mall Walthamstow
points_of_interest.description: Selborne Walk Walthamstow's shopping mall, with the usual selection of shopping mall type shops. Part of it remains closed since a major fire in July 2019.
points_of_interest.address: 35 Selborne Walk, Waltham Forest, London, E17 7JR, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Hampstead Community Centre
points_of_interest.description: On Saturdays, turns into a mini-market selling a variety of things, including a second hand book stall with a fantastic selection.

points_of_interest.name: Hamley's
points_of_interest.description: Largest toy store in England, and the World, with over seven floors. One could spend hours here.

points_of_interest.name: The Exchange Shopping Centre
points_of_interest.description: It was one of the largest American-style malls when it was constructed in the early 1990s. Although now it has an extensive array of shops now it can only really be considered a bog standard shopping centre. The town centre has most high street chain shops.

points_of_interest.name: Keith Fawkes Books
points_of_interest.description: A rare and antiquarian bookshop with a special focus on the great literary characters who lived in Hampstead. Also carries a huge stock of more run-of-the-mill secondhand titles. An absolute must for booklovers.

points_of_interest.name: Brick Lane
points_of_interest.description: The Whitechapel end of Brick Lane is filled with South Asian (mainly Bangladeshi) shops and restaurants, selling music, spices, tasty sweets and sari material.
points_of_interest.address: 43 Hanbury Street, Tower Hamlets, London, E1 5JP, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Liberty
points_of_interest.description: The flagship, original store of the world-famous British brand. Lovely old building and great fun to browse in Liberty even if you are not going to buy something!

points_of_interest.name: Gosh! Comics
points_of_interest.description: Comic and graphic novel specialist.

points_of_interest.name: The Village Haberdashery
points_of_interest.description: An independent haberdashery.
points_of_interest.address: Hardy Building, West Hampstead Square, 6, Heritage Ln, NW6 2BR

points_of_interest.name: Waterstone's Piccadilly
points_of_interest.description: 5 floors of books of all kinds, plus a cafe in the basement and a restaurant on the top floor. The store has long hours and comfortable seating, so you can potentially spend hours in there.

points_of_interest.name: Beyond Retro
points_of_interest.description: Secondhand clothing (male and female).

points_of_interest.name: Cad & the Dandy
points_of_interest.description: Men's Suits Tailors & Shirtmakers Remarkable bespoke and made-to-measure suit tailors for men. Fine English fabrics. Also offer men's wedding suit tailoring. Design your suit using their online designing tool.

points_of_interest.name: M&M's World
points_of_interest.description: The largest sweet shop in the world. Unlike the New York City store, you can only buy the "regular" M&M flavours here, albeit in a wider variety of colours than you would usually find. There is also a wide array of other merchandise available such as homeware and clothing. In the back of the store is an M&M printer which enables you to print text, a logo or even your own face on M&Ms!

points_of_interest.name: Exmouth Market
points_of_interest.description: Area with lifestyle, fashion, health, book and interior shops. Trendy independent shops on a pedestrianised street.

points_of_interest.name: Rokit
points_of_interest.description: Secondhand clothing (male and female).

points_of_interest.name: Microsoft Experience Centre
points_of_interest.description: formerly Microsoft Store In a similar vein to the Apple store, the "Microsoft Experience Centre" stores are dedicated to showcasing the latest Microsoft products and services. A good chance to try the latest Surface computers. The Xbox gaming lounge is closed due to COVID-19.

points_of_interest.name: The Lego Store
points_of_interest.description: The world's largest Lego Store, with a massive Big Ben (yes, they mean the clock tower and not the actual bell -- feel free to tut loudly) sculpture made of building blocks, a Tube entrance arc, and a full scale Tube carriage model -- including Lego figures you can take a picture with!

points_of_interest.name: Hatton Garden
points_of_interest.description: This street is the centre of London's jewellery trade and especially famous for diamonds. A lot of dealers and designers to chose from, both contemporary and traditional.

points_of_interest.name: Brick Lane Market
points_of_interest.description: Selling second hand clothes, bric-a-brac, books, household goods and electronics.
points_of_interest.address: 123 Brick Lane, Tower Hamlets, London, E1 6SE, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Niketown
points_of_interest.description: Flagship store for Nike.

points_of_interest.name: Leather Lane Market
points_of_interest.description: Not much leather sold here these days but worth a visit for some great cheap finds. Clothing, electrical goods, toiletries and food. Combines well with a visit to Hatton Garden which is in the next street east.

points_of_interest.name: Tatty Devine
points_of_interest.description: Little shop specialising in accessories for men and women, such as volume level brooches and newspaper print ties.

points_of_interest.name: Fulham Broadway
points_of_interest.description: Small shopping centre built around the tube station of the same name. Includes a supermarket, some restaurants and cafés along with its other shops, as well as a cinema and pub.
points_of_interest.address: 460 Fulham Road, Hammersmith and Fulham, London, SW6 1BZ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Aspreys
points_of_interest.description: One of the most famous luxury jewellers anywhere in the world. At least have a look in the window

points_of_interest.name: St. George's Shopping Centre
points_of_interest.description: A few restaurants on the same floor as the cinema.

points_of_interest.name: Magma Books
points_of_interest.description: A fine bookshop specialising in the graphic arts, as well as toys, for not-quite-grown-up boys. A good place to pick up foreign design titles, or simply waste an hour browsing through lots of pretty books. A valuable stop for graphic junkies.

points_of_interest.name: Whitechapel Market
points_of_interest.description: A small street market selling food and spices, clothing, jewellery, carpets and the odd dodgy stereo.
points_of_interest.address: 231 Whitechapel Road, Tower Hamlets, London, E1 1DB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Hammersmith Broadway
points_of_interest.description: Small shopping centre inside Hammersmith station (District/Piccadilly) with a Tesco Metro supermarket, a Costa, a Starbuck's, a McDonald's, as well as several other shops and restaurants.

points_of_interest.name: Burberry
points_of_interest.description: Visit the flagship store on Bond St to examine the famous check.

points_of_interest.name: Gay's the Word
points_of_interest.description: The leading gay-related bookshop in Britain. It has been around since 1979, during which time it has been closely linked with LGBT rights and other activism, including the 'Lesbians and Gays Support the Miners' campaign in the 1980s. Visitors will find fiction books and a large academic stock.

points_of_interest.name: St. Ann's Shopping Centre
points_of_interest.description: Upstairs food court with a KFC, Burger King, Pizza Hut, etc.

points_of_interest.name: Ealing Market
points_of_interest.description: Street market with farm products.

points_of_interest.name: The Old Curiosity Shop
points_of_interest.description: The original shop immortalised in the Charles Dickens' novel by the same name. Nestled amongst the campus of LSE, it is worth a visit just for the old Tudor design itself. As the name suggests, it sells some oddities and knick-knacks, but mostly shoes these days.

points_of_interest.name: Canary Wharf Shopping Centre
points_of_interest.description: A shopping centre with the usual High Street shops, plus a John Lewis department store and a Waitrose food store which has the most stunning range of produce. Pleasant upmarket shopping centre, made up of three arcades: Canada, Cabot, and Jubilee Place. The three arcades encircle Jubilee Park and the Tube station, and house over 200 shops, bars, restaurants, and cafes that are open seven days a week. A relaxed shopping environment, especially good for clothes.

points_of_interest.name: Livat Hammersmith
points_of_interest.description: formerly Kings Mall A small 1-floor shopping centre with a large IKEA and H&M's London flagship store. There is also a Primark, Sainsbury's, Wilko and Three. Also has parking.

points_of_interest.name: Grays Antique Markets
points_of_interest.description: A remarkably diverse collection of antique and collectibles dealers all under one roof adjoining Bond St station. Certainly the best option in central London for visitors interested in collectibles in particular.

points_of_interest.name: Judd Books
points_of_interest.description: Large stock of used, remaindered and academic books especially in the fields of architecture, history and philosophy.

points_of_interest.name: Richmond's high street
points_of_interest.description: Contains a few boutique clothing stores and all the standard high street chains, such as Habitat, Marks & Spencer's, WH Smith, Boots, and Robert Dyas. For more boutique clothes shops, such as Matches, and small art galleries and antiques shops, follow the road up the hill called Hill St, which turns into Hill Rise. The alleys off George Street are lined with mostly privately owned boutiques. Two of these are purveyors of fine chocolates: one is '''The House of Chocolate''' located on the corner of Brewers Lane, a long-standing family-run business; the other, a stone's throw to the west on Paved Court, is '''William Curley''', a chocolatier whose award-winning fare, together with pastries and hot drinks, can be consumed on the premises. Another independent shop is '''Gelateria Danieli''', selling gelato ice cream, located on Brewers Lane, which ''Time Out'' has listed as one of the best ice cream parlours in London.

points_of_interest.name: High Road
points_of_interest.description: Mile-long shopping street containing many high street chains and independent shops.
points_of_interest.address: 95 High Road, Haringey, London, N22 6BB, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Smithfield Market
points_of_interest.description: Smithfield Market is London's largest wholesale meat market and hence a great source of fresh meat from Britain and around the world. Additionally, there are many good restaurants in the vicinity.

points_of_interest.name: Roman Road Market
points_of_interest.description: A mix of traditional goods, from high street brands to fish, lying just outside the traditional East End, but has the character. Roman has it all. Market runs Tuesday, Thursday and Saturday until 5PM.

points_of_interest.name: West 12 Shopping Centre
points_of_interest.description: W12 Much smaller than Westfield London opposite and more representative of the Shepherd's Bush area as a whole. However, the Vue cinema tickets are several pounds cheaper. On the ground floor, there's a CeX and several discount supermarkets including Poundland and Lidl. Upstairs, there's a Wetherspoon's. The [https://www.thegameisnow.com/ Sherlock: The Official Live Game] requires booking but is great fun for a family or group of friends.

points_of_interest.name: Beatles store
points_of_interest.description: Souvenirs and memorabilia.

points_of_interest.name: Broadway Market
points_of_interest.description: Visit on a Saturday. Has a variety of gastropubs and trendy clothes!
points_of_interest.address: 35-37 Broadway Market, Hackney, London, E8 4PH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Persephone Books

points_of_interest.name: The Open Book
points_of_interest.description: Independent bookshop. Rather cramped, but stacked with a very good selection of new books, including signed copies.

points_of_interest.name: The Mall Wood Green
points_of_interest.description: It features many high street chains and independent shops, as well as a covered market with a large food section including butchers, fishmongers, fruit and vegetables and international food.

points_of_interest.name: The Waterglade Centre
points_of_interest.description: formerly Arcadia Centre

points_of_interest.name: Tesco Express
points_of_interest.description: Small, local branch of the supermarket. Starbucks and Eat next door.

points_of_interest.name: Rough Trade East
