points_of_interest.name: New Shepherd's Bush Market
points_of_interest.description: Privately owned street market.

points_of_interest.name: Ridley Road Market
points_of_interest.description: Mix of traditional East-end fruit and veg alongside Afro-Caribbean delicacies, imported films, clothes and household items. Little of interest for the tourist to buy, but a great experience. Watch your pockets in the crowded pavements behind the stalls. There are also market stalls on the side streets surrounding Dalston Kingsland station.

points_of_interest.name: Skoob
points_of_interest.description: Wide selection of second-hand academic books, philosophy, modern literature and classics. Very popular with students.

points_of_interest.name: Waterstones
points_of_interest.description: Branch of a big chain store.

points_of_interest.name: Seven Sisters Market
points_of_interest.description: Pueblito Paisa As the slogan goes, "''lo pequeño es hermoso''" - small is beautiful - and the UK's only "Latin village" really is tiny, but an extraordinary diversity of hispanic businesses (cafés, street food stands, butchers, greengrocers) and services (community post office, legal advice) manage to squeeze in, while still leaving room for customers. Threatened with closure due to gentrification as of 2020, so visit ''prontísimo''.

points_of_interest.name: Any Amount of Books
points_of_interest.description: Rare and second-hand books. Specialist in scholarly academic works and art-related titles.

points_of_interest.name: The Chimes
points_of_interest.description: formerly Intu Uxbridge Includes H&M, HMV, Next, Toys R Us, Boots, Chiquito, Frankie & Benny's, Odeon Cinema.

points_of_interest.name: Waitrose
points_of_interest.description: Slightly more upmarket supermarket.
points_of_interest.address: Cherry Tree Walk Centre, Whitecross St, EC1Y 8NX

points_of_interest.name: North End Road Market
points_of_interest.description: A London street market that's high on character and low on tourists, this has been running since the 1880s. A good place for fresh and affordable fruit and vegetables, household goods, and other items.
points_of_interest.address: Running the length of North End Rd, between Lille Rd and Fulham Rd

points_of_interest.name: Kingsland Shopping Centre
points_of_interest.description: The main shopping mall in the borough.
points_of_interest.hours: M–Sa 8AM–10PM, Su & holidays 11AM–5PM, closed Christmas & Easter

points_of_interest.name: Collinge & Clark
points_of_interest.description: Specialises in graphic design and typography. It was also used as an exterior location for the Channel 4 sitcom ''Black Books''.

points_of_interest.name: Duck Pond Market
points_of_interest.description: Street food Market.

points_of_interest.name: Greenwich Arts and Crafts Market
points_of_interest.description: An indoor market also selling good food, and containing many interesting little shops.

points_of_interest.name: West Green Road shops
points_of_interest.description: Specialist Caribbean and African food, open till late.

points_of_interest.name: David Drummond at Pleasures of Past Times
points_of_interest.description: Specialises in books and other memorabilia related to the performing arts and old children's books.

points_of_interest.name: The Pavilions
points_of_interest.description: Home to many high street names including Marks & Spencers and Argos.

points_of_interest.name: Shepherd's Bush Market
points_of_interest.description: An astonishing array of goods with Afro-Caribbean, Middle Eastern and Indian cultural influences vying for the shopper's attention.
points_of_interest.address: Between Uxbridge Rd and Goldhawk Rd

points_of_interest.name: Stamford Hill
points_of_interest.description: The centre of the Hassidic Jewish community and has many kosher bakeries, delis and supermarkets.
points_of_interest.address: 1 Linthorpe Road, Hackney, London, N16 5RE, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Treadwell's Books
points_of_interest.description: Bookshop specialising in esotericism, occultism and magic. Also offers tarot readings.

points_of_interest.name: Barnes Farmers Market
points_of_interest.address: Essex House, Station Rd, London SW13 9HG

points_of_interest.name: The Flea Market
points_of_interest.description: Selling what you would expect.

points_of_interest.name: Goldsboro Books
points_of_interest.description: First editions and signed fiction.

points_of_interest.name: Treaty Centre
points_of_interest.description: Home to the usual retailers you find on many High Streets up and down the country including JD and Debenhams.

points_of_interest.name: Westfield Shopping Centre
points_of_interest.description: The largest urban shopping mall in Europe outside of Russia. A vast array of stores including a designer section called The Village featuring Prada, Louis Vuitton, Hugo Boss, Jimmy Choo, Bucherer, Hogan, and Versus Versace. Along with an assortment of restaurants including Nando's, Pizza Express, Pho, Byron's, Zizzi, Wagamama and Wahaca. There is a 14 Vue screen cinema at the top, usually, the prices are slightly more expensive than the W12 Shopping Centre Vue across the road. The disabled toilets require a RADAR key to open.

points_of_interest.name: Stoke Newington Church St
points_of_interest.description: Many small bookshops and antique stores.
points_of_interest.address: 6 Lordship Road, Hackney, London, N16 0QT, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Roberto Revilla
points_of_interest.description: Bespoke tailoring services and luxury accessories.
points_of_interest.address: Savva Tailors Workroom, Shropshire House, 179 Tottenham Court Rd, W1T 7NZ

points_of_interest.name: Kew Bookshop
points_of_interest.description: Hewson Books Independent bookshop.
points_of_interest.hours: M–Sa 9:30AM–5:30PM, Su & holidays 11AM–5PM, closed Easter & Christmas

points_of_interest.name: Greenwich Vintage Market
points_of_interest.description: Greenwich Antiques Market The name is a bit deceptive but it does have plenty of old books, music, clothes and jewellery.

points_of_interest.name: Paul J Hilton
points_of_interest.description: Antiquarian and general books, especially first edition English literature.

points_of_interest.name: Bookcase
points_of_interest.description: A small independent bookshop with a lot of discounted books. Take a look at the tables outside as you pass by.

points_of_interest.name: X Electrical
points_of_interest.description: A pawn shop specialising in musical instruments, amps and hi-fis. Also has a retro video game collection with prices as low as £2.

points_of_interest.name: Chatsworth Road Market
points_of_interest.address: 53 Chatsworth Road, Hackney, London, E5 0LH, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Millenia
points_of_interest.description: Pop culture merchandise from famous franchises such as Pokémon, Harry Potter and Dungeons & Dragons.

points_of_interest.name: Kew Retail Park
points_of_interest.description: Marks and Spencer, Boots, Next, Costa Coffee, TK Maxx.

points_of_interest.name: The Central Market
points_of_interest.description: The largest part of the market that sells homeware, furniture and books.

points_of_interest.name: Henry Pordes Books Ltd
points_of_interest.description: Secondhand, antiquarian and all out-of print books.

points_of_interest.name: Foster Books
points_of_interest.description: Antiquarian bookseller set in a small old-fashioned shop with a curved window. Apparently the oldest bookshop on the Chiswick High Road.

points_of_interest.name: Amnesty Bookshop Hammersmith
points_of_interest.description: Has a good selection of discounted fiction and non-fiction books over many genres.

points_of_interest.name: London Fields Brewery
points_of_interest.description: Every Saturday, London Fields Brewery run brewery tours. Come down and have a guided tour of the brewery and learn how they are making their superbly tasty beers. Also included in the price are tastings of the beers in the BrewHouse, the brewery's very own pop-up bar.

points_of_interest.name: Tottenham Court Road
points_of_interest.description: The centre for electronics retailers in London. If you are visiting the city and need to buy or replace an electronic item, you will not find a better selection nor better prices than here. Explore both sides of the street to the north of Tottenham Court Road station.
points_of_interest.address: 75 Tottenham Court Road, Camden, London, W1T 2HF, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Lloyds of Kew Bookshop
points_of_interest.description: Second-hand books.

points_of_interest.name: Quinto Bookshop & Francis Edwards
points_of_interest.description: Huge collection. Francis Edwards have been in business here since 1856.

points_of_interest.name: The square in Ealing Broadway
points_of_interest.description: Often eventful, with beautiful decorations at Christmas time and musicians performing in the Summer. Christmas and Easter markets also take place in the shopping centre square.

points_of_interest.name: Ümit & Son Store
points_of_interest.description: DVD, VHS, Videodiscs, 8mm film reels and more are all sold here. Projectors and equipment for some of the less standard formats are available for hire and the shop also offers a video-to-digital transfer service.

points_of_interest.name: The Brunswick Centre
points_of_interest.description: Shopping centre with a large Waitrose supermarket and some other shops.
points_of_interest.address: 37 Brunswick Square, Camden, London, WC1N 1AF, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Mia Wood
points_of_interest.description: Gifts.
points_of_interest.address: 9 Station Parade, Kew Gardens Village Richmond, TW9 3PS

points_of_interest.name: Arthur Beale
points_of_interest.description: Yachting Chandler A quite unusual shop for the centre of London. A marine supply store which sells numerous items related to yachting: from clothing to sailing hardware and accessories. The shop has been at its current location for over 120 years.

points_of_interest.name: Barnard's Books
points_of_interest.description: A small independent bookshop. There's an extensive WWII section at the back.

points_of_interest.name: London Borough of Jam
points_of_interest.description: Boutique jam shop, selling all natural jams free of commercial pectins.

points_of_interest.name: Olivers Wholefoods Store
points_of_interest.description: Health foods and alternative therapies.
points_of_interest.address: 5 Station Approach, Kew Gardens, Richmond, TW9 3QB

points_of_interest.name: Borough Market
points_of_interest.description: One of London's favourite wholesale working food markets, on Fridays and Saturdays offering a general retail market with specialties sold directly from the producers, organic products, delicatessen, cheese, wines, fish and imported continental fare. Around the market are other excellent food shops, for a total food experience! Pick up some food and enjoy it under Southwark Cathedral. For market shopping, go in the morning, or after 2PM, since it gets very crowded at lunchtime.
points_of_interest.address: 8 Southwark Street, Southwark, London, SE1 1TL, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Ocean Leisure
points_of_interest.description: Watersports-related items.

points_of_interest.name: The Shoe Station
points_of_interest.description: Children's shoes.

points_of_interest.name: Gabriel’s Wharf
points_of_interest.description: An eclectic mix of shops and restaurants, the design shops at Gabriel's Wharf are exclusively run by small businesses who design and manufacture their own products, the majority of work available will have been made by the person selling it to you. If you can't find exactly what you are looking for it is possible to commission many of the designers directly. Shops to look out for include Bicha, Game of Graces and Anne Kyyro Quinn., Try a crepe here
points_of_interest.address: 56 Upper Ground, Lambeth, London, SE1 9PP, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Astrology Shop
points_of_interest.description: The place to buy astrology books and tarot cards.

points_of_interest.name: Tesco Express
points_of_interest.description: Small supermarket.
points_of_interest.address: 2-8 Station Parade, Kew Gardens, Richmond, TW9 3PZ

points_of_interest.name: Hay's Galleria
points_of_interest.description: A beautiful converted wharf on the Jubilee Walk which, since 1987, has been home to cafés, shops and traditional barrows. Originally a warehouse and associated wharf (Hay's Wharf) for the port of London, it was redeveloped as a visitor attraction in the 1950s and has lots of boutique shops.
points_of_interest.address: 2 Battle Bridge Lane, Southwark, London, SE1 2HL, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Ben's Cookies
points_of_interest.description: Very nice cookies - try their white chocolate with macadamia cookies. Price is about £1 per cookie, and the cookies here are almost twice as big as those at Millie's. They also have branches at 12 Kensington Arcade, Kensington High St; at 39 Leadenhall Market; and at 9 Pelham St, South Kensington.

points_of_interest.name: Southbank Book Market
points_of_interest.description: Second-hand book sale near the bank of the Thames. A nice place to just browse for books (classic and modern), maps and prints.

points_of_interest.name: Monmouth Coffee
points_of_interest.description: Some people say this is the best coffee in London. Primarily a venue for quality coffee roasters, the shop on Monmouth street has a ''tasting room'', i.e. a café, where you can marvel at the fact that not everywhere in London sells poor chain-café coffee. A selection of goodies such as croissants, pastries, and brownies are also available. As you would expect of a roasters you can also purchase excellent coffee in bean form or ground, with various blends to suit your taste. Helpful and knowledgeable staff can help you make a selection.

points_of_interest.name: Bromley Charter Market
points_of_interest.address: 107-109 High Street, Bromley, BR1 1JQ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Oxo Tower Wharf
points_of_interest.description: Huge galleria.

points_of_interest.name: Neal's Yard Dairy
points_of_interest.description: A fabulous cheese shop specialising in British cheeses. The smell as you walk up the street can be enticing or repulsive, depending on your preference for fragrant cheese. But regardless, a trip to this shop is well worthwhile. Whether they are busy or not, the staff are always keen to have you taste a few cheeses to ensure you find what you are looking for. Everyone here is passionate about their cheese, and while the prices are higher than you will pay pretty much anywhere else in the world for cheese, the quality and taste are second to none.

points_of_interest.name: The Glades
points_of_interest.description: formerly intu Bromley The bulk of the better-known stores are in this area.

points_of_interest.name: Stanfords
points_of_interest.description: This is the flagship store of the world's largest map retailer. They have been selling maps and travel guidebooks of all descriptions from this location since 1901. With three floors of regional maps, walking maps, guidebooks, travel books, a digital mapping service and more this is a huge store that is interesting even if you do not intend to buy anything.

points_of_interest.name: The Mall
points_of_interest.description: Does not get many shoppers.
points_of_interest.address: 7-15 The Mall, Bromley, BR1 1TR, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Thomas Neals Centre
points_of_interest.description: A nice shopping plaza with clothes shops, design shops and cafes.

points_of_interest.name: Centrale Shopping Centre
points_of_interest.description: Shopping centre opened in 2004, situated on 4 floors. Shops include House of Fraser, Next, Zara, H&M, French Connection and Aldo. The Food Gallery is on the top floor of centre and includes a wide variety of restaurants.

points_of_interest.name: The Tintin Shop
points_of_interest.description: The place to go in Britain for fans of the Belgian reporter. Sells non-fiction books, clothes, posters, figurines and memorabilia, as well as each of Hergé's 24 ''Adventures of Tintin'' comic books in English, the original French and any other language you can think of.

points_of_interest.name: North End
points_of_interest.description: The shopping road in Croydon.
points_of_interest.address: 60-68 North End, Croydon, CR0 1UJ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Kryolan City London
points_of_interest.description: This is where the professionals buy make-up, so on the pricey side, but the range of products kept is large. Staff are highly approachable even on specialist queries.

points_of_interest.name: Purley Way
points_of_interest.description: A retail-heavy road including large stores such as IKEA, a B&Q warehouse, TK Maxx, Vue, Megabowl, Argos Extra, and Sainsbury's. Retail parks include Valley Park, Purley Way Retail Park and Croydon Collonades, Waddon Goods Park.
points_of_interest.address: 222-226 Purley Way, Croydon, CR0 4XG, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Hilditch & Key
points_of_interest.description: With another branch at {{marker|type=buy|name=73 Jermyn St, SW1Y 6NP|lat=51.5076|long=-0.1389}}

points_of_interest.name: Forbidden Planet
points_of_interest.description: Massive "geek supplies" store for London and the South-East. Merchandise (T-shirts, toys, figurines, etc.) on the ground floor, comics and manga (all genres) and SF, fantasy and horror books in the basement. Lots of U.S. publications that are rarely available in other London bookstores.

points_of_interest.name: Surrey Street Market
points_of_interest.description: Market which has a Royal Charter dating back to 1276 linking it to the Archbishop of Canterbury.
points_of_interest.address: 44 Surrey Street, Croydon, CR0 1RJ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Whitgift Shopping Centre
points_of_interest.description: Main shopping centre, situated on 3 floors and used to be biggest shopping centre in Europe. Shops include Marks & Spencer, Boots, WHSmith, Sainsbury's Central, Mothercare and Books Etc. Various restaurants and cafes throughout the centre.
points_of_interest.hours: M-W, F Sa 9AM-7PM, Th 9AM-9PM, Su 11AM-5PM, Bank holidays 10AM-6PM

points_of_interest.name: Mimzi
points_of_interest.description: A little Bulgarian supermarket selling various inexpensive Eastern European foods. If you can't read Cyrillic you may have to guess what you're buying.

points_of_interest.name: Budd Shirts
points_of_interest.description: Budd, established in 1910, is the only Jermyn Street shirtmaker to still have a bespoke cutting room on site, where shirts are still made.

points_of_interest.name: Bentall centre
points_of_interest.description: Biggest shopping mall. Four-storey mall, which is anchored by a multi-level department store, Bentalls, which sells high-end fashion, home ware and specialty food products. John Lewis is the other main department store in town and is noted for quality. It has a branch of Waitrose supermarket in the basement.

points_of_interest.name: Cardinal Place
points_of_interest.description: High street shops like Marks & Spencer and a selection of chain restaurants.

points_of_interest.name: One New Change
points_of_interest.description: The City's only modern shopping centre, which opened in October 2010. Includes around 60 shops and restaurants. It is situated right by St Paul's Cathedral and is in a small area of retailing, including Cheapside and the cobbled, old-fashioned Bow Lane. Both the freely accessible roof terrace, and the lifts to get there, offer excellent views of St Paul's.
points_of_interest.address: 8 Cheapside Passage, City of London, London, EC2V 6AF, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Fife Road
points_of_interest.description: Several clothing boutiques.
points_of_interest.address: 41 Fife Road, Kingston upon Thames, KT1 1SF, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Les Senteurs
points_of_interest.description: Specialist perfumery.

points_of_interest.name: Leadenhall Market
points_of_interest.description: Worth visiting for its architecture and old-fashioned cobbled streets. It was used as a location in ''Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone''.
points_of_interest.address: 1 Lime Street Passage, City of London, London, EC3V 1AY, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Kingston Marketplace
points_of_interest.description: The marketplace was historically at the heart of Kingston's prosperity, benefiting from a Royal Charter forbidding any other markets within seven miles. Today it mostly sells fruit and vegetables, although there are some other stalls. There are also occasional visiting markets from France and Germany that sell regional produce and takeaway food and drink.
points_of_interest.address: 5 Market Place, Kingston upon Thames, KT1 1JX, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Retromania
points_of_interest.description: Charity shop specialising in vintage and retro clothing.

points_of_interest.name: Royal Exchange
points_of_interest.description: Situated opposite the Bank of England, the Exchange houses a number of upmarket outlets. Part of the exterior was featured in the film ''Bridget Jones' Diary'' (at the end, when Bridget runs after Mark along a snowy street).
points_of_interest.address: 2 Royal Exchange Avenue, City of London, London, EC3V 3DG, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Spitalfields Market
points_of_interest.description: Just outside the City and owned by the City of London Corporation Once a large thriving market, it has slowly been shrunk to a third of its size by development in the area. It features a good variety of clothing, crafts and food stalls/shops. Rather promisingly sellers have set up another market in a new space off Hanbury St nearby. Visit 66/68 Bell Lane nearby to see a wealthy merchant's house, rumour has it John Lennon once played on the roof of this building with Yoko Ono.

points_of_interest.name: Tesco Express
points_of_interest.description: Small, local branch of the supermarket

points_of_interest.name: Sainsbury's Local
points_of_interest.description: Small, local branch of the supermarket. In a pedestrian square near St. Paul's Cathedral.

points_of_interest.name: The Duke of York Square Shopping Complex
points_of_interest.description: Has a range of spacious branches of popular fashion chains, but lacks some of the road's character, however the small adjoining public space of Duke of York square is a welcome place for a rest between shopping, and a popular place to hang out.
points_of_interest.address: 82 Duke Of York Square, Kensington and Chelsea, London, SW3 4LY, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Harrods
points_of_interest.description: The most famous store in London, favoured by the British establishment and owned by the state of Qatar. As of 2023, their [https://www.harrods.com/en-us/faqs/visiting-our-store website FAQ] says about dress code: "We do not have a specific dress code for entry into the store, including any of our restaurants. However, we do reserve the right to refuse entry to anyone who is not deemed to be appropriately dressed. Sportswear, including trainers, shorts, and tracksuits, are permitted across all areas of the store and restaurants."

points_of_interest.name: Harvey Nichols
points_of_interest.description: Large department store full of designer goods and an excellent cafe.

points_of_interest.name: The Hummingbird Bakery
points_of_interest.description: A nice little bakery with wonderful cupcakes. Try their red velvet cupcake that is incredibly popular with the locals; it even comes in a gluten-free version.

points_of_interest.name: H.R. Owen Ferrari London
points_of_interest.description: If the expensive clothes and products in other shops don't appeal, expensive cars are also available in this area.

points_of_interest.name: King's Road
points_of_interest.description: One of London's smartest fashion streets, having evolved from the cutting-edge of bohemia and innovative fashion in the 1960s to a more genteel place to indulge in retail therapy, albeit with a notable presence of trendy young Londoners (including many so called Sloane Rangers). It is a very attractive street that retains the atmosphere of a small town whilst being in the heart of a huge city. There is a huge range of fashion stores from upmarket chains to one-off boutiques, as well as variety of other shops, complimented by cafés, restaurants, bars, pubs and clubs. There is an obvious affluence to the road without any bling or snobbiness. King's Road stretches south-west from here for miles, though the best of the shopping is in the first mile.
points_of_interest.address: 191 King's Road, Kensington and Chelsea, London, SW3 5ED, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Lamborghini London
points_of_interest.description: If you fancy a new car and have a lot of spare change, it might be worth a look. Poorer people are allowed to look at the shiny cars too.

points_of_interest.name: Sloane Street
points_of_interest.description: Lined with high-end designer label stores, such as Chanel, Dior, Fendi, Gucci, Hermès, Jimmy Choo, Louis Vitton, and many more.
points_of_interest.address: 30 Cadogan Place, Kensington and Chelsea, London, SW1X 9RX, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Whole Foods Market
points_of_interest.description: The Kensington branch of this American chain of natural food supermarkets is the largest in the world.

points_of_interest.name: The Carnival Store
points_of_interest.description: Fancy dress stocking an extensive range of budget to mid-range costumes, masks and acessories, staff are very approachable and prepared to answer queries.

points_of_interest.name: Ibis Hotel Stratford
points_of_interest.description: 104-room hotel with the usual identikit, Ibis set-up.

points_of_interest.name: Bluebells Hotel
points_of_interest.description: In a converted early Victorian building. 30 rooms on four storeys but no lift. Five minutes' walk to Notting Hill Gate and Portobello Rd.

points_of_interest.name: Newham Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Budget hotel in the Forest Gate area of Newham

points_of_interest.name: Notting Hill Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Old converted Victorian building in a quiet square only 5 minutes from Notting Hill Gate. Single, double and family rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Umi Hotel
points_of_interest.description: On a quiet garden square 5 minutes walk from Bayswater station. Single, double and family rooms with en suite bath. A few dormitory rooms.

points_of_interest.name: The Abbey Court
points_of_interest.description: Boutique hotel in a converted Victorian house and decorated in that period style. 22 rooms, no lift.

points_of_interest.name: Travelodge London Stratford
points_of_interest.description: Usual Travelodge set-up. New hotel, spotless rooms with private facilities. 24-hour bar. Friendly staff prepared to go the extra mile. Price - depends, can be as low as £30 for a double room if you pay well in advance and pay up front ("Saver Rate").

points_of_interest.name: Sunborn London
points_of_interest.description: Sunborn Yacht Hotel Luxurious 4-star yacht hotel. London's only and one of a kind yacht hotel situated at the Royal Victoria Dock in London. This floating hotel boast of their surrounding views of Canary Wharf, ExCeL and O2 Arena and the hospitality. It also has a sea themed tea room named Under The Sea Afternoon Tea.

points_of_interest.name: Fraser Suites Queensgate
points_of_interest.description: One of the closest serviced accomodations to Notting Hill, this hotel is known for a range of amenities and services for business guests.

points_of_interest.name: 54 Queens's Gate
points_of_interest.description: Comfy, stylish small hotel by major sights. No children under 16 or dogs.

points_of_interest.name: Laslett
points_of_interest.description: Buzzing hotel in Victorian knock-through, great comfort, style and service.

points_of_interest.name: Antoinette Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A 50-bedroom hotel, refurbished.

points_of_interest.name: Portobello Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Stylish offbeat hotel in knock-through of two mansions. Some rooms are very small.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel du Vin
points_of_interest.description: A beautiful hotel overlooking Cannizaro Park to the rear and Wimbledon Common to the front. Excellent dining.
points_of_interest.address: Cannizaro House, West Side Common, Wimbledon, SW19 4UE

points_of_interest.name: Brewers Inn Wandsworth
points_of_interest.description: A Youngs' pub with rooms. Full English breakfast included.

points_of_interest.name: Equity Point London
points_of_interest.description: An affordable hostel that has clean and cheap rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Flexistay ApartHotel Tooting
points_of_interest.description: Budget serviced apartments. Single and double studios available. nightly, weekly and monthly rentals.

points_of_interest.name: The Wimbledon Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Small family-run hotel.

points_of_interest.name: Smart Camden Inn Hostel
points_of_interest.description: Part of the Smart Backpackers chain of hostels, on the street next to Camden High Street.

points_of_interest.name: The Green Man Publove Hostel
points_of_interest.description: Very cheap hostel above a pub aimed at young partying types. Gets very raucous indeed. Dorm and private rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Holiday Inn Express London - Wandsworth
points_of_interest.description: The usual Holiday Inn Express set up.

points_of_interest.name: St Christopher's Camden Hostel
points_of_interest.description: On the corner of Camden High St and Plender St, which is home to a small morning market. Belushi's bar on the ground floor.

points_of_interest.name: Ascot Hyde Park Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Popular budget hotel.

points_of_interest.name: The Lodge Hotel London
points_of_interest.description: Situated in a great central London location, this three-star Best Western hotel is high quality and affordable.

points_of_interest.name: London City Apartments
points_of_interest.description: Budget studio apartments with kitchens. Maximum 2 person occupancy.

points_of_interest.name: YHA London St Pancras
points_of_interest.description: St Pancras International Youth Hostel The largest of the five London YHA hostels, minutes walk from St Pancras International railway station.

points_of_interest.name: Bluedaws Private Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Very clean budget hotel.

points_of_interest.name: Pembury Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Budget hotel opposite Finsbury Pk Stn. Popular with football fans as it is close to the Emirates Stadium. Cheap, clean and noisy.

points_of_interest.name: Holiday Inn London - Camden Lock
points_of_interest.description: A modern hotel with 130 rooms beside the canal at Camden Lock.

points_of_interest.name: Radisson Blu Edwardian Hampshire Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Small luxury hotel furnished in a sleek, contemporary design.

points_of_interest.name: Hilton London Angel Islington
points_of_interest.description: Next door to the Business Design Centre.

points_of_interest.name: Premier Inn London King's Cross
points_of_interest.description: A modern, clean, reasonably priced hotel.

points_of_interest.name: Charlotte Guest House
points_of_interest.description: Traditional B&B with 43 rooms ranging from singles to family suites. The cheapest rooms do not have private bathrooms.

points_of_interest.name: Thistle Piccadilly
points_of_interest.description: Affordable and centrally located but a tired property.

points_of_interest.name: Mitre House Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Two-star hotel.

points_of_interest.name: Pullman London St. Pancras
points_of_interest.description: formerly Novotel St. Pancras It is equidistant from the St. Pancras and Euston railway stations. This former corporate Novotel was taken over and completely refurbished by Accor's upscale Pullman brand. It features rather spacious rooms and interesting views from upper floors, as well as modern decor and fitments and all the creature comforts expected from an upscale hotel.

points_of_interest.name: Dawson House
points_of_interest.description: Budget guest house with 15 rooms including family options. A five-minute walk to the West Hampstead stations.

points_of_interest.name: The Trafalgar
points_of_interest.description: Hilton's first boutique hotel in London. The boardroom was apparently used for the first James Bond film ''Dr. No''.

points_of_interest.name: St. Pancras Renaissance Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Midland Hotel This is the rebirth of the former Midland Hotel that operated the space from 1873-1935, inside the palatial heritage-listed Neo-Gothic St. Pancras station building above. Definitely outside the budget of many travellers, but for architectural aficionados this is one hotel that should be stayed in at least once in a lifetime.

points_of_interest.name: Dillons
points_of_interest.description: Bed and breakfast in a converted Victorian building in Belsize Park. Quiet and reserved residential neighbourhood but easy access to Hampstead Village.

points_of_interest.name: Premier Inn London Leicester Square
points_of_interest.description: Premier Inn are a popular mid-range budget hotel chain, but in this location you're unlikely to find a night for under £100.

points_of_interest.name: Brynteg Hotel
points_of_interest.description: 3-star bed and breakfast. Well-appointed, modern bedrooms with spotlessly clean and en-suite facilities.

points_of_interest.name: Great Northern Hotel
points_of_interest.description: The railway hotel of King's Cross station, and the oldest of London's railway hotels, opened in 1854. The hotel is named after the Great Northern Railway, the company that built King's Cross station and operated it until 1923.

points_of_interest.name: La Gaffe
points_of_interest.description: Charming boutique bed and breakfast accommodation above a restaurant and wine bar of the same name. Family owned and managed.

points_of_interest.name: Haymarket Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Lovely stylish place at the top of Pall Mall, great comfort and cuisine.

points_of_interest.name: Lancaster Hall Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Small hotel run by the YMCA. Rooms are small and basic, but reasonably priced and comfortable (and with free Wi-Fi). Breakfast is normally served from 7:30-9:30AM (though apparently can be arranged earlier through management the day before) and consists of various breads, jams, hardboiled eggs, cottage cheese, deli meats, yoghurts and breakfast cereals; with a choice of fruit juices and tea or coffee. Not to be confused with the much more expensive Royal Lancaster Hotel.

points_of_interest.name: Langorf Hotel and Apartments
points_of_interest.description: Converted townhouse within walking distance of Hampstead Village.

points_of_interest.name: Mercure London Paddington Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Good value for the price. The rooms are tiny, but that is where the resemblance to other London hotels ends. The rooms are immaculate, the plumbing is perfect, the decor is beautiful, and the fitness room is brand new.

points_of_interest.name: Caspian Hotel
points_of_interest.description: On the slightly cheaper end of the scale.

points_of_interest.name: Maiden Oval Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Nice little economy hotel with friendly staff. Very simple clean rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Palmer's Lodge Hostel
points_of_interest.description: A high-quality hostel in a converted Victorian mansion. Has private rooms and a number of dorm options. Offers free WiFi, breakfast included in the price and nice touches such as serving fair trade coffee only.

points_of_interest.name: The Pilgrim
points_of_interest.description: In three Victorian townhouses, reception and service are automated. Comfy place right by the railway station.

points_of_interest.name: Chelsea Guest House
points_of_interest.description: Nice little economy hotel with friendly staff. Very simple clean rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Swiss Cottage Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Best Western Converted Victorian townhouse with 59 rooms. Two-minute walk to Swiss Cottage tube station.

points_of_interest.name: Travelodge
points_of_interest.address: Res Centre, High St, Feltham TW13 4GU

points_of_interest.name: Church Street Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Small beautifully decorated boutique hotel. Also the amazing '''Hotel Pasha''' is nearby.

points_of_interest.name: Hilton London Hyde Park
points_of_interest.description: Opposite Hyde Park, with136 guest rooms, a bar, a restaurant and a meeting room.

points_of_interest.name: London Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Small budget hotel.

points_of_interest.name: Martel Guest House
points_of_interest.description: Comfortable rooms, reasonably priced.

points_of_interest.name: Hilton London Paddington
points_of_interest.description: Essentially inside Paddington Station. A nice and convenient place to stay, particularly if someone else is picking up the tab.

points_of_interest.name: No 7 Guesthouse
points_of_interest.description: A bed and breakfast run by a friendly gay couple.

points_of_interest.name: The Crown London Hotel
points_of_interest.description: 4-star hotel.

points_of_interest.name: Royal Lancaster London
points_of_interest.description: Right alongside Hyde Park and many of the rooms have clear views over the park.

points_of_interest.name: Clayton Hotel Chiswick
points_of_interest.description: 116 designer rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Park Plaza London Riverbank
points_of_interest.description: Stylish and reputable.

points_of_interest.name: London Backpackers Hostel
points_of_interest.description: Decorated in bright colours. Female-only and mixed dorms with shared bathroom facilities; private rooms are also available. Free Wi-Fi and lockers. Continental breakfast included. There's also a kitchen, TV lounge, games room, business centre and laundrette.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Indigo London-Paddington
points_of_interest.description: Close to Paddington Station.

points_of_interest.name: Danubius Hotel Regents Park
points_of_interest.description: Very friendly staff. Spotlessly clean quiet room. Great view of Regents Park. Breakfast is excellent. Service the same. The location is superb, particularly for any cricket fan, as it looks right over Lords cricket ground.

points_of_interest.name: Premier Inn
points_of_interest.description: Premier Inn London Heathrow Airport (Bath Road) Hotel This hotel is just outside the northeast perimeter of Heathrow Airport. It is a very well maintained facility with excellent service. A free shuttle runs from the hotel to Heathrow's terminals on a routine schedule. This hotel has a full-service restaurant, and a Costa coffee shop. Basic WiFi is free and an upgrade can be purchased.
points_of_interest.address: Heathrow Airport Terminal 5, 420 Bath Road, Longford UB7 0EA

points_of_interest.name: Roseate House
points_of_interest.description: Chic hotel in a knock-through of three Victorian townhouses.

points_of_interest.name: Abbey Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Budget hotel close to the BBC Television Centre. Discounts for long stays.

points_of_interest.name: YHA London Oxford Street
points_of_interest.description: Oxford Street Youth Hostel A busy, vibrant hostel, not a place for a quiet break. Self-catering kitchen. 2-4 bed rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Hilton London Metropole
points_of_interest.description: Modern 4-star hotel. Amenities include various meeting rooms, a Mediterranean-style restaurant and a contemporary lounge bar. There's also an indoor pool and a gym, along with a steam room and a sauna.

points_of_interest.name: Adria Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A four generation family run hotel with excellent transport connections and good value for money. Regularly refurbished.

points_of_interest.name: Grantly Hotel
points_of_interest.description: No-frills budget hotel in a converted Edwardian house. Single, Double and Family rooms available.

points_of_interest.name: Holiday Inn London - Oxford Circus
points_of_interest.description: A clean hotel. As typical for Holiday Inns, dinner for children under 12 is free. Wheelchair access through rear. No pets. No smoking.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Sergul
points_of_interest.description: Affordable smart hotel with excellent links to West End and close to Olympia and Earls Court exhibition centre.

points_of_interest.name: Holiday Inn London - Regents Park
points_of_interest.description: The hotel is near attractions including Madame Tussauds and has a restaurant and bar. It is also close to Tube and railway stations.

points_of_interest.name: Jim's Guest House
points_of_interest.description: Good value bed and breakfast. Family suite available.

points_of_interest.name: Bromley Court Hotel
points_of_interest.description: An elegant old-time place, that has been taken over now by Best Western.

points_of_interest.name: The Leonard Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Offers central London accommodation from grand suites to individually decorated bedrooms near the shops of Oxford Street and Bond Street and local attractions.

points_of_interest.name: Amhurst Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Budget hotel in north London with self-catering facilities.

points_of_interest.name: Plaza Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Actually three hotels all run by the same company - The Plaza, The Rex and The Acropolis. All similar standard and nearby to each other.

points_of_interest.name: Lincoln House Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A three-star accommodation a few minutes from Madame Tussauds, Sherlock Holmes museum, Hyde Park corner.

points_of_interest.name: Royal Guest House
points_of_interest.description: Very cheap guesthouse within walking distance of Shepherd's Bush and Hammersmith. Triple rooms available.

points_of_interest.name: The Langham London
points_of_interest.description: Opened in 1865 as Europe's grand hotel, the Langham still retains its elegance and charm with luxuriously furnished rooms and spectacular views.

points_of_interest.name: Jurys Inn Chelsea Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Affordable hotel of one of the better hotel chains. All rooms are ensuite and large by London standards.

points_of_interest.name: The Montcalm London Marble Arch
points_of_interest.description: 120 bedrooms and suites with all marble bathrooms, a minute's walk from Hyde Park, Marble Arch and Oxford Street shopping.

points_of_interest.name: Novotel London West
points_of_interest.description: Very large business-class hotel. The rooms are reasonably priced with basic amenities in each room. Wireless internet available, or basic internet through the room's television. English breakfast available at extra charge. Restaurant/bar/lounge, massage center, concierge, cash machine, shoe shine machine, tourist information desk, porter, dry cleaning/ironing available, currency exchange, pets allowed with deposit.

points_of_interest.name: Amba Hotel
points_of_interest.address: Bryanston St, Marylebone, London W1H 7EH, UK

points_of_interest.name: Courthouse Hotel
points_of_interest.description: WorldHotels A Hilton hotel in a spectacular old building.

points_of_interest.name: Premier Inn
points_of_interest.description: In the extreme south of the district close to the Thames.

points_of_interest.name: London Croydon Aerodrome Hotel, BW Signature Collection
points_of_interest.description: Luxury hotel.

points_of_interest.name: Dorchester Hotel
points_of_interest.description: One of the most prestigious five-star luxury hotels anywhere in the world owned by the Brunei royal family. If you have to ask the rates, you probably can not afford to stay here.

points_of_interest.name: Hazlitt's
points_of_interest.description: A quirky hotel with 30 rooms in a knock-through of Georgian townhouses. Ever-so-boutique (translation: lots of awkward angles, and no lift to the upper floors). No bar or restaurant, breakfast is served in your room, but oodles of eating and sluicing places within a short stroll. No dogs.

points_of_interest.name: The Ville's B&B
points_of_interest.description: In the friendly area with fashionable restaurants, cafes, pubs and antique shops

points_of_interest.name: Holiday Inn Express London - Croydon
points_of_interest.description: Built in 2003, new and modern.

points_of_interest.name: Claridge's
points_of_interest.description: A London institution for those in the know. On the corner of Brook street and Davies street. Famous for serving traditional afternoon tea and hosts the Fera restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: The Soho Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Pizazzy boutique hotel with 91 rooms in a converted warehouse. With spa, gym, restaurant and bar.

points_of_interest.name: K-West
points_of_interest.description: Modern, fashionable hotel with a day spa.

points_of_interest.name: Leonardo Hotel
points_of_interest.description: formerly Jury's Inn Modern hotel.

points_of_interest.name: The Connaught Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Suites and rooms individually designed by Guy Oliver. Home to the restaurant of Hélène Darroze, a Michelin-starred French chef.

points_of_interest.name: Ham Yard Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Elegant relaxing Soho hotel, central yet peaceful.

points_of_interest.name: Lamington Serviced Apartments
points_of_interest.description: Luxury short term serviced apartments for business and leisure guests. Spacious and modern apartments in a quiet residential area, with local restaurants, delicatessens, and amenities, and in walking distance of major transport links.

points_of_interest.name: Premier Inn London Croydon (Purley A23)
points_of_interest.description: Hotel which offer warm and cosy rooms.
points_of_interest.address: The Colonnades Leisure Park, 619 Purley Way, CR0 4RQ

points_of_interest.name: Durrants
points_of_interest.description: Grand old hotel in a Georgian knock-through, occasional lapses on decor and service but usually scores. No dogs in rooms.

points_of_interest.name: St Paul's Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Stylish hotel in a former boys school of gothic red brick. Remarkably quiet for the location, great dining. No dogs.

points_of_interest.name: Premier Inn London Croydon South (A212)
points_of_interest.description: Hotel which offer warm and cosy rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Hyatt Regency London - The Churchill
points_of_interest.description: Five-star hotel with 444 rooms and suites. The hotel is host to Locanda Locatelli Michelin star Italian restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: LSE Vacations
points_of_interest.description: London School of Economics LSE offers residences to the general public during spring, summer, and winter student vacation periods. There are seven sites in central London.
points_of_interest.address: 2 St. Clement's Lane, Westminster, London, WC2A 2HA, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: Travelodge Croydon Central
points_of_interest.description: Cheap and modest.
points_of_interest.address: Norfolk House, Wellesley Rd, Croydon, CR0 1LH

points_of_interest.name: London Marriott Hotel Marble Arch
points_of_interest.description: Less expensive than some of the other hotels in the area. It is on a side street, so it is a little quieter. The rooms are reasonably sized, the beds have been upgraded. The hotel is in a district that has a lot of Middle Eastern shops and restaurants. People can be seen smoking hookahs in the cafes in the neighborhood. Very close to the shopping on Oxford St. Rooms have high speed internet at £15 per day.

points_of_interest.name: Swinton Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Good value bed and breakfast in the north west of the district.

points_of_interest.name: London Marriott Hotel Grosvenor Square
points_of_interest.description: In the heart of Mayfair, adjacent to Hyde Park and a stroll from Oxford St and Bond St. It was built as a large townhouse.

points_of_interest.name: The One Tun Pub & Rooms
points_of_interest.description: Smart pub with Thai cuisine and rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Park Lane Mews Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A luxury four-star hotel. Minutes walk to Knightsbridge, Oxford Street, Green Park, Buckingham Palace, Regents Street and Hyde Park. Combines the charm of a traditional boutique hotel with modern facilities.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Strand Contiental
points_of_interest.description: Excellently-located on south side of the Aldywch, straddling Westminster and the City. While it could be noisy at night and it appears small and grimy from the outside, there is a superb Indian restaurant on the 2nd floor.

points_of_interest.name: ibis London Docklands
points_of_interest.description: An economy London hotel in the Docklands area. The 87 guestrooms have a satellite TV and internet access. On site cafe. City Airport is 5 km from the hotel, and there is secure onsite parking for up to 30 cars.
points_of_interest.address: 1 Baffin Way off Preston Rd, E14 9PE

points_of_interest.name: The Mandeville Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Modern amenities including LCD flat-screen TV, iPod docking stations, and WiFi access.

points_of_interest.name: MiNC Eagle Court
points_of_interest.description: Studio, one and two bedroom service apartments. Very modern and nicely appointed.

points_of_interest.name: City Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A fairly average two-star hotel at typical London prices, however the rooms are clean and provide the basic facilities you need. The area isn't pretty but you are close to where all the action is. WiFi £5/day.

points_of_interest.name: Zetter Townhouse
points_of_interest.description: Dingbat hotel in former home of Edward Lear, the concept is that "Great Uncle Seymour" has filled the place with odd stuff from his grand European tour. (They have two other hotels in Clerkenwell.) Gets great reviews for comfort and service. Assistance dogs only.

points_of_interest.name: St Christopher's Inn
points_of_interest.description: A lively hostel - part of the popular chain - above the lively Belushi's bar (a student favourite). Right next to Greenwich station - providing quick links into central London. 6-12 bed mixed dorms, dedicated female dorm and private rooms available. Includes free WiFi, continental breakfast, a free walking tour of Greenwich and 25% off food and drink in the hostel bar.

points_of_interest.name: The Hoxton
points_of_interest.description: Lively modern hotel, some rooms are very small. They have another branch in Shoreditch.

points_of_interest.name: Travelodge London Docklands
points_of_interest.description: Affordbable for London. It is a modern branch of the ubiquitous budget hotel chain, but is well located almost next to ''East India'' DLR station, which has links directly to central London, and is just a few stops from Canary Wharf. Ask for a room on the front to avoid the busy road at the back.
points_of_interest.address: Coriander Avenue, Off East India Dock Road, E14 2AA

points_of_interest.name: Astor Museum Inn Hostel
points_of_interest.description: For 18-35 year-olds.

points_of_interest.name: Venture Hostel
points_of_interest.description: previously Journeys West Hostel Bright, modern and refurbished hostel above a lively pub - probably the cheapest price in the area. 3-12 bed mixed dorms, with dedicated female-only dorms available. Rate includes free WiFi and breakfast.

points_of_interest.name: Hart Shoreditch Hotel London, Curio Collection by Hilton
points_of_interest.description: 126 guest rooms, and event spaces for gatherings.

points_of_interest.name: Generator Hostels London
points_of_interest.description: Right in the heart of Bloomsbury. Communal showers and cold water, all-night parties and generally an architecture obviously designed exclusively with the easy clean-up of bodily fluids in mind. It is cheap, though, in London terms.

points_of_interest.name: De Vere Devonport House
points_of_interest.description: This Georgian-style hotel has 93 rooms all in a grand old converted building. Located right at the Maritime World Heritage site. Specialises in hosting corporate functions and seminars but the accommodation for casual visitors offers decent value.

points_of_interest.name: Rosewood Chancery Court London
points_of_interest.description: Try this hotel for a very upscale experience. It is in an older building that has been beautifully renovated (formerly HQ of Pearl Assurance). There is high-speed internet, but the charge is £15 per day. The hotel is air-conditioned. The staff is very helpful. A great experience, if you can pay the rates.

points_of_interest.name: Britannia International
points_of_interest.description: Extremely modern three star hotel.

points_of_interest.name: YHA London Central
points_of_interest.description: London Central Youth Hostel The newest of the five London YHA hostels, with state-of-the-art interiors, and a short walk from Regent's Park.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Ibis Greenwich
points_of_interest.description: A typical, rather identikit Ibis hotel. Not expensive by any means though.

points_of_interest.name: St Christopher's Village
points_of_interest.description: Youth hostel with late night bar.

points_of_interest.name: The Montcalm Royal London House
points_of_interest.description: Spa hotel with spectacular rooftop bar-restaurant offering view over the skyline. Comfy rooms with all mod cons. Professional, unobtrusive staff.

points_of_interest.name: Limehouse Serviced Apartments
points_of_interest.address: 2 John Nash Mews, Tower Hamlets, London, E14 7GQ, United Kingdom

points_of_interest.name: The Pilot Inn
points_of_interest.description: This 200-year-old Fullers pub has five bedrooms upstairs at reasonable rates.

points_of_interest.name: The Rookery
points_of_interest.description: Groaning with antiques, an atmosphere that more recalls a private gentleman's club than a hotel. No dogs.

points_of_interest.name: The Hoxton
points_of_interest.description: Chic buzzing hotel in Shoreditch. Assistance dogs only.

points_of_interest.name: UCL Summer Residences
points_of_interest.description: University College London Student halls of residence which are made available for rental during academic holiday periods.

points_of_interest.name: Premier Inn
points_of_interest.description: Popular mid-range chain - close to Greenwich station with easy access into central London.

points_of_interest.name: Express by Holiday Inn London Southwark
points_of_interest.description: On the River Thames, clean and charming hotel.

points_of_interest.name: The Zetter Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Business hotel in a Victorian warehouse, good restaurant. Stylish but sensible (for something wacky, try their townhouses adjacent and in Marylebone). Assistance dogs only.
points_of_interest.address: St John's Square, 86 Clerkenwell Rd EC1M 5RJ

points_of_interest.name: Canary Riverside Plaza
points_of_interest.description: Four Seasons Hotel Canary Wharf Five-star hotel and the most upmarket hotel in the area with views across the Thames or Canary Wharf, offering the kind of 5 star luxury to be expected from this chain.

points_of_interest.name: Alhambra Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Well-known multi-lingual (Spanish, Portuguese, French) family hotel. Free wireless Internet.

points_of_interest.name: Novotel
points_of_interest.description: Four-star chain hotel with stylish rooms. Next to Greenwich station, providing easy access into central London.

points_of_interest.name: Novotel London City South
points_of_interest.description: Great views along with a fitness gym and spa.

points_of_interest.name: Zetter Townhouse Clerkenwell
points_of_interest.description: Offbeat hotel, the concept is that it's the home of dingbat "Great Aunt Wilhelmina". Gets good reviews for comfort and service, and it looks like the old lady could knock a few back - the splendid cocktail bar is open W-Sa 12:00-23:00, reckon £12 a snort. (Their similar townhouse in Marylebone is styled for "Great Uncle Seymour"). Assistance dogs only.

points_of_interest.name: Hilton Docklands
points_of_interest.description: On the South bank of the River Thames, the hotel has a great view of Canary Wharf.

points_of_interest.name: The Apollo Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Clean, but staff somewhat unhelpful. WiFi Internet.

points_of_interest.name: Onesixtwo
points_of_interest.description: Boutique guest house with stylish and modern rooms in between Blackheath and Greenwich. Out of the way and not as close to public transport as other hotels, but located in a very relaxed area away from the tourist centre of Greenwich. Free WiFi and continental breakfast.

points_of_interest.name: ibis Styles London Southwark
points_of_interest.description: A boutique hotel less than 200 metres from the Thames. Air conditioned rooms with en suites, meeting room facilities.

points_of_interest.name: Marriott Executive Apartments London, Canary Wharf
points_of_interest.description: Looking out over Canary Wharf's beautiful district, the Marriott combines elegance and comfort to create a welcoming environment.

points_of_interest.name: Excelsior Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Budget hotel in a quiet, leafy square close to King's Cross Station. All rooms have high speed internet connection.

points_of_interest.name: Clarendon Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Three-star hotel in a lovely old converted Georgian building on Blackheath Green. Price includes a full breakfast and free WiFi.

points_of_interest.name: H10 London Waterloo
points_of_interest.description: Boxy modern building by St George's Circus, stylish, good value and well insulated against street noise. Assistance dogs only.

points_of_interest.name: Batty Langley's
points_of_interest.description: Gorgeous small hotel in two Georgian buildings. Assistance dogs only.

points_of_interest.name: Guilford House Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A little shabby but well-located and fair value.

points_of_interest.name: The Mitre
points_of_interest.description: This historic pub in the heart of Greenwich has 14 guest rooms upstairs. Free WiFi and continental buffet breakfast.

points_of_interest.name: CitizenM London Bankside
points_of_interest.description: Slick modern hotel, part of Dutch chain. No dogs.

points_of_interest.name: The Jesmond Dene Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A budget hotel run on a bed & breakfast basis. Free WiFi Internet access.

points_of_interest.name: London Bridge Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Four-star boutique hotel popular with business travellers with its sleek and contemporary design and furnishings.

points_of_interest.name: The Fielding
points_of_interest.description: Great little hotel between Bow St and Drury Lane. No breakfast or other meals, but lots nearby. No dogs.

points_of_interest.name: Marriott London County Hall
points_of_interest.description: With Big Ben checking on you across the street, it's home to the largest pool in any London hotel. Provides first class service, luxurious spa treatment on site and trendy bar downstairs.

points_of_interest.name: Strand Palace Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Good value hotel in a convenient location for Covent Garden theatres and shopping.

points_of_interest.name: Euston Square Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Completely renovated in 2008.

points_of_interest.name: Park Plaza County Hall
points_of_interest.description: Stylish and reputable.

points_of_interest.name: Travelodge London Covent Garden
points_of_interest.description: Popular hotel with visitors and decent value for the area. Convenient for Covent Garden theatres and shopping.

points_of_interest.name: Bermondsey Square Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Slick modern hotel with good daytime restaurant. No alcohol.

points_of_interest.name: The Savoy
points_of_interest.description: The famed Savoy offers magnificent views of the river Thames. It opened in 1889 as Britain's first luxury hotel and remains a popular destination in London. The hotel has 263 rooms and suites, a nifty blend of elegance and contemporary design. Inventive cuisine can be enjoyed in the Savoy Grill and the more informal Banquette.

points_of_interest.name: George Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Historic building, full English breakfast.

points_of_interest.name: St Martins Lane
points_of_interest.description: Ian Schrager (of Studio 54 fame) is known worldwide for being an innovator in the ‘hip’ hotel business. His first foray into London, St Martins Lane, is a playful and urbane destination in the West End theatre district off Trafalgar Square that combines urban cool and modern design (via design guru Philippe Starck). Unique features of this trendy-meets-luxury hotel include the Asia de Cuba restaurant, the popular Light Bar and interactive light displays in every guest room that encourages guests to personalise their own individual space.

Not a cheap hotel by any means but good value for the location and standard. Popular with families. See the magnificent ballroom which was designed by the same people who created interiors for RMS Titanic.

points_of_interest.name: Sanderson Hotel

points_of_interest.name: Lime Tree Hotel

points_of_interest.name: SACO Apartments – Aldgate

points_of_interest.name: Ambassadors Hotel

If you cannot afford to stay here (likely), then a splurge on afternoon tea in the opulent Louis XIV Palm Court is recommended (£54-£90). Dress appropriately - a jacket and tie for gentlemen; smart attire and proper shoes for everyone - otherwise you will not get past the door.

The hotel is not nice, but OK. The breakfast is uninteresting, except the coffee, which is awful! But, the tea and the juice are good. It is close to many pubs, cafés and shops. Good place to stay, but lots of traffic.

points_of_interest.name: Richmond Harbour Hotel & Spa
points_of_interest.description: Georgian Hotel.

The rooms are nicer than many of the double rooms in the hostels along Earls Court Rd, for much the same price, although there is no wi-fi internet.

There is a TV lounge, a 24-hour concierge, and the staff is friendly and helpful. It is clean and the shared bathrooms are not bad at all.

points_of_interest.name: The Kew Gardens Hotel

points_of_interest.name: Merlyn Court Hotel

points_of_interest.name: Hyde Park Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Mandarin Oriental Hyde Park London

points_of_interest.name: Number Sixteen
points_of_interest.description: Victorian mansion with gorgeous stylish interior. Afternoon tea in the Orangery is a treat. No dogs.

points_of_interest.name: The Park Tower Knightsbridge Hotel
